u|year=2007|publisher=T. Krishna Press |location=Chennai |isbn=81-7478-177-3|ref=tourist}}\n* {{cite book |last=V.|first=Vriddhagirisan|authorlink= |title=Nayaks of Tanjore |year=1995 |publisher=Asian Educational Services |location=New Delhi |isbn=81-206-0996-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GD_6ka-aYuQC&pg=PA120&dq=tiruvidaimarudur&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nP8MT7WAIZCztwfCxYHTDQ&ved=0CGYQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=tiruvidaimarudur&f=false|ref=V.}}\n*{{cite book |last=Vasudevan|first=Geetha |authorlink= |title=The royal temple of Rajaraja: an instrument of imperial Cola power|year=2003|publisher=Abhinav Publications |location=New Delhi |isbn=81-7017-383-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1b1N_Dx0jsC&pg=RA1-PA116&dq=tiruvidaimarudur&hl=en&sa=X&ei=RwQNT5PgEJTatwfW7N3IBQ&ved=0CFUQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=tiruvidaimarudur&f=false|ref=Vasudevan}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mahalingeswarar Temple, Thiruvidaimarudur}}\n\n{{Famous Shiva temples}}\n{{Hindu Temples of Kumbakonam}}\n\n==Photogallery==\n<gallery>\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple1.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple3.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple4.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple2.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple9.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple7.jpg\nFile: Tiruvidaimaruthurtemple6.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Thanjavur district]]\n[[Category:Padal Petra Stalam]]\n", "name_user": "Ssriram mt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Kasi\u2192Varanasi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahalingeswarar_Temple,_Thiruvidaimarudur"}
{"title_page": "Scientific Time Sharing Corporation", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Scientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC)\n| logo = \n| type = {{Unbulleted list |[[Privately held company|Private]] 1969-1993 |[[Public company|Public]] 1993-2006}}\n| industry = [[Software]], services, applications\n| fate = Acquired by [[JDA Software]] Group, July 2006\n| predecessor = \n| successor = {{Unbulleted list |STSC, Inc. |[[Manugistics]] Group, Inc.}}\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1969}}<!-- After year, if known, add correct |MM|DD --> in [[Bethesda, Maryland|Bethesda]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]] ''(as STSC)''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jda.com/manugistics/history.html |title=JDA Software Group Inc., demand chain management software and services for global retailers, wholesalers and manufacturers |publisher=JDA Software |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103214751/http://jda.com/manugistics/history.html |archivedate=2010-01-03 }}</ref>\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list |Dan Dyer, |[[Burton C. Gray]], |[[Philip S. Abrams]], |[[Lawrence M. Breed]] |Allen J. Rose}}\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Rockville, Maryland|Rockville]], [[Maryland]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations = 30 offices\n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = {{Unbulleted list |[[North America]] |[[Europe]]}}\n| key_people = \n| products = Prepackaged software<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allbusiness.com/companyprofile/Manugistics_Group_Inc/B147AAA3EDBE7BD7BCFFC11A0B53E048-1.html |title=Manugistics Group Inc \u2013 Technology > Software Services & Applications from AllBusiness.com |publisher=AllBusiness}}</ref>\n| brands = APL*Plus\n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data, if known -->\n| services = \n| revenue = <!-- US$ -->\n| revenue_year = \n| owner = Continental Telecom, Inc.\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = \n| parent = Continental Telecom, Inc.\n| website = {{URL|jda.com/industries/distribution-and-logistics}}<!-- Web domain www.manugistics.com is for sale. Do not use. -->\n}}\n\n'''Scientific Time Sharing Corporation''' ('''STSC''') was a pioneering timesharing and consulting service company which offered [[APL (programming language)|APL]] from its datacenter in Bethesda, MD to users in the United States and Europe.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Embassy of Moldova (Washington, D.C.).JPG|thumb|Scientific Time Sharing Corporation's former headquarters in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]\nScientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC) was formed in 1969 in [[Bethesda, Maryland]] by Dan Dyer, [[Burton C. Gray]], and some of the people who originally implemented the programming language [[APL (programming language)|APL]], notably [[Philip S. Abrams]], [[Lawrence M. Breed]], and Allen Rose.<ref>[http://alumninet.yale.edu/classes/yc1962/obituaries/grayb.html Burton C. Gray's Yale obituary]</ref>  In 1970, STSC released ''APL*Plus'', a version of the ''APL\\360'' language with many practical extensions oriented toward fostering business use of APL. Together with [[I. P. Sharp Associates]], STSC made many enhancements to the APL language, including:\n* []FMT formatting\n* []VR and []FX, APL program [[Reflection (computer programming)|reflection]] features\n* a file system to store APL variables outside of the APL environment\n \nSTSC continued to make enhancements to the [[Interpreter (computing)|interpreter]], notably improving the performance of many of the primitive [[Subroutine|function]]s.\n\nIn 1985, Dan Dyer of STSC and Ian Sharp of [[I. P. Sharp Associates]] jointly received the ''Kenneth E. [[Iverson Award]] for Outstanding Contribution to APL''.\n\nIn the early 1980s, the timesharing market began collapsing, mostly due to the appearance in the marketplace of relatively lower cost IBM [[mainframe computer]]s, such as the [[IBM 4300]]. STSC quickly changed its focus to supply APL services for in-house and the rapidly developing [[personal computer]] (PC) market.\n\nIn 1982, STSC released ''APL*Plus/PC'', which was a very successful APL [[Interpreter (computing)|interpreter]] for the IBM personal computer. In the mid 1980s, STSC developed the ''APL*Plus/Unix'' interpreter, a full 32-bit interpreter which was the basis of further APL development, notably ''APL*Plus/386'', which was later available for [[Intel 386]] class machines and higher. Arguably, the ''APL*Plus/386'' interpreter fostered the exodus of APL applications from mainframe to PC environments, as the hardware and software were finally correctly matched to facilitate a straightforward migration of medium- to large-sized applications away from mainframes.\n\nIn the mid 1980s, STSC released an APL [[compiler]] for its APL*Plus add-on for the IBM VSAPL [[License Program Product]]. Along with language features designed to profile code execution, this compiler implementation was oriented toward replacing resource-consuming functions in place with compiled ones, leading to overall performance improvements.\n\nBy the mid 1990s, the ''APL*Plus/386'' system had become one of the leading APL interpreters in the market, however it did not run under the then-new [[Microsoft Windows 3.1]]. Although there were some attempts at Windows interoperability, development on the ''APL*Plus/Win'' product began shortly before the APL products were sold to ''LEX2000''. This latest Windows product is the basis for the current ''APLNow'' (formerly ''APL2000'') interpreter product line.\n\n==Timeline==\n* 1969 \u2013 Scientific Time Sharing Corporation formed\n* 1972 \u2013 APL Mailbox, an early email system by [[Lawrence M. Breed|Larry Breed]]<ref>[http://www.jsoftware.com/papers/APLQA.htm APL Quotations and Anecdotes], including Leslie Goldsmith's story of the Mailbox</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.actewagl.com.au/Education/communications/Internet/historyOfTheInternet/InternetOnItsInfancy.aspx |title=Home > Communications > The Internet > History of the internet > Internet in its infancy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227151622/http://www.actewagl.com.au/Education/communications/Internet/historyOfTheInternet/InternetOnItsInfancy.aspx |archive-date=2011-02-27 |work=actewagl.com.au |access-date=2016-11-03}}</ref>\n* 1976 \u2013 STSC Mailbox used to coordinate the [[Jimmy Carter]] presidential campaign\n* 1979 \u2013 the firm name was changed to ''STSC, Inc.''\n* 1982 \u2013 APL*Plus/PC launched, one of the first versions of APL on the [[personal computer]]\n* 1982 \u2013 acquired by Continental Telecom, Inc.\n* 1992 \u2013 name changed to [[Manugistics]] Group, Inc.\n* 1993 \u2013 [[initial public offering]]\n* 1995 \u2013 the APL product line was sold to ''LEX2000, Inc.''\n* 1999 \u2013 [[Cognos]] Corporation acquired LEX2000\n\n[[Manugistics]] continued to own all supply chain software.\n\n== See also==\n* [[Kenneth E. Iverson|Kenneth Iverson]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.thocp.net/software/languages/apl.htm APL programming language - Chronology]\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mjgkhK-nXmk |title=The STSC Story: It's About Time |date=c. 1979 |editor=[http://lathwellproductions.ca Catherine Lathwell] |publisher=Scientific Time Sharing Corporation |access-date=2017-01-06 }} Promotional video for Scientific Time Sharing Corporation, which features President [[Jimmy Carter]]'s press secretary [[Jody Powell]] explaining how the company's ''APL Mailbox'' enabled the 1976 Carter presidential campaign to easily move information around the country to coordinate the campaign.  Plus many employees and corporate customers explaining how STSC's APL helped them solve business problems.\n\n{{APL programming language}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Maryland]]\n[[Category:APL programming language family]]\n[[Category:Time-sharing companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Scientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC)\n| logo = \n| type = {{Unbulleted list |[[Privately held company|Private]] 1969-1993 |[[Public company|Public]] 1993-2006}}\n| industry = [[Software]], services, applications\n| fate = Acquired by [[JDA Software]] Group, July 2006\n| predecessor = \n| successor = {{Unbulleted list |STSC, Inc. |[[Manugistics]] Group, Inc.}}\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1969}}<!-- After year, if known, add correct |MM|DD --> in [[Bethesda, Maryland|Bethesda]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]] ''(as STSC)''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jda.com/manugistics/history.html |title=JDA Software Group Inc., demand chain management software and services for global retailers, wholesalers and manufacturers |publisher=JDA Software |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103214751/http://jda.com/manugistics/history.html |archivedate=2010-01-03 }}</ref>\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list |Dan Dyer, |[[Burton C. Gray]], |[[Philip S. Abrams]], |[[Lawrence M. Breed]] |Allen J. Rose}}\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = [[Rockville, Maryland|Rockville]], [[Maryland]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations = 30 offices\n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = {{Unbulleted list |[[North America]] |[[Europe]]}}\n| key_people = \n| products = Prepackaged software<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allbusiness.com/companyprofile/Manugistics_Group_Inc/B147AAA3EDBE7BD7BCFFC11A0B53E048-1.html |title=Manugistics Group Inc \u2013 Technology > Software Services & Applications from AllBusiness.com |publisher=AllBusiness}}</ref>\n| brands = APL*Plus\n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data, if known -->\n| services = \n| revenue = <!-- US$ -->\n| revenue_year = \n| owner = Continental Telecom, Inc.\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = \n| parent = Continental Telecom, Inc.\n| website = {{URL|jda.com/industries/distribution-and-logistics