{"title_page": "George Gasc\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = George Gasc\u00f3n\n|image        = Chief George Gascon SFPD.jpg\n|office       = 28th [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office|District Attorney of San Francisco]]\n|term_start   = January 9, 2011\n|term_end     = October 19, 2019\n|predecessor  = [[Kamala Harris]]\n|successor    = [[Suzy Loftus]] (interim)\n|office1      = Chief of the [[San Francisco Police Department]]\n|term_start1  = January 8, 2010\n|term_end1    = January 9, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Heather Fong]]\n|successor1   = Greg Suhr\n|birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1954}}\n|birth_place  = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] \n|spouse       = Fabiola Kramsky\n|education    = [[California State University, Long Beach]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Western State College of Law at Argosy University|Western State University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''George Gasc\u00f3n''' (born March 12, 1954) is an American attorney who served as the [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office|District Attorney of San Francisco]] from 2011 to 2019. George Gasc\u00f3n previously served as an Assistant Chief of Police for the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]], and Chief of Police in [[Mesa, Arizona]] and [[San Francisco Police Department|San Francisco]].\n\nGasc\u00f3n was born in Havana, Cuba. In 1967, his family immigrated to the United States and settled in [[Bell, California]]. He joined the [[United States Army]] at the age of eighteen and became a sergeant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://laist.com/2019/10/28/lapd-george-gascon-los-angeles-district-attorney-da-jackie-lacey.php|title=George Gascon Has Said 'We Need To Turn Our Court System Upside Down.' Now He's Running To Be LA's Next DA|last=Stoltze|first=Frank|website=LAist|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> After earning a bachelor of arts in history from [[California State-Long Beach]], Gasc\u00f3n joined the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] as a patrol officer.      \n\nDuring his tenure with the Los Angeles Police Department, he attained the rank of Assistant Chief of Police under Chief [[William Bratton]]. In 2006, Gasc\u00f3n was appointed as Chief of Police for the [[Mesa Police Department (Arizona)|Mesa Police Department]]. He had frequent clashes with [[Maricopa County Sheriff's Office|Maricopa County Sheriff]] [[Joe Arpaio]] over immigration sweeps targeting Latinos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/mesa-police-chief-george-gascn-stares-down-sheriff-joe-arpaio-6426648|title=Mesa Police Chief George Gasc\u00f3n stares down Sheriff Joe Arpaio|last=Stern|first=Ray|date=2008-07-10|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 2009, then-Mayor [[Gavin Newsom]] appointed Gasc\u00f3n as the Chief of Police for the [[San Francisco Police Department]]. In 2011, after [[Kamala Harris]] was elected [[California Attorney General]], Newsom appointed Gasc\u00f3n to be the San Francisco District Attorney. In 2019, Gasc\u00f3n announced he was running to be the District Attorney for Los Angeles County.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web |last1=Arango |first1=Tim |title=George Gascon Enters Race for District Attorney in Los Angeles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/28/us/george-gacon-district-attorney-los-angeles.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=9 February 2020 |date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life & Education ==\n\nIn 1954, Gasc\u00f3n was born in pre-communist [[Cuba]]. Shortly after the communist revolution in Cuba, Gasc\u00f3n's father lost his job for alleged anti-government activity, and his uncle, a union organizer, was jailed for over a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfweekly.com/news/beyond-the-law-district-attorney-george-gascons-threat-to-san-franciscos-business-as-usual/|title=Beyond the Law: District Attorney George Gasc\u00f3n's threat to San Francisco's business as usual|date=2016-06-09|website=SF Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 1967, Gasc\u00f3n and his family immigrated from Cuba to the United States. \n\nThe Gasc\u00f3n family settled in [[Bell, California]], a suburb of [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2020/02/20/george-gascon-running-to-unseat-jackie-lacey/|title=George Gasc\u00f3n running to unseat Jackie Lacey|date=2020-02-20|website=Los Angeles Blade:  LGBT News, Rights, Politics, Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> At the age of thirteen, Gasc\u00f3n enrolled in [[Los Angeles Unified School District]] schools where he struggled to learn english. He recalled: \"I was spending hours translating everything with a Spanish-English dictionary. I started missing a lot of school.\"<ref name=sfgate>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/nevius/article/George-Gasc-n-From-high-school-dropout-to-DA-2446643.php|title=George Gasc\u00f3n: From high school dropout to DA|last=Nevius|first=C. W.|date=2012-01-07|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> By 1972, he dropped out of [[Bell High School (Bell, California)|Bell High School]].<ref name=sfgate/> \n\nGasc\u00f3n joined the [[United States Army]] in 1972. In the army, he earned his high school diploma and two years toward an undergraduate degree.<ref name=military>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-jun-04-me-onthelaw4-story.html|title=He Said No to Naysayers|date=2004-06-04|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Gasc\u00f3n served in the 64th Military Police Detachment, much of it in Germany.<ref name=military/> In 1975, he received an honorable discharge as a sergeant.<ref name=military/> After the Army, Gasc\u00f3n completed a bachelor of arts in history from [[California State-Long Beach]] while working sales jobs.<ref name=military/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Los Angeles Police Department ===\nIn 1978, Gasc\u00f3n joined the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] as a patrol officer.<ref name=military/> After a three-year stint with the LAPD, he returned to work in business management.<ref name=military/> He served as a reserve officer in the Hollenbeck Division of LAPD until 1987.<ref name=military/> In 1987, he returned to LAPD as a full-time police officer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rivera |first1=Carla |title=San Francisco Police Chief George Gascon named district attorney |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2011-jan-10-la-me-gascon-da-20110110-story.html |website=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=9 February 2020 |date=10 January 2011}}</ref> Upon his return, he rose through the ranks of LAPD as a Sergeant, Lieutenant, Captain, Commander, and Deputy Chief in 2002.<ref name=lapd>{{Cite web|url=http://lapdonline.org/february_2003/news_view/21584|title=Two New Assistant Chiefs to be Sworn In at Police Commission Meeting - Los Angeles Police Department|website=lapdonline.org|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\n====Training Commander after Rampart Scandal====\nIn 2000, he took command of the LAPD training unit at the height of the [[Rampart Scandal]].<ref name=military/> He was in command of the LAPD training unit, overseeing the LAPD Academy and in-service training, during the federal government's oversight of police reforms. Even though there was a mandate for reform, then-Police Chief [[Bernard Parks]] did not allocate funding for additional training.<ref name=weekly/> Gasc\u00f3n utilized a grant that had originally been funded to research community-policing strategies, and produced three hundred thousand additional training hours.<ref name=weekly/>\n\nOne of his first orders as training commander was to create an ethics training manual for the LAPD.<ref name=weekly>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/rewriting-the-book/|title=Rewriting the Book|last=Fremon|first=Celeste|date=2002-09-04|website=LA Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> He also implemented problem-based learning and posted a copy of the bill of rights in every LAPD classroom. Michael Gennaco, the former head of the [[United States Justice Department]]'s civil rights division said at the time: \u201cHe fundamentally changed the way the LAPD teaches its officers about civil rights.\u201d<ref name=military/>\n\nIn 2002, Gasc\u00f3n applied to be the Los Angeles Police Department Chief of Police. He wanted to partner with community agencies to reduce California's prisoner-recidivism rate.<ref name=weekly/> [[William Bratton]] was ultimately appointed Chief of Police.\n\n====Assistant Chief of Police====\nIn 2003, he was sworn in as Assistant Chief of the Los Angeles Police Department under Chief [[William Bratton]].<ref name=lapd/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lacp.org/Articles%20-%20Main/ChiefPicksThree.html|title=Chief Bratton Makes Three Great Picks ... LA Community Policing|website=www.lacp.org|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 2004, Gasc\u00f3n oversaw the daily operations of the department.<ref name=military/>\n\n=== Mesa Chief of Police ===\nGasc\u00f3n served as chief of the [[Mesa, Arizona]] police department from 2006 to 2009.<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Mayor-picks-Arizona-chief-as-S-F-top-cop-3295093.php Mayor Picks Arizona Chief] Retrieved April 24, 2018</ref>\n\n=== San Francisco Chief of Police ===\nGasc\u00f3n served as [[San Francisco Police Department]] chief from August 2009 to January 2011, succeeding [[Heather Fong]]. He was replaced by [[Greg Suhr]].<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/From-high-school-dropout-to-police-chief-to-DA-s-4705542.php From High School Dropout to Police Chief] Referenced October 9th, 2019</ref> In 2009, San Francisco saw a significant drop in homicides, falling from 96 in 2008 to 45 in 2009. Between 2009 and 2011, violent crime decreased in San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/S-F-cops-Homicide-up-overall-violent-crime-down-2479732.php|title=S.F. cops: Homicide up, overall violent crime down|last=Berton|first=Justin|date=2011-01-02|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco District Attorney===\nIn 2011, in his last act as Mayor of San Francisco, [[Gavin Newsom]] appointed Gasc\u00f3n as San Francisco District Attorney, filling the seat vacated by [[Kamala Harris]]. In 2018, Gasc\u00f3n announced that he would not be seeking re-election, citing his need to care for his mother in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7news.com/4395553/|title=San Francisco District Attorney George Gascon will not seek reelection|last=KGO|date=2018-10-03|website=ABC7 San Francisco|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> He resigned from his San Francisco District Attorney position in October 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lagos |first1=Marisa |title=San Francisco District Attorney George Gascon Resigns |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11778096/san-francisco-district-attorney-george-gascon-resigns |accessdate=4 October 2019 |publisher=KQED |date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Bail reform====\nGasc\u00f3n advocated for the end of monetary bail.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/State-must-make-cash-bail-system-just-and-protect-12842585.php State must make cash bail system just and protect public safety] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> Gasc\u00f3n brought the Public Safety Assessment (\u201cPSA\u201d) tool to San Francisco to assist courts in making bail decisions more equitably. Initial results indicate that, compared to defendants released by the PSA, double the percentage of defendants were arrested while they were out on bail or their own recognizance.<ref>[https://www.kqed.org/news/11619469/bail-or-jail-tool-used-by-san-francisco-courts-shows-promising-results Bail or Jail? Tool Used by San Francisco Courts Shows Promising Results] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\n====Drug policy====\nIn 2018, Gasc\u00f3n announced that he would apply California's [[Adult Use of Marijuana Act]] retroactively to every marijuana case since 1975 in order to level the playing field for those adversely affected by the criminalization of marijuana. The move cleared misdemeanor convictions and reduced felony convictions for those entitled for record relief under the act.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2019/02/26/698045482/san-francisco-to-expunge-thousands-of-marijuana-convictions San Francisco To Expunge Thousands Of Marijuana Convictions] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> He partnered with [[Code for America]], a 501(c)3 non-profit organization, which kicked off a national movement resulting in dozens of cities across the country clearing marijuana convictions.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/SF-district-attorney-wipes-out-9-000-plus-13643128.php SF district attorney to wipe out 9,000-plus pot cases going back to 1975] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\nGasc\u00f3n supports ending the war on drugs. Prop 47, which was co-authored by Gasc\u00f3n, reduced simple drug possession from a felony to a misdemeanor in California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/article/Prop-47-is-necessary-to-put-the-war-on-drugs-13413035.php|title=Prop. 47 is necessary to put war on drugs behind us|date=2018-11-23|website=SFChronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n====Data management system====\nGasc\u00f3n implemented and launched the California's first prosecutorial data management system, similar to [[CompStat]], called DA Stat.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/SF-DA-Gasc-n-launches-state-s-first-website-13904234.php SF DA Gasc\u00f3n launches state's first website showing prosecution data] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>  This internal data collection tool is part of a trend toward \"data-driven prosecution.\"\n\n====Investigations of police officers====\nGasc\u00f3n launched a Blue Ribbon Panel<ref>[http://sfdistrictattorney.org/sites/default/files/Document/BRP_report_0.pdf Blue Ribbon Panel] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> to investigate a scandal in the San Francisco Police Department regarding homophobic and racist texts exchanged between over 14 police officers in 2014.<ref>[https://abc7news.com/news/sf-cops-accused-of-exchanging-racist-text-messages/1271363/ San Francisco cops accused of exchanging racist text messages] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2016, following recommendations of both the Department of Justice and Blue Ribbon Panel, Gasc\u00f3n secured funding to create the Independent Investigations Bureau, which investigates shootings involving police officers, excessive force, and in-custody deaths.<ref>[https://missionlocal.org/2019/06/the-san-francisco-district-attorney-is-now-the-lead-investigator-in-the-event-of-a-police-shooting/ The San Francisco District Attorney is now the lead investigator of police shootings] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles County District Attorney Race===\nIn 2019, Gasc\u00f3n announced he was running to be the District Attorney for Los Angeles County.<ref name=nyt/> The [[Los Angeles Police Protective League]] contributed one million dollars to defeat Gasc\u00f3n.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theappeal.org/george-gascon-los-angeles-police-union/|title=LA Police Union Contributes $1 Million To Anti-George Gasc\u00f3n PAC|website=The Appeal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Policy positions==\n===Large-Capacity Magazines===\nIn 2013, Gasc\u00f3n wrote an op-ed in support of the ban of large capacity gun magazines (devices that hold more than ten bullets). He cited, among other things, the large number of mass shootings in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/turn-gun-control-attack-toward-large-magazines-86023.html|title=Time to ban large gun clips|last=Gasc\u00f3n|first=George|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nGasc\u00f3n coauthored Senate Bill 962, legislation requiring a \u201ckill switch\u201d on all smartphones sold in California.<ref>[http://www.sfweekly.com/news/snitch/people-are-such-jerks-sometimes/cell-phone-thefts-decrease-in-s-f/ Cell Phone Thefts Decrease in S.F.] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref> \n\nGasc\u00f3n co-authored Proposition 47 that reduced many crimes from felonies to misdemeanors. Proposition 47, according to one study, has reduced the disparity in arrests in San Francisco between Caucasians and African Americans by nearly half.<ref>[https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/article213694224.html Research finds Prop. 47 has reduced racial disparities in drug arrests] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>  Some have criticized the law.<ref>Los Angeles Times[https://www.latimes.com/local/politics/la-me-cap-proposition47-20150226-column.html] \"Movement builds to correct major flaw in Prop. 47\"</ref><ref>California Globe[https://californiaglobe.com/section-2/how-prop-47-fueled-the-homeless-epidemic/] \"How Prop. 47 Fueled the Homeless Epidemic\"</ref><ref>San Diego Union Tribune [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/editorials/story/2019-12-04/california-car-burglaries-doors-locked-loophole?_amp=true] \u201cCriminal justice reform is a great cause. Defending a bad law isn\u2019t.\u201c</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* \"New Training Program Helps LAPD Meet Training Mandates,\" ''Police Chief'', November 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=192753|title=NCJRS Abstract - National Criminal Justice Reference Service|website=www.ncjrs.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Visionary Award (2017), Southern California Leadership Network<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lachamber.com/news/2017/101/press-release/southern-california-leadership-network-celebrates-30th-anniversary-by-recognizing-30-outstanding-leaders-during-2017-visionaries-awards/|title=Southern California Leadership Network Celebrates 30th Anniversary by Recognizing 30 Outstanding Leaders During 2017 Visionaries Awards|website=lachamber.com|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n* Top 100 Lawyers in California by the Daily Journal,<ref>[https://blog.sfbar.org/2017/10/24/basf-bulletin-board-our-members-and-leaders-circle-firms-making-headlines-24/, BASF Bulletin Board: Our Members and Leaders Circle Firms Making Headlines] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>\n* Anti-Defamation League's Civil Rights Award.<ref>[https://sanfrancisco.adl.org/event/adl-awards-luncheon-honoring-michael-rubin-and-george-gascon/ ADL Awards Luncheon Event] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn March 2010, Gasc\u00f3n made remarks about San Francisco's susceptibility to terrorism by the \"[[Middle Eastern]] community\" that upset [[Arab-Americans]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sfist.com/2010/03/26/police_chief_gascon_angers_middle_e.php | title=Police Chief Gasc\u00f3n Angers Middle Eastern and Arab Community | publisher=SFist | date=26 March 2010 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Keeling, Brock | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516210853/http://sfist.com/2010/03/26/police_chief_gascon_angers_middle_e.php | archivedate=16 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Police-chief-s-remarks-on-terrorism-anger-Arabs-3195205.php | title=Police chief's remarks on terrorism anger Arabs | publisher=SF Gate | date=26 March 2010 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Knight, Heather}}</ref> Several San Francisco police officers accused Gasc\u00f3n of calling [[African-Americans]] \"those people\" in \"a derogatory way.\" Gasc\u00f3n denied making those remarks.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/D-A-Gasc-n-s-divide-with-law-enforcement-6880747.php | title=SF D.A. Gasc\u00f3n\u2019s divide with law enforcement deepens | publisher=San Francisco Chronicle | date=9 March 2016 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Ho, Vivian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/video/category/news-politics/3368209-sf-police-union-officials-claim-da-gascon-made-racist-remarks-at-drunken-party/ | title=SF Police Union Officials Claim DA Gascon Made Racist Remarks At Drunken Party | publisher=CBS SF Bay Area | date=2 March 2016 | accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lapdonline.org/lapd_command_staff/comm_bio_view/7608 LAPD Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gascon, George}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:California State University, Long Beach alumni]]\n[[Category:Cuban emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:District attorneys in California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Police Department officers]]\n[[Category:People from Havana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Police Department chiefs]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American politicians]]\n[[Category:American police chiefs]]\n[[Category:American law enforcement officials]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = George Gasc\u00f3n\n|image        = Chief George Gascon SFPD.jpg\n|office       = 28th [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office|District Attorney of San Francisco]]\n|term_start   = January 9, 2011\n|term_end     = October 19, 2019\n|predecessor  = [[Kamala Harris]]\n|successor    = [[Suzy Loftus]] (interim)\n|office1      = Chief of the [[San Francisco Police Department]]\n|term_start1  = January 8, 2010\n|term_end1    = January 9, 2011\n|predecessor1 = [[Heather Fong]]\n|successor1   = Greg Suhr\n|birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1954}}\n|birth_place  = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] \n|spouse       = Fabiola Kramsky\n|education    = [[California State University, Long Beach]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Western State College of Law at Argosy University|Western State University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''George Gasc\u00f3n''' (born March 12, 1954) is an American attorney who served as the [[San Francisco District Attorney's Office|District Attorney of San Francisco]] from 2011 to 2019. George Gasc\u00f3n previously served as an Assistant Chief of Police for the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]], and Chief of Police in [[Mesa, Arizona]] and [[San Francisco Police Department|San Francisco]].\n\nGasc\u00f3n was born in Havana, Cuba. In 1967, his family immigrated to the United States and settled in [[Bell, California]]. He joined the [[United States Army]] at the age of eighteen and became a sergeant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://laist.com/2019/10/28/lapd-george-gascon-los-angeles-district-attorney-da-jackie-lacey.php|title=George Gascon Has Said 'We Need To Turn Our Court System Upside Down.' Now He's Running To Be LA's Next DA|last=Stoltze|first=Frank|website=LAist|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> After earning a bachelor of arts in history from [[California State-Long Beach]], Gasc\u00f3n joined the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] as a patrol officer.      \n\nDuring his tenure with the Los Angeles Police Department, he attained the rank of Assistant Chief of Police under Chief [[William Bratton]]. In 2006, Gasc\u00f3n was appointed as Chief of Police for the [[Mesa Police Department (Arizona)|Mesa Police Department]]. He had frequent clashes with [[Maricopa County Sheriff's Office|Maricopa County Sheriff]] [[Joe Arpaio]] over immigration sweeps targeting Latinos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/news/mesa-police-chief-george-gascn-stares-down-sheriff-joe-arpaio-6426648|title=Mesa Police Chief George Gasc\u00f3n stares down Sheriff Joe Arpaio|last=Stern|first=Ray|date=2008-07-10|website=Phoenix New Times|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 2009, then-Mayor [[Gavin Newsom]] appointed Gasc\u00f3n as the Chief of Police for the [[San Francisco Police Department]]. In 2011, after [[Kamala Harris]] was elected [[California Attorney General]], Newsom appointed Gasc\u00f3n to be the San Francisco District Attorney. In 2019, Gasc\u00f3n announced he was running to be the District Attorney for Los Angeles County.<ref name=nyt>{{cite web |last1=Arango |first1=Tim |title=George Gascon Enters Race for District Attorney in Los Angeles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/28/us/george-gacon-district-attorney-los-angeles.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=9 February 2020 |date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life & Education ==\n\nIn 1954, Gasc\u00f3n was born in pre-communist [[Cuba]]. Shortly after the communist revolution in Cuba, Gasc\u00f3n's father lost his job for alleged anti-government activity, and his uncle, a union organizer, was jailed for over a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfweekly.com/news/beyond-the-law-district-attorney-george-gascons-threat-to-san-franciscos-business-as-usual/|title=Beyond the Law: District Attorney George Gasc\u00f3n's threat to San Francisco's business as usual|date=2016-06-09|website=SF Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 1967, Gasc\u00f3n and his family immigrated from Cuba to the United States. \n\nThe Gasc\u00f3n family settled in [[Bell, California]], a suburb of [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2020/02/20/george-gascon-running-to-unseat-jackie-lacey/|title=George Gasc\u00f3n running to unseat Jackie Lacey|date=2020-02-20|website=Los Angeles Blade:  LGBT News, Rights, Politics, Entertainment|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> At the age of thirteen, Gasc\u00f3n enrolled in [[Los Angeles Unified School District]] schools where he struggled to learn english. He recalled: \"I was spending hours translating everything with a Spanish-English dictionary. I started missing a lot of school.\"<ref name=sfgate>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/nevius/article/George-Gasc-n-From-high-school-dropout-to-DA-2446643.php|title=George Gasc\u00f3n: From high school dropout to DA|last=Nevius|first=C. W.|date=2012-01-07|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> By 1972, he dropped out of [[Bell High School (Bell, California)|Bell High School]].<ref name=sfgate/> \n\nGasc\u00f3n joined the [[United States Army]] in 1972. In the army, he earned his high school diploma and two years toward an undergraduate degree.<ref name=military>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-jun-04-me-onthelaw4-story.html|title=He Said No to Naysayers|date=2004-06-04|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> Gasc\u00f3n served in the 64th Military Police Detachment, much of it in Germany.<ref name=military/> In 1975, he received an honorable discharge as a sergeant.<ref name=military/> After the Army, Gasc\u00f3n completed a bachelor of arts in history from [[California State-Long Beach]] while working sales jobs.<ref name=military/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Los Angeles Police Department ===\nIn 1978, Gasc\u00f3n joined the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] as a patrol officer.<ref name=military/> After a three-year stint with the LAPD, he returned to work in business management.<ref name=military/> He served as a reserve officer in the Hollenbeck Division of LAPD until 1987.<ref name=military/> In 1987, he returned to LAPD as a full-time police officer.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rivera |first1=Carla |title=San Francisco Police Chief George Gascon named district attorney |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2011-jan-10-la-me-gascon-da-20110110-story.html |website=The Los Angeles Times |accessdate=9 February 2020 |date=10 January 2011}}</ref> Upon his return, he rose through the ranks of LAPD as a Sergeant, Lieutenant, Captain, Commander, and Deputy Chief in 2002.<ref name=lapd>{{Cite web|url=http://lapdonline.org/february_2003/news_view/21584|title=Two New Assistant Chiefs to be Sworn In at Police Commission Meeting - Los Angeles Police Department|website=lapdonline.org|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> \n\n====Training Commander after Rampart Scandal====\nIn 2000, he took command of the LAPD training unit at the height of the [[Rampart Scandal]].<ref name=military/> He was in command of the LAPD training unit, overseeing the LAPD Academy and in-service training, during the federal government's oversight of police reforms. Even though there was a mandate for reform, then-Police Chief [[Bernard Parks]] did not allocate funding for additional training.<ref name=weekly/> Gasc\u00f3n utilized a grant that had originally been funded to research community-policing strategies, and produced three hundred thousand additional training hours.<ref name=weekly/>\n\nOne of his first orders as training commander was to create an ethics training manual for the LAPD.<ref name=weekly>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/rewriting-the-book/|title=Rewriting the Book|last=Fremon|first=Celeste|date=2002-09-04|website=LA Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> He also implemented problem-based learning and posted a copy of the bill of rights in every LAPD classroom. Michael Gennaco, the former head of the [[United States Justice Department]]'s civil rights division said at the time: \u201cHe fundamentally changed the way the LAPD teaches its officers about civil rights.\u201d<ref name=military/>\n\nIn 2002, Gasc\u00f3n applied to be the Los Angeles Police Department Chief of Police. He wanted to partner with community agencies to reduce California's prisoner-recidivism rate.<ref name=weekly/> [[William Bratton]] was ultimately appointed Chief of Police.\n\n====Assistant Chief of Police====\nIn 2003, he was sworn in as Assistant Chief of the Los Angeles Police Department under Chief [[William Bratton]].<ref name=lapd/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lacp.org/Articles%20-%20Main/ChiefPicksThree.html|title=Chief Bratton Makes Three Great Picks ... LA Community Policing|website=www.lacp.org|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> In 2004, Gasc\u00f3n oversaw the daily operations of the department.<ref name=military/>\n\n=== Mesa Chief of Police ===\nGasc\u00f3n served as chief of the [[Mesa, Arizona]] police department from 2006 to 2009.<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Mayor-picks-Arizona-chief-as-S-F-top-cop-3295093.php Mayor Picks Arizona Chief] Retrieved April 24, 2018</ref>\n\n=== San Francisco Chief of Police ===\nGasc\u00f3n served as [[San Francisco Police Department]] chief from August 2009 to January 2011, succeeding [[Heather Fong]]. He was replaced by [[Greg Suhr]].<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/From-high-school-dropout-to-police-chief-to-DA-s-4705542.php From High School Dropout to Police Chief] Referenced October 9th, 2019</ref> In 2009, San Francisco saw a significant drop in homicides, falling from 96 in 2008 to 45 in 2009. Between 2009 and 2011, violent crime decreased in San Francisco.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/crime/article/S-F-cops-Homicide-up-overall-violent-crime-down-2479732.php|title=S.F. cops: Homicide up, overall violent crime down|last=Berton|first=Justin|date=2011-01-02|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco District Attorney===\nIn 2011, in his last act as Mayor of San Francisco, [[Gavin Newsom]] appointed Gasc\u00f3n as San Francisco District Attorney, filling the seat vacated by [[Kamala Harris]]. In 2018, Gasc\u00f3n announced that he would not be seeking re-election, citing his need to care for his mother in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7news.com/4395553/|title=San Francisco District Attorney George Gascon will not seek reelection|last=KGO|date=2018-10-03|website=ABC7 San Francisco|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref> He resigned from his San Francisco District Attorney position in October 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lagos |first1=Marisa |title=San Francisco District Attorney George Gascon Resigns |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11778096/san-francisco-district-attorney-george-gascon-resigns |accessdate=4 October 2019 |publisher=KQED |date=3 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Bail reform====\nGasc\u00f3n advocated for the end of monetary bail.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/State-must-make-cash-bail-system-just-and-protect-12842585.php State must make cash bail system just and protect public safety] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> Gasc\u00f3n brought the Public Safety Assessment (\u201cPSA\u201d) tool to San Francisco to assist courts in making bail decisions more equitably. Initial results indicate that, compared to defendants released by the PSA, double the percentage of defendants were arrested while they were out on bail or their own recognizance.<ref>[https://www.kqed.org/news/11619469/bail-or-jail-tool-used-by-san-francisco-courts-shows-promising-results Bail or Jail? Tool Used by San Francisco Courts Shows Promising Results] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\n====Drug policy====\nIn 2018, Gasc\u00f3n announced that he would apply California's [[Adult Use of Marijuana Act]] retroactively to every marijuana case since 1975 in order to level the playing field for those adversely affected by the criminalization of marijuana. The move cleared misdemeanor convictions and reduced felony convictions for those entitled for record relief under the act.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2019/02/26/698045482/san-francisco-to-expunge-thousands-of-marijuana-convictions San Francisco To Expunge Thousands Of Marijuana Convictions] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> He partnered with [[Code for America]], a 501(c)3 non-profit organization, which kicked off a national movement resulting in dozens of cities across the country clearing marijuana convictions.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/SF-district-attorney-wipes-out-9-000-plus-13643128.php SF district attorney to wipe out 9,000-plus pot cases going back to 1975] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\nGasc\u00f3n supports ending the war on drugs. Prop 47, which was co-authored by Gasc\u00f3n, reduced simple drug possession from a felony to a misdemeanor in California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/article/Prop-47-is-necessary-to-put-the-war-on-drugs-13413035.php|title=Prop. 47 is necessary to put war on drugs behind us|date=2018-11-23|website=SFChronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n====Data management system====\nGasc\u00f3n implemented and launched the California's first prosecutorial data management system, similar to [[CompStat]], called DA Stat.<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/crime/article/SF-DA-Gasc-n-launches-state-s-first-website-13904234.php SF DA Gasc\u00f3n launches state's first website showing prosecution data] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>  This internal data collection tool is part of a trend toward \"data-driven prosecution.\"\n\n====Investigations of police officers====\nGasc\u00f3n launched a Blue Ribbon Panel<ref>[http://sfdistrictattorney.org/sites/default/files/Document/BRP_report_0.pdf Blue Ribbon Panel] Referenced October 9 2019</ref> to investigate a scandal in the San Francisco Police Department regarding homophobic and racist texts exchanged between over 14 police officers in 2014.<ref>[https://abc7news.com/news/sf-cops-accused-of-exchanging-racist-text-messages/1271363/ San Francisco cops accused of exchanging racist text messages] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\nIn 2016, following recommendations of both the Department of Justice and Blue Ribbon Panel, Gasc\u00f3n secured funding to create the Independent Investigations Bureau, which investigates shootings involving police officers, excessive force, and in-custody deaths.<ref>[https://missionlocal.org/2019/06/the-san-francisco-district-attorney-is-now-the-lead-investigator-in-the-event-of-a-police-shooting/ The San Francisco District Attorney is now the lead investigator of police shootings] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles County District Attorney Race===\nIn 2019, Gasc\u00f3n announced he was running to be the District Attorney for Los Angeles County.<ref name=nyt/> The [[Los Angeles Police Protective League]] contributed one million dollars to defeat Gasc\u00f3n.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theappeal.org/george-gascon-los-angeles-police-union/|title=LA Police Union Contributes $1 Million To Anti-George Gasc\u00f3n PAC|website=The Appeal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Policy positions==\n===Large-Capacity Magazines===\nIn 2013, Gasc\u00f3n wrote an op-ed in support of the the ban of large capacity gun magazines (devices that hold more than ten bullets). He cited, among other things, the large number of mass shootings in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/01/turn-gun-control-attack-toward-large-magazines-86023.html|title=Time to ban large gun clips|last=Gasc\u00f3n|first=George|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nGasc\u00f3n coauthored Senate Bill 962, legislation requiring a \u201ckill switch\u201d on all smartphones sold in California.<ref>[http://www.sfweekly.com/news/snitch/people-are-such-jerks-sometimes/cell-phone-thefts-decrease-in-s-f/ Cell Phone Thefts Decrease in S.F.] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref> \n\nGasc\u00f3n co-authored Proposition 47 that reduced many crimes from felonies to misdemeanors. Proposition 47, according to one study, has reduced the disparity in arrests in San Francisco between Caucasians and African Americans by nearly half.<ref>[https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/article213694224.html Research finds Prop. 47 has reduced racial disparities in drug arrests] Referenced October 9 2019</ref>  Some have criticized the law.<ref>Los Angeles Times[https://www.latimes.com/local/politics/la-me-cap-proposition47-20150226-column.html] \"Movement builds to correct major flaw in Prop. 47\"</ref><ref>California Globe[https://californiaglobe.com/section-2/how-prop-47-fueled-the-homeless-epidemic/] \"How Prop. 47 Fueled the Homeless Epidemic\"</ref><ref>San Diego Union Tribune [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/editorials/story/2019-12-04/california-car-burglaries-doors-locked-loophole?_amp=true] \u201cCriminal justice reform is a great cause. Defending a bad law isn\u2019t.\u201c</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n* \"New Training Program Helps LAPD Meet Training Mandates,\" ''Police Chief'', November 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=192753|title=NCJRS Abstract - National Criminal Justice Reference Service|website=www.ncjrs.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Visionary Award (2017), Southern California Leadership Network<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lachamber.com/news/2017/101/press-release/southern-california-leadership-network-celebrates-30th-anniversary-by-recognizing-30-outstanding-leaders-during-2017-visionaries-awards/|title=Southern California Leadership Network Celebrates 30th Anniversary by Recognizing 30 Outstanding Leaders During 2017 Visionaries Awards|website=lachamber.com|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n* Top 100 Lawyers in California by the Daily Journal,<ref>[https://blog.sfbar.org/2017/10/24/basf-bulletin-board-our-members-and-leaders-circle-firms-making-headlines-24/, BASF Bulletin Board: Our Members and Leaders Circle Firms Making Headlines] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>\n* Anti-Defamation League's Civil Rights Award.<ref>[https://sanfrancisco.adl.org/event/adl-awards-luncheon-honoring-michael-rubin-and-george-gascon/ ADL Awards Luncheon Event] Referenced October 9, 2019</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn March 2010, Gasc\u00f3n made remarks about San Francisco's susceptibility to terrorism by the \"[[Middle Eastern]] community\" that upset [[Arab-Americans]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sfist.com/2010/03/26/police_chief_gascon_angers_middle_e.php | title=Police Chief Gasc\u00f3n Angers Middle Eastern and Arab Community | publisher=SFist | date=26 March 2010 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Keeling, Brock | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516210853/http://sfist.com/2010/03/26/police_chief_gascon_angers_middle_e.php | archivedate=16 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Police-chief-s-remarks-on-terrorism-anger-Arabs-3195205.php | title=Police chief's remarks on terrorism anger Arabs | publisher=SF Gate | date=26 March 2010 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Knight, Heather}}</ref> Several San Francisco police officers accused Gasc\u00f3n of calling [[African-Americans]] \"those people\" in \"a derogatory way.\" Gasc\u00f3n denied making those remarks.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/D-A-Gasc-n-s-divide-with-law-enforcement-6880747.php | title=SF D.A. Gasc\u00f3n\u2019s divide with law enforcement deepens | publisher=San Francisco Chronicle | date=9 March 2016 | accessdate=27 April 2016 | author=Ho, Vivian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/video/category/news-politics/3368209-sf-police-union-officials-claim-da-gascon-made-racist-remarks-at-drunken-party/ | title=SF Police Union Officials Claim DA Gascon Made Racist Remarks At Drunken Party | publisher=CBS SF Bay Area | date=2 March 2016 | accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lapdonline.org/lapd_command_staff/comm_bio_view/7608 LAPD Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gascon, George}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:California State University, Long Beach alumni]]\n[[Category:Cuban emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:District attorneys in California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Police Department officers]]\n[[Category:People from Havana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Police Department chiefs]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American politicians]]\n[[Category:American police chiefs]]\n[[Category:American law enforcement officials]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Gasc%C3%B3n"}
{"title_page": "Peopleton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|52.15196|-2.09177|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Peopleton\n| population               = 640\n| static_image             = Village Shop and Post Office, Peopleton - geograph.org.uk - 131870.jpg\n| static_image_width       = 250px\n| static_image_caption     = Village shop and post office\n| shire_district           = [[Wychavon]] \n| shire_county             = [[Worcestershire]]\n| region                   = West Midlands\n| civil_parish             = \n| constituency_westminster = [[Mid Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Worcestershire]]\n| postcode_district        = WR10\n| postcode_area            = WR\n| post_town                = PERSHORE\n| dial_code                = 01905\n| os_grid_reference        = SO938504\n| london_distance          = {{convert|96.5|mi|km}}\n}}\n'''Peopleton''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[Wychavon]] district of [[Worcestershire]], England. In 2001 the parish had a population of 640, with 245 households.<ref>{{cite web\n | title = Worcestershire County Council : 2001 Census Worcestershire County Population Report\n | publisher = Worcestershire County Council\n | url =http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/cs-research-census-populationreport.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-09-05\n | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927003043/http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/cs-research-census-populationreport.pdf\n | archivedate=2007-09-27\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Location==\nPeopleton is located about {{convert|7|mi|0}} south east of [[Worcester]] and {{convert|3|mi|0}} north of [[Pershore]]. The parish is bounded by [[Bow Brook]] to the west, [[Piddle Brook]] to the east and the [[A44 road|A44]] to the south.<ref>{{cite web  | title =  'Parishes: Peopleton', A History of the County of Worcester: volume 4 (1924), pp. 147-150.  | publisher = British History Online | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42871 |  accessdate = 2007-09-05  }}</ref>\n\nThe parish is bounded by the parishes of [[White Ladies Aston]], [[Upton Snodsbury]], [[Naunton Beauchamp]], [[Throckmorton, Worcestershire|Throckmorton]], [[Pinvin]], [[Drakes Broughton| Drakes Broughton & Wadborough]] and Stoulton.\n\nPeopleton is in the Upton Snodsbury [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]].\n\n==Amenities==\nThe village church is dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]], and is in the [[Anglican Diocese of Worcester]]. It dates from the 13th century with modifications in the 14th and 19th centuries.\n\nOpposite the church in the centre of the village lies the Crown Inn public house.\n\nThe tin at the Cricket Ground is where items such as [[Cricket ball]] , [[Stump (cricket)]] , [[Roller (agricultural tool)]] and [[Beer]]s can be found, this is a valuable part of the cricketing society of Peopleton\n\nIn December 2010 the long-established village shop and post office became a community shop, with a legal structure based on the [[Plunkett Foundation]] rules.<ref name=\"plunkett\"/> In February 2011 it was featured on an edition of the [[BBC]] [[Countryfile]] programme focusing on Worcestershire\n.<ref name=\"countryfile\"/>  A tea room was opened during celebrations of the first anniversary of the community shop in December 2011.<ref name=\"tearoom\"/>\n\nThe village hall and playing fields are on the northern edge of the village. The village hall is home to the Peopleton Scout Group.<ref>http://www.peopletonscouts.com/</ref>\n\nThe village school was closed after the [[Second World War]], and the building is now used as a private residence.<ref name=\"visuk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitoruk.com/evesham/peopleton-C592-V26800.html|title=Peopleton|accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> The only school in the village is now [[Bowbrook House School]], an independent day school,<ref name=\"bowbrook\"/> situated in a mansion at the south end of the village. This house was previously occupied by parish benefactor Caroline Baroness Norton, and later by the mother of [[Barbara Cartland]]; in the Second World War it was used by [[Morgan Crucible]] to accommodate European Voluntary Workers.<ref name=\"visuk\" />\n\nTo the north of Peopleton the track to White Ladies Aston fords Bow Brook at Barrels Bridge.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url=http://www.wetroads.co.uk/worcestershire.htm#peopleton\n | title=Peopleton\n | publisher=wetroads.co.uk\n}}\n</ref>\n\nAfter the extensive [[2007 United Kingdom floods#Worcestershire|floods in 2007]] when a quarter of the houses in Peopleton were flooded, Peopleton Parish Council raised money for a drainage system to reduce the effects of any future flooding.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | title= Flood protection for deluged Worcestershire village\n | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10215655\n | date=2010-06-02\n | publisher=[[BBC]]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nA bus service operated by N.N. Cresswell links Peopleton to [[Upton Snodsbury]], [[Pershore]], and [[Drakes Broughton]].\n\n[[Pershore railway station]] is the closest passenger railway station.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of Worcestershire}}\nThe place-name 'Peopleton' is first attested in a Saxon charter of 972, where it appears as ''Piplincgtun''. It appears as ''Piplintune'' in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086. The name means 'the town or settlement of Pyppel's people'.<ref>[[Eilert Ekwall]], ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names'', p.363.</ref>\n\nThe Worcestershire map in [[John Speed]]'s ''Theatre of the Empire of Great Britaine'' refers to Peopleton as\n\"Pippleton\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url= http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/deptserv/maps/speed.html\n | title= John Speed proof maps\n | publisher=[[Cambridge University Library]]\n | year=1612\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century the cricket club was founded and has progressed nicely over the last century. Tom 'Big Fish' Smith now captains the somewhat \u2018undercooked\u2019 Sunday side. Tom is a product of the Kings School, Worcester where he achieved excellence in all his school work, probably due to playing 'Soggy Biscuit' with the Headmaster. Unfortunately he can\u2019t seem to get this excellence to rub off on the field. Tom also lives in the shadows of his father a prolific and heavy drinker and monkey fister, who has played for multiple clubs and shown his array of cricket talent where ever he has played, something that Tom has failed to replicate since breaking two of his toes on his webbed foot and contracting a nasty rash on his 'Old Chap'!\n\nThe rash has dissapeared but his cricketing skills are still woefully dreadful. The local 'Jungle News' said that the rash was caused by 'rooting' a lady o'the night in Solihull a while ago and according to an 'ex-girlfriend' of Tom's, the rash was on one side only and his 'Old Chap' now bends to the left like a Costa-Rican Banana!...\n\nTom is well settled at Peopleton now as he claim\u2019s \u2018he loves to be the big fish in a small pond\u2019 something that other key members of the side my feel is in correct. Hopefully Tom\u2019s Kings school education will pay off and take the cricket club to the next level.\n\n\n\n\n\nIn 2018 the village was named Cricket Village of the Year by the Ex - England ODI Cricket Captain James Tredwell\n\nThe Cricket Club has a very famous connection with the French City of [[Dijon]] and its [[Dijon mustard|mustard]] , where the notorious club motto Blozzer, Dijon, Wedge comes from. The motto has huge significance for all player members, that much so a Blozzer, Dijon, Wedge Tour was created\n\nThe village has its own local dish called the 'Worcestershire Log' which is essentially a long kebab served with pickled entrails.\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[John Days]], [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire cricketer]] in the 1900s, was born in Peopleton.\n* [[Jeremy Paxman]], [[television presenter]], was brought up in [[Yorkshire]] and Peopleton.\n* [[John Snow (cricketer)|John Snow]], professional [[cricket]]er in the 1960s and 1970s, was born in Peopleton.\n* Giles Turberville (died March 1689), a prosperous local farmer, left \"to the poor of Peopleton 6 shillings and 8 pence\" in his Will.\n* Mark Mongowogchops, [[overall fromage legend]], professional [[cheese]] technician, now sells olives in Middlesex.\n* Angus McCoatup.\n* Dilbert Clinkers Esq.\n* R. Slicker.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist | refs=\n  <ref name=\"plunkett\">{{cite web\n   | url=http://www.plunkett.uk.net/shop/peopleton-community-shop\n   | title=Peopleton Community Shop\n   | publisher=Plunkett Community Shop Network\n   | accessdate=2011-11-02\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"countryfile\">{{cite web\n   | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00z7hc8\n   | title=Countryfile 27/02/2011\n   | publisher=BBC\n   | date=2011-02-27\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"bowbrook\">{{cite web\n   | title = Bowbrook House School\n   | url = http://www.bowbrookhouseschool.co.uk/\n   | accessdate=2011-11-02\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"tearoom\">{{cite web\n   | title = Peopleton people celebrate community shop anniversary\n   | url = http://www.eveshamjournal.co.uk/news/9406958.Peopleton_people_celebrate_community_shop_anniversary/\n   | date=2011-12-08\n   | publisher=Evesham Journal\n  }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42871\n|title=Peopleton\n|work=A History of the County of Worcester: volume 4 (1924), pp. 147-150.\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.worcesterbmsgh.co.uk/Peopleton.html\n|publisher=Worcester Branch of the Birmingham & Midland Society for Genealogy and Heraldry\n|title=Parish Records\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/cms/images/Census_OldParish_Peopleton.jpg\n|title=Map of 1850 parish boundary\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n|publisher=[[Worcestershire County Council]]\n}}\n*{{YouTube\n |id=eNrog2b_aiw\n |title=Peopleton Flood Defence\n}}\n*{{Cite journal\n | journal=Peopleton Times\n | first1=Peter\n | last1=Burfitt\n | first2=Celia\n | last2=Emmins\n | first3=Nicky\n | last3=Piercy\n | year=2004\n | volume=1\n}}\n\n{{Wychavon}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Worcestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|52.15196|-2.09177|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Peopleton\n| population               = 640\n| static_image             = Village Shop and Post Office, Peopleton - geograph.org.uk - 131870.jpg\n| static_image_width       = 250px\n| static_image_caption     = Village shop and post office\n| shire_district           = [[Wychavon]] \n| shire_county             = [[Worcestershire]]\n| region                   = West Midlands\n| civil_parish             = \n| constituency_westminster = [[Mid Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Worcestershire]]\n| postcode_district        = WR10\n| postcode_area            = WR\n| post_town                = PERSHORE\n| dial_code                = 01905\n| os_grid_reference        = SO938504\n| london_distance          = {{convert|96.5|mi|km}}\n}}\n'''Peopleton''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[Wychavon]] district of [[Worcestershire]], England. In 2001 the parish had a population of 640, with 245 households.<ref>{{cite web\n | title = Worcestershire County Council : 2001 Census Worcestershire County Population Report\n | publisher = Worcestershire County Council\n | url =http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/cs-research-census-populationreport.pdf\n | accessdate = 2007-09-05\n | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927003043/http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/home/cs-research-census-populationreport.pdf\n | archivedate=2007-09-27\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Location==\nPeopleton is located about {{convert|7|mi|0}} south east of [[Worcester]] and {{convert|3|mi|0}} north of [[Pershore]]. The parish is bounded by [[Bow Brook]] to the west, [[Piddle Brook]] to the east and the [[A44 road|A44]] to the south.<ref>{{cite web  | title =  'Parishes: Peopleton', A History of the County of Worcester: volume 4 (1924), pp. 147-150.  | publisher = British History Online | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42871 |  accessdate = 2007-09-05  }}</ref>\n\nThe parish is bounded by the parishes of [[White Ladies Aston]], [[Upton Snodsbury]], [[Naunton Beauchamp]], [[Throckmorton, Worcestershire|Throckmorton]], [[Pinvin]], [[Drakes Broughton| Drakes Broughton & Wadborough]] and Stoulton.\n\nPeopleton is in the Upton Snodsbury [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]].\n\n==Amenities==\nThe village church is dedicated to [[Saint Nicholas]], and is in the [[Anglican Diocese of Worcester]]. It dates from the 13th century with modifications in the 14th and 19th centuries.\n\nOpposite the church in the centre of the village lies the Crown Inn public house.\n\nThe tin at the Cricket Ground is where items such as [[Cricket ball]] , [[Stump (cricket)]] , [[Roller (agricultural tool)]] and [[Beer]]s can be found, this is a valuable part of the cricketing society of Peopleton\n\nIn December 2010 the long-established village shop and post office became a community shop, with a legal structure based on the [[Plunkett Foundation]] rules.<ref name=\"plunkett\"/> In February 2011 it was featured on an edition of the [[BBC]] [[Countryfile]] programme focusing on Worcestershire\n.<ref name=\"countryfile\"/>  A tea room was opened during celebrations of the first anniversary of the community shop in December 2011.<ref name=\"tearoom\"/>\n\nThe village hall and playing fields are on the northern edge of the village. The village hall is home to the Peopleton Scout Group.<ref>http://www.peopletonscouts.com/</ref>\n\nThe village school was closed after the [[Second World War]], and the building is now used as a private residence.<ref name=\"visuk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitoruk.com/evesham/peopleton-C592-V26800.html|title=Peopleton|accessdate=2013-06-04}}</ref> The only school in the village is now [[Bowbrook House School]], an independent day school,<ref name=\"bowbrook\"/> situated in a mansion at the south end of the village. This house was previously occupied by parish benefactor Caroline Baroness Norton, and later by the mother of [[Barbara Cartland]]; in the Second World War it was used by [[Morgan Crucible]] to accommodate European Voluntary Workers.<ref name=\"visuk\" />\n\nTo the north of Peopleton the track to White Ladies Aston fords Bow Brook at Barrels Bridge.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url=http://www.wetroads.co.uk/worcestershire.htm#peopleton\n | title=Peopleton\n | publisher=wetroads.co.uk\n}}\n</ref>\n\nAfter the extensive [[2007 United Kingdom floods#Worcestershire|floods in 2007]] when a quarter of the houses in Peopleton were flooded, Peopleton Parish Council raised money for a drainage system to reduce the effects of any future flooding.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | title= Flood protection for deluged Worcestershire village\n | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10215655\n | date=2010-06-02\n | publisher=[[BBC]]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nA bus service operated by N.N. Cresswell links Peopleton to [[Upton Snodsbury]], [[Pershore]], and [[Drakes Broughton]].\n\n[[Pershore railway station]] is the closest passenger railway station.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of Worcestershire}}\nThe place-name 'Peopleton' is first attested in a Saxon charter of 972, where it appears as ''Piplincgtun''. It appears as ''Piplintune'' in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086. The name means 'the town or settlement of Pyppel's people'.<ref>[[Eilert Ekwall]], ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names'', p.363.</ref>\n\nThe Worcestershire map in [[John Speed]]'s ''Theatre of the Empire of Great Britaine'' refers to Peopleton as\n\"Pippleton\".<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url= http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/deptserv/maps/speed.html\n | title= John Speed proof maps\n | publisher=[[Cambridge University Library]]\n | year=1612\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 20th century the cricket club was founded and has progressed nicely over the last century. Tom Smith now captains the some what \u2018undercooked\u2019 Sunday side. Tom is a product of the Kings School, Worcester where he achieved excellence in all his school work. Unfortunately he can\u2019t seem to get this excellence to rub off on the field. Tom also lives in the shadows of his father a prolific batsmen, who has played for multiple clubs and shown his array of cricket talent where ever he has played, something that Tom has failed to replicate. Tom is well settled at Peopleton now as he claim\u2019s \u2018he loves to be the big fish in a small pond\u2019 something that other key members of the side my feel is in correct. Hopefully Tom\u2019s Kings school education will pay off and take the cricket club to the next level\n\nIn 2018 the village was named Cricket Village of the Year by the Ex - England ODI Cricket Captain James Tredwell\n\nThe Cricket Club has a very famous connection with the French City of [[Dijon]] and its [[Dijon mustard|mustard]] , where the notorious club motto Blozzer, Dijon, Wedge comes from. The motto has huge significance for all player members, that much so a Blozzer, Dijon, Wedge Tour was created\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[John Days]], [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire cricketer]] in the 1900s, was born in Peopleton.\n* [[Jeremy Paxman]], [[television presenter]], was brought up in [[Yorkshire]] and Peopleton.\n* [[John Snow (cricketer)|John Snow]], professional [[cricket]]er in the 1960s and 1970s, was born in Peopleton.\n* Giles Turberville (died March 1689), a prosperous local farmer, left \"to the poor of Peopleton 6 shillings and 8 pence\" in his Will.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist | refs=\n  <ref name=\"plunkett\">{{cite web\n   | url=http://www.plunkett.uk.net/shop/peopleton-community-shop\n   | title=Peopleton Community Shop\n   | publisher=Plunkett Community Shop Network\n   | accessdate=2011-11-02\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"countryfile\">{{cite web\n   | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00z7hc8\n   | title=Countryfile 27/02/2011\n   | publisher=BBC\n   | date=2011-02-27\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"bowbrook\">{{cite web\n   | title = Bowbrook House School\n   | url = http://www.bowbrookhouseschool.co.uk/\n   | accessdate=2011-11-02\n  }}</ref>\n  <ref name=\"tearoom\">{{cite web\n   | title = Peopleton people celebrate community shop anniversary\n   | url = http://www.eveshamjournal.co.uk/news/9406958.Peopleton_people_celebrate_community_shop_anniversary/\n   | date=2011-12-08\n   | publisher=Evesham Journal\n  }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42871\n|title=Peopleton\n|work=A History of the County of Worcester: volume 4 (1924), pp. 147-150.\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.worcesterbmsgh.co.uk/Peopleton.html\n|publisher=Worcester Branch of the Birmingham & Midland Society for Genealogy and Heraldry\n|title=Parish Records\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://worcestershire.whub.org.uk/cms/images/Census_OldParish_Peopleton.jpg\n|title=Map of 1850 parish boundary\n|accessdate=2011-05-18\n|publisher=[[Worcestershire County Council]]\n}}\n*{{YouTube\n |id=eNrog2b_aiw\n |title=Peopleton Flood Defence\n}}\n*{{Cite journal\n | journal=Peopleton Times\n | first1=Peter\n | last1=Burfitt\n | first2=Celia\n | last2=Emmins\n | first3=Nicky\n | last3=Piercy\n | year=2004\n | volume=1\n}}\n\n{{Wychavon}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Worcestershire]]\n", "name_user": "94.5.65.171", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 953872765 byPdcook(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peopleton"}
{"title_page": "Division (naval)", "text_new": "{{naval units}}\nA naval '''division''' is a subdivision of a [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]] or [[flotilla]]. It can also be a  [[1st Division (Royal Navy)|sub-division of a fleet]]. A division is the smallest naval formation, most commonly numbering between 2 to 4 ships.\n\n[[File:All Four Iowas.jpg|thumbnail|right|The four Iowa-class ships operating as Battleship Division 2 off the Virginia Capes in 1954; from front to back is Iowa, Wisconsin, Missouri and New Jersey]]\nA '''BatDiv''' or '''BATDIV''' was a standard [[U.S. Navy]] abbreviation or acronym for \"[[battleship]] [[Division (naval)|division]].\" The Commander of a Battleship Division was known, in official Navy communications, as COMBATDIV (followed by a number), such as COMBATDIV ONE.\n\n\n== Command Element ==\nA division is usually commanded by senior flag officer, most commonly a [[vice admiral]] or [[rear admiral]], irrespective of the division's size. For example, in the Imperial Japanese Navy the [[First Carrier Division| First Carrier Division]] was commanded by a rear or vice admiral, same as the  [[18th Cruiser Division (Imperial Japanese Navy) | 18th Cruiser Division]]. \n\n== Division Types ==\nDivisions are most commonly grouped by ship class and type, dependent on the respective nation's navy is organised. Examples of division types include:\n*Submarine Division - [[24th Submarine Division (Russia) | 24th Submarine Division (Russian Navy)]] - 6 submarines\n*Minesweeper Division - [[Mine_Squadron_7#Mine_Division_71| Mine Division 71]] (United States Navy) - 2 minesweepers \n*Sloop Division - [[2nd Escort Group (Royal Navy)]] - 6 Sloops\n*Destroyer Division - Destroyer Division 22 (United States Navy) - 4 destroyers \n*Cruiser Division - 18th Cruiser Division (Imperial Japanese Navy) - 2 light cruisers\n*Battleship Division - [[BatDiv#cite_note-4| Battleship Division 2]] (United States Navy) - 4 battleships\n*Carrier Division - [[Second Carrier Division]] (Imperial Japanese Navy) - 2 aircraft carriers \n\n== References == \n*Peattie, Mark R. (1999). Sunburst: The Rise of Japanese Naval Air Power 1909-1941. Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. ISBN 1-59114-664-X.\n*Morison, Samuel E. (1963) The Two-Ocean War: A Short History of the United States Navy in the Second World War. New York City: Little, Brown and Company. ISBN 0-316-5835-2-9\n\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BatDiv]]\n* [[Destroyer squadron]]\n\n[[Category:Naval units and formations by size]]\n{{term-stub}}\n{{navy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{naval units}}\nA naval '''division''' is a subdivision of a [[Squadron (naval)|squadron]] or [[flotilla]]. It can also be a  [[1st Division (Royal Navy)|sub-division of a fleet]]. A division is the smallest naval formation, most commonly numbering between 2 to 4 ships.\n\n== Command Element ==\nA division is usually commanded by senior flag officer, most commonly a [[vice admiral]] or [[rear admiral]], irrespective of the division's size. For example, in the Imperial Japanese Navy the [[First Carrier Division| First Carrier Division]] was commanded by a rear or vice admiral, same as the  [[18th Cruiser Division (Imperial Japanese Navy) | 18th Cruiser Division]]. \n\n== Division Types ==\nDivisions are most commonly grouped by ship class and type, dependent on the respective nation's navy is organised. Examples of division types include:\n*Submarine Division - [[24th Submarine Division (Russia) | 24th Submarine Division (Russian Navy)]] - 6 submarines\n*Minesweeper Division - [[Mine_Squadron_7#Mine_Division_71| Mine Division 71]] (United States Navy) - 2 minesweepers \n*Sloop Division - [[2nd Escort Group (Royal Navy)]] - 6 Sloops\n*Destroyer Division - Destroyer Division 22 (United States Navy) - 4 destroyers \n*Cruiser Division - 18th Cruiser Division (Imperial Japanese Navy) - 2 light cruisers\n*Battleship Division - [[BatDiv#cite_note-4| Battleship Division 2]] (United States Navy) - 4 battleships\n*Carrier Division - [[Second Carrier Division]] (Imperial Japanese Navy) - 2 aircraft carriers \n\n== References == \n*Peattie, Mark R. (1999). Sunburst: The Rise of Japanese Naval Air Power 1909-1941. Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. ISBN 1-59114-664-X.\n*Morison, Samuel E. (1963) The Two-Ocean War: A Short History of the United States Navy in the Second World War. New York City: Little, Brown and Company. ISBN 0-316-5835-2-9\n\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BatDiv]]\n* [[Destroyer squadron]]\n\n[[Category:Naval units and formations by size]]\n{{term-stub}}\n{{navy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "OMaxwell43", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added image of BATDIV 2, Taken from the BATDIV page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(naval)"}
{"title_page": "Green Mountains", "text_new": "{{about|the mountain range in Vermont|other uses|Green Mountain (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n| name = Green Mountains\n| photo = South from Mount Mansfield.jpg\n| photo_caption = Green Mountains looking South from the summit of [[Mount Mansfield]]\n| parent =[[Appalachian Mountains]]\n| location = [[Vermont]]\n| highest = Mount Mansfield\n}}\n\nThe '''Green Mountains''' are a [[mountain range]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]]. The range runs primarily south to north and extends approximately {{convert|250|mi|km}} from the border with [[Massachusetts]] to the border with [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The part of the same range that is in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Connecticut]] is known as [[The Berkshires]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academics.smcvt.edu/vtgeographic/textbook/mountains/mountains_of_vermont.htm|title=The Mountains of Vermont|publisher=Saint Michael's College|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref> or the Berkshire Hills<ref>{{Cite gnis|id=619372|name=Berkshire Hills|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> (with the Connecticut portion, mostly in [[Litchfield County, Connecticut|Litchfield County]], locally called the Northwest Hills or Litchfield Hills) and the Quebec portion is called the Sutton Mountains, or ''Monts Sutton'' in French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/toposweb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=61211|title=Monts Sutton|publisher=Commission de toponymie Qu\u00e9bec|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nAll mountains in Vermont are often referred to as the \"Green Mountains\". \"Green\" because even with winter snow the trees hide the snow and they still appear \"Green\".  However, other ranges within Vermont, including the [[Taconics]]\u2014in southwestern Vermont's extremity\u2014and the [[Northeast Kingdom|Northeastern Highlands]], are not geologically part of the Green Mountains.\n\n==Peaks==\n[[Image:GreenMtns fromJayPeak.jpg|thumb|right|Green Mountains looking south from [[Jay Peak (Vermont)|Jay Peak]]]]\n[[Image:Northern Green Mtns.jpg|thumb|right|Jay Peak, located at the northern end of the Green Mountains in Vermont]]\n[[Image:greenmountains.jpg|thumb|right|Green Mountains outside of [[Montpelier, Vermont]]]]\nThe best-known mountains\u2014for reasons such as high elevation, ease of public access by road or trail (especially the [[Long Trail]] and [[Appalachian Trail]]), or with ski resorts or towns nearby\u2014in the range include:<ref>Peak elevations taken from {{cite web|title=Mountain Peaks, Summits, and High Points|url=http://www.mountainzone.com/mountains|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n# [[Mount Mansfield]], {{convert|4395|ft|m}}, the highest point in Vermont\n# [[Killington Peak]], {{convert|4241|ft|m}}\n# [[Camel's Hump]], {{convert|4084|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Ellen (Vermont)|Mount Ellen]], {{convert|4083|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Abraham (Vermont)|Mount Abraham]], {{convert|4017|ft|m}}\n# [[Pico Peak]], {{convert|3957|ft|m}}\n# [[Stratton Mountain (Vermont)|Stratton Mountain]], {{convert|3940|ft|m}}, the mountain at which the initial ideas of both the Long Trail and the Appalachian Trail were born{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n# [[Jay Peak (Vermont)|Jay Peak]], {{convert|3862|ft|m}}, receives the most snowfall on average in the eastern United States.<ref>{{cite book | author = Wheeler, Scott |title = The Man Who Helped Electrify the Jay Peak Ski Area | publisher = Northland Journal |date=February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = McLean, Dan |title = Investors purchase Jay Peak | publisher = Burlington Free Press | date = July 1, 2008}}</ref>\n# [[Bread Loaf Mountain]], {{convert|3835|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Wilson (Vermont)|Mount Wilson]], {{convert|3780|ft|m}}\n# [[Glastenbury Mountain]], {{convert|3748|ft|m}}\n# [[Burke Mountain (Vermont)|Burke Mountain]], {{convert|3280|ft|m|}}\n\nThe Green Mountains are part of the [[Appalachian Mountains]], a range that stretches from Quebec in the north to [[Alabama]] in the south. The Green Mountains are part of the [[New England/Acadian forests]] [[ecoregion]].<ref name=\"Ecoregions\">{{cite journal|author=Olson, D. M, E. Dinerstein |title=Terrestrial Ecoregions of the World: A New Map of Life on Earth |journal=[[BioScience]] |year=2001 |volume=51 |issue=11 |pages=933\u2013938 |url=http://gis.wwfus.org/wildfinder/ |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2001)051[0933:TEOTWA]2.0.CO;2 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014034322/http://gis.wwfus.org/wildfinder/ |archivedate=2011-10-14 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThree peaks\u2014Mount Mansfield, Camel's Hump, and Mount Abraham\u2014support [[alpine plant|alpine vegetation]].{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Tourism==\nSome of the mountains are developed for [[skiing]] and other snow-related activities. Others have hiking trails for use in summer.<ref>[http://www.summitpost.org/green-mountains-vermont/170967 Green Mountains (Vermont) : Climbing, Hiking & Mountaineering]. SummitPost. Retrieved on 2013-07-12.</ref> Mansfield, Killington, Pico, and Ellen have downhill ski resorts on their slopes. All of the major peaks are traversed by the [[Long Trail]], a wilderness [[hiking trail]] that runs from the southern to northern borders of the state and is overlapped by the [[Appalachian Trail]] for roughly {{frac|3}} of its length.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Vermont Republic]], also known as the Green Mountain Republic,<ref>See, e.g., Robert Temple, ''Edge Effects: The Border-Name Places'' (2008), p. 6; Paul Finkelman and Stephen E. Gottlieb, ''Toward a Usable Past: Liberty Under State Constitutions'' (University of Georgia Press, 2009), p. 375; Ralph Nading Hill, ''The College on the Hill: A Dartmouth Chronicle'' (Dartmouth Publications: 1965), pp. 46, 50; Vermont Historical Society, ''Vermont History'', Vol. 66-67 (1998), p. 87.</ref> existed from 1777 to 1791, at which time Vermont became the 14th state.\n\nVermont not only takes its [[state nickname]] (\"The Green Mountain State\") from the mountains, it is named after them. The French ''Monts Verts'' or ''Verts Monts'' is literally translated as \"Green Mountains\". This name was suggested in 1777 by [[Thomas Young (American revolutionary)|Dr. Thomas Young]], an American revolutionary and [[Boston Tea Party]] participant.  The [[University of Vermont|University of Vermont and State Agricultural College]] is referred to as UVM, after the Latin ''Universitas Viridis Montis'' (University of the Green Mountains).<ref>[http://www.uvm.edu/about_uvm/?Page=history/default.html&SM=historysubmenu.html History and Traditions], University of Vermont.</ref>\n\n==Geology and physiography==\n[[Image:NortheastAppalachiansMap.jpg|thumb|right|320px|Map of the main regions of the northern Appalachians]]\nThe Green Mountains are a [[Physiographic regions of the world|physiographic section]] of the larger [[New England province]], which in turn is part of the larger [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] physiographic division.<ref name=\"USGS-Water\">{{cite web |title=Physiographic divisions of the conterminous U. S. |publisher=U.S. Geological Survey |url=http://water.usgs.gov/GIS/metadata/usgswrd/XML/physio.xml |accessdate=2007-12-06 }}</ref>\n\nLemon Fair runs through the towns of Orwell, Sudbury, Shoreham, Bridport, and [[Cornwall, Vermont]], before flowing into [[Otter Creek (Vermont)|Otter Creek]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}{{clarify|needs tie-in with Green Mountains|date=July 2015}} The story is that its name derives from early English-speaking settlers' phonetic approximation of 'Les Monts Verts'.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Green Mountain National Forest]]\n* [[Green Mountain Boys]]\u2014[[paramilitary]] infantry led by [[Ethan Allen]] that took [[Fort Ticonderoga]] during the [[American Revolution]]\n* [[Green Mountain Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Green Mountains}}\n{{AmCyc Poster}}\n* {{GNIS|1460934|Green Mountains}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|short=x|wstitle=Green Mountains}}\n\n{{Vermont}}\n{{Mountains of Quebec}}\n{{Mountains of Vermont}}\n{{coord|44|47|30|N|72|34|58|W|type:mountain_region:US-VT_dim:50km_source:GNIS|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Addison County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Bennington County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Chittenden County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lamoille County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Orleans County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Rutland County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Washington County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Windham County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Physiographic sections]]\n[[Category:Regions of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Subranges of the Appalachian Mountains]]\n[[Category:Vermont culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the mountain range in Vermont|other uses|Green Mountain (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox mountain range\n| name = Green Mountains\n| photo = South from Mount Mansfield.jpg\n| photo_caption = Green Mountains looking South from the summit of [[Mount Mansfield]]\n| parent =[[Appalachian Mountains]]\n| location = [[Vermont]]\n| highest = Mount Mansfield\n}}\n\nThe '''Green Mountains''' are a [[mountain range]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Vermont]]. The range runs primarily south to north and extends approximately {{convert|250|mi|km}} from the border with [[Massachusetts]] to the border with [[Quebec]], [[Canada]]. The part of the same range that is in [[Massachusetts]] and [[Connecticut]] is known as [[The Berkshires]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academics.smcvt.edu/vtgeographic/textbook/mountains/mountains_of_vermont.htm|title=The Mountains of Vermont|publisher=Saint Michael's College|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref> or the Berkshire Hills<ref>{{Cite gnis|id=619372|name=Berkshire Hills|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref> (with the Connecticut portion, mostly in [[Litchfield County, Connecticut|Litchfield County]], locally called the Northwest Hills or Litchfield Hills) and the Quebec portion is called the Sutton Mountains, or ''Monts Sutton'' in French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/toposweb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=61211|title=Monts Sutton|publisher=Commission de toponymie Qu\u00e9bec|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nAll mountains in Vermont are often referred to as the \"Green Mountains\". However, other ranges within Vermont, including the [[Taconics]]\u2014in southwestern Vermont's extremity\u2014and the [[Northeast Kingdom|Northeastern Highlands]], are not geologically part of the Green Mountains.\n\n==Peaks==\n[[Image:GreenMtns fromJayPeak.jpg|thumb|right|Green Mountains looking south from [[Jay Peak (Vermont)|Jay Peak]]]]\n[[Image:Northern Green Mtns.jpg|thumb|right|Jay Peak, located at the northern end of the Green Mountains in Vermont]]\n[[Image:greenmountains.jpg|thumb|right|Green Mountains outside of [[Montpelier, Vermont]]]]\nThe best-known mountains\u2014for reasons such as high elevation, ease of public access by road or trail (especially the [[Long Trail]] and [[Appalachian Trail]]), or with ski resorts or towns nearby\u2014in the range include:<ref>Peak elevations taken from {{cite web|title=Mountain Peaks, Summits, and High Points|url=http://www.mountainzone.com/mountains|accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n# [[Mount Mansfield]], {{convert|4395|ft|m}}, the highest point in Vermont\n# [[Killington Peak]], {{convert|4241|ft|m}}\n# [[Camel's Hump]], {{convert|4084|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Ellen (Vermont)|Mount Ellen]], {{convert|4083|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Abraham (Vermont)|Mount Abraham]], {{convert|4017|ft|m}}\n# [[Pico Peak]], {{convert|3957|ft|m}}\n# [[Stratton Mountain (Vermont)|Stratton Mountain]], {{convert|3940|ft|m}}, the mountain at which the initial ideas of both the Long Trail and the Appalachian Trail were born{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n# [[Jay Peak (Vermont)|Jay Peak]], {{convert|3862|ft|m}}, receives the most snowfall on average in the eastern United States.<ref>{{cite book | author = Wheeler, Scott |title = The Man Who Helped Electrify the Jay Peak Ski Area | publisher = Northland Journal |date=February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = McLean, Dan |title = Investors purchase Jay Peak | publisher = Burlington Free Press | date = July 1, 2008}}</ref>\n# [[Bread Loaf Mountain]], {{convert|3835|ft|m}}\n# [[Mount Wilson (Vermont)|Mount Wilson]], {{convert|3780|ft|m}}\n# [[Glastenbury Mountain]], {{convert|3748|ft|m}}\n# [[Burke Mountain (Vermont)|Burke Mountain]], {{convert|3280|ft|m|}}\n\nThe Green Mountains are part of the [[Appalachian Mountains]], a range that stretches from Quebec in the north to [[Alabama]] in the south. The Green Mountains are part of the [[New England/Acadian forests]] [[ecoregion]].<ref name=\"Ecoregions\">{{cite journal|author=Olson, D. M, E. Dinerstein |title=Terrestrial Ecoregions of the World: A New Map of Life on Earth |journal=[[BioScience]] |year=2001 |volume=51 |issue=11 |pages=933\u2013938 |url=http://gis.wwfus.org/wildfinder/ |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2001)051[0933:TEOTWA]2.0.CO;2 |display-authors=etal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014034322/http://gis.wwfus.org/wildfinder/ |archivedate=2011-10-14 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nThree peaks\u2014Mount Mansfield, Camel's Hump, and Mount Abraham\u2014support [[alpine plant|alpine vegetation]].{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Tourism==\nSome of the mountains are developed for [[skiing]] and other snow-related activities. Others have hiking trails for use in summer.<ref>[http://www.summitpost.org/green-mountains-vermont/170967 Green Mountains (Vermont) : Climbing, Hiking & Mountaineering]. SummitPost. Retrieved on 2013-07-12.</ref> Mansfield, Killington, Pico, and Ellen have downhill ski resorts on their slopes. All of the major peaks are traversed by the [[Long Trail]], a wilderness [[hiking trail]] that runs from the southern to northern borders of the state and is overlapped by the [[Appalachian Trail]] for roughly {{frac|3}} of its length.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Vermont Republic]], also known as the Green Mountain Republic,<ref>See, e.g., Robert Temple, ''Edge Effects: The Border-Name Places'' (2008), p. 6; Paul Finkelman and Stephen E. Gottlieb, ''Toward a Usable Past: Liberty Under State Constitutions'' (University of Georgia Press, 2009), p. 375; Ralph Nading Hill, ''The College on the Hill: A Dartmouth Chronicle'' (Dartmouth Publications: 1965), pp. 46, 50; Vermont Historical Society, ''Vermont History'', Vol. 66-67 (1998), p. 87.</ref> existed from 1777 to 1791, at which time Vermont became the 14th state.\n\nVermont not only takes its [[state nickname]] (\"The Green Mountain State\") from the mountains, it is named after them. The French ''Monts Verts'' or ''Verts Monts'' is literally translated as \"Green Mountains\". This name was suggested in 1777 by [[Thomas Young (American revolutionary)|Dr. Thomas Young]], an American revolutionary and [[Boston Tea Party]] participant.  The [[University of Vermont|University of Vermont and State Agricultural College]] is referred to as UVM, after the Latin ''Universitas Viridis Montis'' (University of the Green Mountains).<ref>[http://www.uvm.edu/about_uvm/?Page=history/default.html&SM=historysubmenu.html History and Traditions], University of Vermont.</ref>\n\n==Geology and physiography==\n[[Image:NortheastAppalachiansMap.jpg|thumb|right|320px|Map of the main regions of the northern Appalachians]]\nThe Green Mountains are a [[Physiographic regions of the world|physiographic section]] of the larger [[New England province]], which in turn is part of the larger [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachian]] physiographic division.<ref name=\"USGS-Water\">{{cite web |title=Physiographic divisions of the conterminous U. S. |publisher=U.S. Geological Survey |url=http://water.usgs.gov/GIS/metadata/usgswrd/XML/physio.xml |accessdate=2007-12-06 }}</ref>\n\nLemon Fair runs through the towns of Orwell, Sudbury, Shoreham, Bridport, and [[Cornwall, Vermont]], before flowing into [[Otter Creek (Vermont)|Otter Creek]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}{{clarify|needs tie-in with Green Mountains|date=July 2015}} The story is that its name derives from early English-speaking settlers' phonetic approximation of 'Les Monts Verts'.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Green Mountain National Forest]]\n* [[Green Mountain Boys]]\u2014[[paramilitary]] infantry led by [[Ethan Allen]] that took [[Fort Ticonderoga]] during the [[American Revolution]]\n* [[Green Mountain Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Green Mountains}}\n{{AmCyc Poster}}\n* {{GNIS|1460934|Green Mountains}}\n* {{Cite NSRW|short=x|wstitle=Green Mountains}}\n\n{{Vermont}}\n{{Mountains of Quebec}}\n{{Mountains of Vermont}}\n{{coord|44|47|30|N|72|34|58|W|type:mountain_region:US-VT_dim:50km_source:GNIS|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Addison County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Bennington County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Chittenden County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lamoille County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Orleans County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Rutland County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Washington County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Windham County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Physiographic sections]]\n[[Category:Regions of Vermont]]\n[[Category:Subranges of the Appalachian Mountains]]\n[[Category:Vermont culture]]\n", "name_user": "Steveruth88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Why the term \"Green Mountains\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Mountains"}
{"title_page": "Maria Majocchi", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maria Majocchi Plattis\n| image              = Maria Majocchi Plattis.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| othername          = Margheritina di Cento, Jolanda,\n\nMarchesa Maria Plattis\n| birth_name         = Maria Majocchi\n| birth_date         = 23 April 1864\n| birth_place        = Cento, Italy\n| death_date         = 8 August 1917\n| death_place        = Cento, Italy\n| burial_place       = \n| nationality        = Italian\n| occupation         = Writer, Journalist, Editor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = Marquis Fernando Plattis\n| children           = Giovan Battista Plattis\n| mother             = Lavinia Agnoletti (1839-1911)\n| father             = Antonio Majocchi (1831-1907)\n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Maria Majocchi''' (sometimes spelled '''Maiocchi''') (Cento, 23 April 1864 - Cento, 8 August 1917), was an Italian writer, journalist and publisher. She wrote under several pseudonyms, often '''Jolanda,''' or more rarely '''Viola d'Alba''' or '''Margheritina di Cento.''' \n\n== Biography ==\n\nMaria was born to the musician and politician Antonio Majocchi (1831-1907), one time mayor of Cento, and his wife Lavinia Agnoletti (1839-1911) who had a rich literary, linguistic and musical background. Maria had at least two sisters, Clementina Laura and Gabriella.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it//enciclopedia/maria-majocchi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=MAJOCCHI, Maria in \"Dizionario Biografico\"|website=www.treccani.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> \n\nMaria was a writer, journalist and editor. In 1882 she chose to publish using the pseudonym '''Jolanda''', which she borrowed from a character in the opera ''Una Partita a Scacchi (\"A Game of Chess\")'' by [[Giuseppe Giacosa|Giuseppe Giacosa.]]<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Giacosa|first=Giuseppe|url=http://archive.org/details/unapartitascacch00giacuoft|title=Una partita a scacchi, leggenda dramatica in un atto; Il Triomfo d'amore, leggenda drammatica in due atti: Intermezzi e Scene|date=1911|publisher=Milano, Treves|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== Writer ===\nMajocchi acquired excellent knowledge of the French language and she subscribed to the Parisian magazine ''Poup\u00e9e mod\u00e8le. A''t 17 years of age, Majocchi was known to be translating its stories from French into Italian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe was also a subscriber to Italian magazines and one in particular attracted her attention: it was ''Cordelia'', conceived in 1881, and directed until 1884, by [[Angelo de Gubernatis|Angelo De Gubernatis]], who would become Maria's lifelong friend and collaborator.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bloom|first=Karin|date=2017|title=L\u2019affermarsi nell\u2019Italia postunitaria di un nuovo genere editoriale: il caso di Cordelia|url=https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=588427|journal=Italica Wratislaviensia|language=Italian|volume=8|issue=2|pages=37\u201352|issn=2084-4514}}</ref> In its first issue, the editor invited his young readers to send \"a little thing done there\" to the editorial staff for publication.<ref name=\":0\" /> Majocchi responded immediately and, on 12 February 1882, her first poetic sketch, ''Il fior della ventura (The Flower of Fortune)'', was published under her first pseudonym '''Margheritina di Cento'''. From that time on, not yet 20 years old, she became a regular contributor to the magazine, with a fixed starting salary of 5 lire per page. Her signature appeared at the bottom of each piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer first stories, which were originally published in installments, would be brought together into collections for publication in later years as single volumes: ''Dal mio verziere (From My Orchard), Critical essays'' (Rocca San Casciano, 1896) and ''Le Ignote (The Unknowns)'' (Bologna, 1899).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Married life ===\nAt about the same time, on 8 December 1884, Majocchi married the Marquis Ferdinando Plattis, a young man from [[Padua]] and she moved to [[San Giovanni in Persiceto]]. They had a son named Giovan Battista Plattis, who they called Gino. Writing to De Gubernatis, to whom she was always bound by friendship and deep esteem, she assured him that her collaboration with ''Cordelia'' would not be interrupted because of her marriage. Ferdinando died on 5 May 1893 following a brief illness and economic difficulties forced Majocchi to intensify her writing work. She sent Gino to De Gubernatis for some time so he could continue his studies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBy the end of the 1800s, she was a widely known author, winning a succession of awards and seeing new editions and reprints of her volumes become available. She also expanded her range of collaborations with magazines and newspapers, conferences, public speeches, participation in humanitarian activities and new editorial experiences.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Editor-in-chief ===\nHaving been a collaborator with ''Cordelia'' since the first issue, Majocchi assumed the vacant position of editor-in-chief in 1911 after the death of editor [[Ida Baccini]]. She became only the third person to hold that position for the magazine and she made immediate improvements in hopes of improving readership and encouraging her subscribers to become more active readers and writers.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAccording to Bloom, her efforts succeeded.<ref name=\":1\" /><blockquote>\"The magazine, despite its success in its first years of publishing, reached a wider audience over time during the editorship of Ida Baccini and, later, that of Maria Maiocchi Plattis, better known by her pen name, Jolanda. This later success can be attributed to the ability of these two editors to create a recognizable product as well as to the relationship that they managed to establish with their young readers.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> </blockquote>Under Majocchi's leadership, ''Cordelia'' met with \"unusual success\" and by 1913, its subscriber base reached about 10,000, said Bloom.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nShe also took on more philanthropic roles and founded an association to collect books for prisoners. The success of that initiative spurred the formation of other associations and activities, such as making ''Cordelia'' available in [[braille]] to expand its reach to blind patrons. She was also instrumental in creating several conferences.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Death ===\nMajocchi was actively engaged in the education of young female readers until her death in Cento, 8 August 1917.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA street near Cento's city center is named in her honor using several of her names: Via Jolanda Maria Maiocchi Plattis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuttocitta.it/mappa/cento/viale-jolanda-maria-maiocchi-plattis|title=Mappa di Cento - Viale Jolanda Maria Maiocchi Plattis - CAP 44042|website=TuttoCitt\u00e0|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* A critical review of M.'s writings can be found in ''Jolanda: the ideas and the work'', edited by C. Mazzotta, Bologna-Cento, 1999\n\n<br />\n\n* \n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Majocchi, Maria}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian women]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:Women editors]]\n[[Category:People from Cento]]\n[[Category:Italian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Italian magazine publishers (people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maria Majocchi Plattis\n| image              = Maria Majocchi Plattis.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| othername          = Margheritina di Cento, Jolanda,\n\nMarchesa Maria Plattis\n| birth_name         = Maria Majocchi\n| birth_date         = 23 April 1864\n| birth_place        = Cento, Italy\n| death_date         = 8 August 1917\n| death_place        = Cento, Italy\n| burial_place       = \n| nationality        = Italian\n| occupation         = Writer, Journalist, Editor\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| spouse             = Marquis Fernando Plattis\n| children           = Giovan Battista Plattis\n| mother             = Lavinia Agnoletti (1839-1911)\n| father             = Antonio Majocchi (1831-1907)\n| signature          = \n}}\n'''Maria Majocchi''' (sometimes spelled '''Maiocchi''') (Cento, 23 April 1864 - Cento, 8 August 1917), was an Italian writer, journalist and publisher. She wrote under several pseudonyms, often '''Jolanda,''' or more rarely '''Viola d'Alba''' or '''Margheritina di Cento.''' \n\n== Biography ==\n\nMaria was born to the musician and politician Antonio Majocchi (1831-1907), one time mayor of Cento, and his wife Lavinia Agnoletti (1839-1911) who had a rich literary, linguistic and musical background. Maria had at least two sisters, Clementina Laura and Gabriella.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.treccani.it//enciclopedia/maria-majocchi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=MAJOCCHI, Maria in \"Dizionario Biografico\"|website=www.treccani.it|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> \n\nMaria was a writer, journalist and editor. In 1882 she chose to publish using the pseudonym '''Jolanda''', which she borrowed from a character in the opera ''Una Partita a Scacchi (\"A Game of Chess\")'' by [[Giuseppe Giacosa|Giuseppe Giacosa.]]<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Giacosa|first=Giuseppe|url=http://archive.org/details/unapartitascacch00giacuoft|title=Una partita a scacchi, leggenda dramatica in un atto; Il Triomfo d'amore, leggenda drammatica in due atti: Intermezzi e Scene|date=1911|publisher=Milano, Treves|others=Robarts - University of Toronto|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== Writer ===\nMajocchi acquired excellent knowledge of the French language and she subscribed to the Parisian magazine ''Poup\u00e9e mod\u00e8le. A''t 17 years of age, Majocchi was known to be translating its stories from French into Italian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe was also a subscriber to Italian magazines and one in particular attracted her attention: it was ''Cordelia'', conceived in 1881, and directed until 1884, by [[Angelo de Gubernatis|Angelo De Gubernatis]], who would become Maria's lifelong friend and collaborator.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Bloom|first=Karin|date=2017|title=L\u2019affermarsi nell\u2019Italia postunitaria di un nuovo genere editoriale: il caso di Cordelia|url=https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=588427|journal=Italica Wratislaviensia|language=Italian|volume=8|issue=2|pages=37\u201352|issn=2084-4514}}</ref> In its first issue, the editor invited his young readers to send \"a little thing done there\" to the editorial staff for publication.<ref name=\":0\" /> Majocchi responded immediately and, on 12 February 1882, her first poetic sketch, ''Il fior della ventura (The Flower of Fortune)'', was published under her first pseudonym '''Margheritina di Cento'''. From that time on, not yet 20 years old, she became a regular contributor to the magazine, with a fixed starting salary of 5 lire per page. Her signature appeared at the bottom of each piece.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nHer first stories, which were originally published in installments, would be brought together into collections for publication in later years as single volumes: ''Dal mio verziere (From My Orchard), Critical essays'' (Rocca San Casciano, 1896) and ''Le Ignote (The Unknowns)'' (Bologna, 1899).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Married life ===\nAt about the same time, on 8 December 1884, Majocchi married the Marquis Ferdinando Plattis, a young man from [[Padua]] and she moved to [[San Giovanni in Persiceto]]. They had a son named Giovan Battista Plattis, who they called Gino. Writing to De Gubernatis, to whom she was always bound by friendship and deep esteem, she assured him that her collaboration with ''Cordelia'' would not be interrupted because of her marriage. Ferdinando died on 5 May 1893 following a brief illness and economic difficulties forced Majocchi to intensify her writing work. She sent Gino to De Gubernatis for some time so he could continue his studies.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBy the end of the 1800s, she was a widely known author, winning a succession of awards and seeing new editions and reprints of her volumes become available. She also expanded her range of collaborations with magazines and newspapers, conferences, public speeches, participation in humanitarian activities and new editorial experiences.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Editor-in-chief ===\nHaving been a collaborator with ''Cordelia'' since the first issue, Majocchi assumed the vacant position of editor-in-chief in 1911 after the death of editor [[Ida Baccini]]. She became only the third person to hold that position for the magazine and she made immediate improvements in hopes of improving readership and encouraging her subscribers to become more active readers and writers.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAccording to Bloom, her efforts succeeded.<ref name=\":1\" /><blockquote>\"The magazine, despite its success in its first years of publishing, reached a wider audience over time during the editorship of Ida Baccini and, later, that of Maria Maiocchi Plattis, better known by her pen name, Jolanda. This later success can be attributed to the ability of these two editors to create a recognizable product as well as to the relationship that they managed to establish with their young readers.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> </blockquote>Under Majocchi's leadership, ''Cordelia'' met with \"unusual success\" and by 1913, its subscriber base reached about 10,000, said Bloom.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nShe also took on more philanthropic roles and founded an association to collect books for prisoners. The success of that initiative spurred the formation of other associations and activities, such as making ''Cordelia'' available in [[braille]] to expand its reach to blind patrons. She was also instrumental in creating several conferences.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Death ===\nMajocchi was actively engaged in the education of young female readers until her death in Cento, 8 August 1917.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA street near Cento's city center is named in her honor using several of her names: Via Jolanda Maria Maiocchi Plattis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuttocitta.it/mappa/cento/viale-jolanda-maria-maiocchi-plattis|title=Mappa di Cento - Viale Jolanda Maria Maiocchi Plattis - CAP 44042|website=TuttoCitt\u00e0|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* A critical review of M.'s writings can be found in ''Jolanda: the ideas and the work'', edited by C. Mazzotta, Bologna-Cento, 1999\n\n<br />\n\n* \n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Majocchi, Maria}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1917 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian women]]\n[[Category:19th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:Women editors]]\n[[Category:Italian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Italian magazine publishers (people)]]\n", "name_user": "AMM Pittsburgh", "label": "safe", "comment": "added category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Majocchi"}
{"title_page": "Flag of China", "text_new": "{{About|the flag of the People's Republic of China since its creation in 1949|the flag of the Republic of China since 1921|Flag of the Republic of China|other uses|Flag of China (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox flag\n|Name = People's Republic of China\n|Article = the\n|Nickname = ''W\u01d4x\u012bng H\u00f3ngq\u00ed'' (\"Five-starred Red Flag\")\n|Image = Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg\n|Use = 110110\n|Symbol = \n|Proportion = 2:3\n|Adoption = 27 September 1949<ref name=\"CPC news\">{{cite web |url = http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64165/70293/70320/4861365.html |script-title = zh:1949\u5e749\u670827\u65e5 \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u65d7\u8bde\u751f |trans-title = 27 September 1949: The Birth of PRC's Flag |website = CPC News |access-date = 4 November 2009 |language = zh-Hans }}</ref>\n|Designer = [[Zeng Liansong]]\n|Design = A large golden star within an arc of four smaller golden stars, in the canton, on a field of [[Chinese red]]. \n|Image2 = \n|Nickname2 = \n|Imagetext2 = \n|Morenicks2 = \n|Use2 = \n|Symbol2 = \n|Proportion2 = \n|Adoption2 = \n|Design2 = \n|Designer2 = \n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title = Flag of China\n|order = st\n|s = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u56fd|\u56fd\u65d7}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u570b|\u570b\u65d7}}\n|l = State flag of China\n|w = Chungkuo kuoch'i\n|p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 gu\u00f3q\u00ed\n|y = Z\u00f9ngw\u00f3k gw\u00f3kkei\n|xej = \ufe9f\u0652\ufeee \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \u0686\u0650\n|bpmf = \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311bChina\u2019s stupid dictator let the Chinese virus spread and kill thousands of people\n|s2 = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd|\u56fd\u65d7}}\n|t2 = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b|\u570b\u65d7}}\n|l2 = State flag of the People's Republic of China\n|w2 = Chunghua Jenmin Kunghokuo kuoch'i\n|p2 = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 gu\u00f3q\u00ed\n|y2 = Z\u00f9ngf\u00e0a J\u00e0nman G\u00f9ngwogw\u00f3k gw\u00f3kkei\n|xej2 = \ufe9f\u0652\ufeee \ufea7\u064f\ufeee\u064e \u0698\u064c \u0645\u064d \ufed7\u0652\ufeee \u062d\u0652 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \u0686\u0650\n|bpmf2 = \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u00b4 \u3116\u3123\u00b4 \u3107\u3127\u3123\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u3125` \u310f\u311c\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u3111\u3127\u00b4\n|altname3 = Five-star Red Flag\n|s3 = {{linktext|\u4e94|\u661f|\u7ea2|\u65d7}}\n|t3 = {{linktext|\u4e94|\u661f|\u7d05|\u65d7}}\n|p3 = W\u01d4 x\u012bng h\u00f3ng q\u00ed\n|xej3 = \u0621\u064f \u0633\u064d \ufea1\u0652\ufeee \u0686\u0650\n|y3 = Ngh s\u00e8ng g\u00f9ng kei\n}}\n\nThe '''flag of China''', officially the '''National Flag of the People's Republic of China''' and also known as the '''Five-starred Red Flag''',<ref>{{cite book |author1 = \u9a6c\u5168\u6d32 |author2 = \u5468\u51ef\u519b |title = Stories About the National Flag, Emblem and Anthem | publisher = People's Liberation Army Publishing House | date = 2009-04-01 | location = Beijing, China | page = 1 |isbn = 978-7-5065-5729-0 }}</ref> is a [[Vermilion#Chinese red|Chinese red]] field [[charge (heraldry)|charged]] in the [[Glossary of vexillology#Flag elements|canton]] (upper corner nearest the flagpole) with five golden [[Five-pointed star|stars]]. The design features one large star, with four smaller stars in a semicircle set off towards the fly (the side farthest from the flag pole). The red represents the [[Chinese Communist Revolution|revolution]]; the five stars and their relationship represent the unity of the [[Chinese people]] under the leadership of the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC).  The first flag was hoisted by the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA) on a pole overlooking Beijing's [[Tiananmen Square]] on 1 October 1949, at a ceremony announcing the establishment of the [[People's Republic of China]].\n\nOther flags used in the People's Republic use a red background to symbolize the revolution in conjunction with other symbols. The flag of the [[People's Liberation Army]] uses the gold star with the Chinese characters 8-1 (for 1 August, the date of the PLA's founding). The flag of the [[Communist Party of China]] replaces all of the stars with the party emblem. Due to government regulations, cities and provinces of China cannot have their own flags; the only sub-national flags that exist are those of the [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]]. However, this law was defied when the cities of [[Kaifeng]] and [[Shangrao]] adopted their flags in March 2006 and March 2009 respectively.\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Flag of the Qing dynasty|Flag of the Republic of China}}\n\n===Early flags===\n[[File:Flag_of_China_(1862\u20131889).svg|alt=Flag of the Qing Dynasty|thumb|[[Flag of the Qing Dynasty]]]]\n\nOne of the first earlier flags of China was the \"[[Yellow Dragon Flag]]\" used by the [[Qing dynasty]] from 1862 until the overthrow of the monarchy during the Xinhai Revolution.  The Qing dynasty was the last imperial dynasty in China's history. The flag that was adopted in 1862 was triangular, but the dynasty adopted a rectangular version of the dragon flag in 1889.\n\n===Republic of China===\n[[File:Flag of the Republic of China.svg|alt=Flag of the Republic of China|thumb|[[Flag of the Republic of China]]]]\n\nThe [[Flag terminology|canton]] (upper corner on the hoist side) originated from the \"[[Blue Sky with a White Sun|Blue Sky with a White Sun flag]]\" ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u9752\u5929|\u767d\u65e5|\u65d7}}|p=q\u012bngti\u0101n b\u00e1ir\u00ec q\u00ed|labels=no}}) designed by [[Lu Haodong]], a martyr of the [[Xinhai Revolution]]. He presented his design to represent the revolutionary army at the inauguration of the [[Society for Regenerating China]], an [[Anti-Qing sentiment|anti-Qing]] society in [[Hong Kong]], on 21 February 1895. This design was later adopted as the KMT party flag and the [[Coat of Arms of the Republic of China]]. The \"red Earth\" portion was added by [[Sun Yat-sen]] in winter of 1906, bringing the flag to its modern form. According to [[George Yeo]], the Foreign Minister of Singapore, in those days the Blue Sky with a White Sun flag was sewn in the Sun Yat Sen Villa or [[Wan Qing Yuan]] in Singapore by Teo Eng Hock and his wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.mfa.gov.sg/pr/read_content.asp?View,15231,|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610153714/http://app.mfa.gov.sg/pr/read_content.asp?View,15231,|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2011|title=MFA Press Release Admin Page|date=10 June 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wanqingyuan.com.sg/english/onceupon/spsupp.html Dr Sun & 1911 Revolution: Teo Eng Hock (1871\u20131957)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126010654/http://wanqingyuan.com.sg/english/onceupon/spsupp.html |date=2009-11-26 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Wuchang Uprising]] in 1911 that heralded the Republic, the various revolutionary armies had different flags. Lu Hao-tung's \"Blue Sky with a White Sun\" flag was used in the provinces of [[Guangdong]], [[Guangxi]], [[Yunnan]], and [[Guizhou]]. In [[Wuhan]], a flag with 18 yellow stars was used to represent the 18 [[history of the political divisions of China|administrative divisions]] at the time. In [[Shanghai]] and northern China, a \"Five-Colored Flag\" ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u4e94\u8272|\u65d7}}|p=w\u01d4 s\u00e8 q\u00ed|labels=no}}) ([[Five Races Under One Union]] flag) was used of five horizontal stripes representing the five major [[nationalities of China]]: the [[Han Chinese|Han]] (red), the [[Manchu]] (yellow), the [[Mongol]] (blue), the [[Hui Chinese|Hui]] (white), and the [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]] (black).\n\nWhen the government of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] was established on January 1, 1912, the \"Five-Colored Flag\" was selected by the provisional Senate as the national flag. The [[:File:Chinese-Army-Wuhan-Flag-1911-1928 dots18.svg|\"18-Star Flag\"]] was adopted by the army<ref name=\"army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aiplus.idv.tw/soviet/FARMY.HTM |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u6b77\u4ee3\u9678\u8ecd\u65d7\u5e5f |accessdate=2008-12-26 |last=Yu-liang |first=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language=Chinese }}</ref> and the modern flag was adopted as a naval ensign.<ref name=\"navy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aiplus.idv.tw/soviet/FNAVY.HTM |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u6b77\u4ee3\u6d77\u8ecd\u65d7\u5e5f |accessdate=2007-12-11 |last=Yu-liang |first=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language=Chinese }}</ref> Sun Yat-sen, however, did not consider the five-colored flag appropriate, reasoning that horizontal order implied a hierarchy or class like that which existed during dynastic times.\n\nAfter President [[Yuan Shikai]] assumed [[Dictatorship|dictatorial powers]] in 1913 by dissolving the [[National Assembly of the Republic of China|National Assembly]] and outlawing the KMT, Sun Yat-sen established a government-in-exile in [[Tokyo]] and employed the modern flag as the national ROC flag. He continued using this design when the KMT established a [[Government of the Republic of China in Guangzhou|rival government]] in [[Guangzhou]] in 1917. The modern flag was made the official national flag on December 17, 1928 after the successful [[Northern Expedition (1926\u20131927)|Northern Expedition]] that overthrew the [[Beiyang government|Beijing government]], though the Five-Colored Flag still continued to be used by locals in an unofficial capacity. One reason for this discrepancy in use was lingering regional biases held by officials and citizens of northern China, who favored the Five-Colored Flag, against southerners such as the [[Guangdong|Cantonese]]/Hakka Sun Yat-sen.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nDuring [[the Second Sino-Japanese War]], the invading [[Japan]]ese established a [[Japanese puppet states|variety of puppet governments]] using several flag designs. The \"[[Reformed Government of the Republic of China|Reform Government]]\" established in March 1938 in [[Nanjing]] to consolidate the various puppet governments employed the Five-Colored Flag. When [[Wang Jingwei]] was slated to take over the [[Reorganized National Government of the Republic of China|Japanese-installed government in Nanjing]] in 1940, he demanded to use the modern flag as a means to challenge the authority of the [[Nationalist Government]] in [[Chongqing]] under [[Chiang Kai-shek]] and position himself as the rightful successor to Sun Yat-sen. However, the Japanese preferred the Five-Colored flag. As a compromise, the Japanese suggested adding a triangular yellow pennant on top with the slogan \"Peace, Anti-Communism, National Construction\" ({{zh|t=\u548c\u5e73\u53cd\u5171\u5efa\u570b|p=H\u00e9p\u00edng f\u01ceng\u00f2ng ji\u00e0n gu\u00f3|labels=no}}) in black, but this was rejected by Wang. In the end, Wang and the Japanese agreed that the yellow banner was to be used outdoors only, until 1943 when the banner was abandoned, leaving two rival governments with the same flag, each claiming to be the legitimate National Government of China.<ref>{{cite journal\n |first=Andrew \n |last=Cheung \n |title=Slogans, Symbols, and Legitimacy: The Case of Wang Jingwei's Nanjing Regime \n |version=Working paper \n |publisher=East Asian Working Paper Series on Language and Politics in Modern China \n |year=1995 \n |url = http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/working_paper/noframe_6a_sloga.htm \n |access-date=24 July 2008 \n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080226023546/http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/working_paper/noframe_6a_sloga.htm \n |archive-date=26 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nThe flag was specified in Article Six of the [[Constitution of the Republic of China|1947 Constitution]]. After the [[Chinese Civil War]] in 1949, the ROC government led by Chiang Kai-shek relocated its government and its institutions to the island of [[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]]. On the [[mainland China|mainland]], the communist forces of [[Mao Zedong]] established the [[People's Republic of China (PRC)]] and adopted their own national flag. On October 23, 1954, the National Emblem and National Flag of the Republic of China Act ({{zh|t={{linktext|\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b|\u570b\u5fbd|\u570b\u65d7\u6cd5}} |p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 gu\u00f3hu\u012b gu\u00f3q\u00edf\u01ce|labels=no}}) was promulgated by the [[Legislative Yuan]] to specify the size, measure, ratio, production, and management of the flag.<ref name=\"1954law\">{{cite web |url = http://www.globalflag.idv.tw/wg/gqf.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u570b\u5fbd\u570b\u65d7\u6cd5 |access-date=2008-12-26 |first=Yu-liang |last=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language= zh-TW }}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\n[[File:Zeng Liansong's proposal for the PRC flag.svg|thumb|alt=A red flag with four small golden stars and one giant gold star at the top left corner. In the giant gold star, a red crossed hammer and sickle is placed in the center.|The original design submitted by Zeng Liansong]]\n\nOn July 4, 1949, the sixth working group of the Preparatory Committee of the New Political Consultative Conference ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703}}, PCNPCC) created a notice to submit designs for the national flag. After a few changes, the notice was published in the papers ''[[People's Daily]]'', ''Beiping Liberation News'', ''Xinmin News'', ''Dazhong Daily'', ''[[Guangming Daily (China)|Guangming Daily]]'', ''Jinbu Daily'' and ''Tianjin Daily'' during the period July 15\u201326.<ref name=\"gov news\">{{cite web |url = http://gov.people.com.cn/GB/46743/4889273.html |title=Creation of the Flag, Emblem and Anthem of the People's Republic of China |date=2006-10-08|access-date=2009-11-05 |language= zh-CN |website = Chinese Government News |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081013052258/http://gov.people.com.cn/GB/46743/4889273.html |archive-date=2008-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The list of requirements for the national flag were also posted in the notice:\n# Chinese characteristics (geography, nationality, history, culture, etc.);\n# Power characteristics (people's democratic government, led by the working class and based on the worker-peasant alliance);\n# The shape should be rectangular and the length-breadth ratio should be 3:2;\n# The color should mainly be bright red<ref>{{cite web |url = http://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703\u7232\u5fb5\u6c42\u570b\u65d7\u570b\u5fbd\u5716\u6848\u53ca\u570b\u6b4c\u8fad\u8b5c\u5553\u4e8b |script-title = zh:\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703\u7232\u5fb5\u6c42\u570b\u65d7\u570b\u5fbd\u5716\u6848\u53ca\u570b\u6b4c\u8fad\u8b5c\u5553\u4e8b |trans-title = Notice to Solicit Designs of the National Flag, Emblem and Anthem |author=PCNPCC |date=1949-07-10 |access-date=2009-11-05 |website=Wikisource |language=zh-Hant }}</ref> (an early draft of the notice had the color as dark red, but this was changed to bright red by [[Zhou Enlai]]).<ref name=\"kong\" />\n\n[[File:Mao Zedong's proposal for the PRC flag.svg|thumb|The \"[[Yellow River]]\" flag design originally preferred by [[Mao Zedong]].]]\n[[Zeng Liansong]], a citizen from [[Wenzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], was working in Shanghai at the time the announcement came out; he wanted to create a flag design to express his patriotic enthusiasm for the new country. In the middle of July, he sat down in his attic over several nights to come up with designs. His inspiration for the current design came from the stars shining in the night sky. He thought of a Chinese proverb \"longing for the stars, longing for the moon\", ({{lang|zh|\u76fc\u661f\u661f\u76fc\u6708\u4eae}}, ''p\u00e0n x\u012bngx\u012bng p\u00e0n yu\u00e8li\u00e0ng'') which shows yearning. He viewed the CPC as the great saviour ({{lang|zh|\u5927\u6551\u661f}}, ''d\u00e0 ji\u00f9x\u012bng'' \"great saving star\") of the Chinese people, represented by a larger star. The idea for four small stars came from [[On the People's Democratic Dictatorship]], a speech by Mao Zedong, which defined the Chinese people as consisting of four [[social class]]es, also referred to in Asian cultures as the [[four occupations]] ({{lang|zh|\u58eb\u8fb2\u5de5\u5546}}) ''shi, nong, gong, shang'' (\"the working class, the peasantry, the urban petty bourgeoisie and the national bourgeoisie\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-4/mswv4_65.htm|title=On the People's Democratic Dictatorship : In Commemoration of the Twenty-eighth Anniversary of the Communist Party of China, June 30, 1949|accessdate=2017-09-27}}</ref>).  The color yellow implies that China belongs to the Chinese people, a \"[[yellow race]]\".<ref name=\"kong\"/> After working out the details of the placement of the stars and their sizes (he had tried to put all of the stars in the center, but believed it would be too heavy and dull), he sent his \"Five Stars on a Field of Red\" ({{lang|zh|\u7d05\u5730\u4e94\u661f\u65d7}}, ''h\u00f3ng d\u00ec w\u01d4x\u012bng q\u00ed'') design to the committee in the middle of August.<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref name=\"kong\"/>\n\nBy August 20, a between 2,992<ref name=\"design_participation\"/> and 3,012<ref name=\"govprcflag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.cn/test/2005-05/24/content_18247.htm|title=National Flag of the People's Republic of China|publisher=Gov.cn|date=2005-05-24|access-date=2009-11-08|language=Chinese}}</ref> designs had been sent to the flag committee,<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/82819/121799/121806/7185220.html|chapter=2, Work of the Preparatory Committee of the New Political Consultative Conference (4)|title=1948\u20132008, Let history tell the future \u2013 the CPC Central Committee issued \"51 slogan\" 60 anniversary |url = http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/82819/121799/index.html|publisher=China Publishing House|editor1-first=Weiqun |editor1-last=Zhu|isbn=978-7-5075-2294-5|year=2008|language=zh-CN }}</ref> including input from committee members themselves such as [[Guo Moruo]] and [[Tan Kah Kee]].<ref name=\"design_participation\">{{cite news|url=http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/85040/9850276.html|title=The National People's active participation in the design within 1 month of flag design up to 2992 candidates|author=Chen, Yu|website=CPC News|date=2009-08-13|access-date=2009-11-05|language=Chinese}}</ref> From August 16 to 20, the designs were viewed at the [[Beijing Hotel]] and culled down to a list of 38.<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref name=\"gov news\" /> These designs are collected into a book named ''A Reference of National Flag Designs'' ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u570b\u65d7\u5716\u6848\u53c3\u8003\u8cc7\u6599}}). This book was then submitted to the newly established [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]] (CPPCC) for further discussion. However, Zeng's design was not included until [[Tian Han]] nominated it again.<ref name=\"\u56fd\u65d7\u662f\u600e\u6837\u8bde\u751f\u7684\">{{cite news |url = http://www.gmw.cn/01wzb/1999-07/22/GB/wzb%5E1664%5E6%5EWZ3-2210.htm |title=How Was The National Flag Created? |publisher=Digest News |date=1999-07-22 |access-date=2009-11-06 |last=Bai |first = Zhi |language= zh }}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of September 23, the representatives of the CPPCC discussed the national flags, but came to no conclusion. Some disliked the symbolism which Zeng attached to the four smaller stars, and said it should not include the bourgeoisie. The design Mao and others liked had a giant golden star in the corner on a red flag that was charged with a golden horizontal bar. But this design was strongly opposed by [[Zhang Zhizhong]], who saw the golden bar as symbolizing the tearing apart of the revolution from the country.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/8798903.html|title=Zhang Zhizhong and the Birth of the 5 Star Red Flag |date=2009-02-13|access-date=2009-11-05|last=Tian |first = Shuhe |website = CPC News|language= zh-CN }}</ref> That night, Peng Guanghan ({{lang|zh|\u5f6d\u5149\u6db5}}) recommended Zeng's design to [[Zhou Enlai]]. Zhou was satisfied with it and asked for a larger copy of the design to be made. Tan Kah Kee also gave his advice to Mao and Zhou that the power characteristics are more important than Chinese geography characteristics, so there was no need to insist on the golden bar which stands for the [[Yellow River]]. Two days later, Mao had a meeting in his office about the flag. He persuaded everyone to adopt Zeng's design, with some slight modifications.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Witnesses to the Birth of the National Flag|author=Peng Guanghan|journal=At Home and Overseas|publisher=The All-China Federation of returned overseas Chinese and overseas Chinese|location=Beijing|issn=1002-3801|date=March 2003|language=Chinese}}</ref> According to earlier discussions at the Beijing Hotel, the [[hammer and sickle]] from Zeng's original design was removed since it was similar to the [[Flag of the Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"\u56fd\u65d7\u662f\u600e\u6837\u8bde\u751f\u7684\"/> On September 27, 1949, Zeng's modified design was selected unanimously by the First Plenary Session of CPPCC, which changed the flag's name to \"Five-star Red Flag\".<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/85039/10163392.html|title=Peng Han: the tortuous process of the flag's birth|author=Wang Jianzhu|date=2009-10-09|publisher=CPC News|accessdate=2009-11-05|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The first flag of China.jpg|thumbnail|[[Mao Zedong]] pressed the button and raised the flag of China for the first time in the announcement of the establishment of the People's Republic of China at [[Tiananmen Square]] on October 1, 1949]]\nOn September 29, the new flag was published in the [[People's Daily]], so the design could be copied by other local authorities.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=People's Daily|url=http://images.china.cn/attachement/jpg/site1000/20090929/000802ab801d0c2c17a32d.jpg|language=Chinese|format=Image|date=1949-09-29|volume=466|page=1|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> The flag was officially unveiled in Beijing's [[Tiananmen Square]] on October 1, 1949, at the formal announcement of the establishment of the [[People's Republic of China]]. The first flag flown over Tiananmen Square was sewn together by Zhao Wenrui ({{lang|zh|\u8d75\u6587\u745e}}), a seamstress who finished the task around 1{{Nbsp}}pm on September 30.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://2008.qq.com/a/20080807/000443.htm|title=The first one who stitched the flag of The People's Republic of China \u2013 Zhao Wenrui|date=2008-08-07|accessdate=2009-11-06|publisher=QQ.com|language=Chinese}}</ref> Zeng had a hard time believing that his design was picked, due to the missing hammer and sickle from the giant star. However, he was officially congratulated by the General Office of the Central People's Government as the designer of the flag and received 5 million yuan for his work.<ref name=\"kong\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbw.com/btm/issue71/62-63.html |title=The Worker Who Forged the Red Flag |accessdate=2009-11-03 |last=Kong |first=Mark |date=1999-10-01 |work=Beijing This Month |publisher=Chinese Business World |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211184343/http://www.cbw.com/btm/issue71/62-63.html |archivedate=February 11, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hantailun\">{{cite book|title=Witnessed the Tiananmen Square|volume=3|author=Han Tailun|isbn=978-7-224-05364-7|location=Xi'an|publisher=Shaanxi People's Publishing House|year=2000|page=2066|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"140\" caption=\"Rejected designs of the Five-star Red Flag\">\nFile:Proposal 2 for the PRC flag.svg|\nFile:Proposal 3 for the PRC flag.svg|\nFile:Proposal 4 for the PRC flag.svg|\n</gallery><gallery widths=\"140\" caption=\"Other rejected proposed designs\">\nFile:Proposed PRC national flags 006.svg |Proposal by [[Wu Yuzhang]]\nFile:Proposed-PRC-10.svg |Proposal by [[Ai Qing]]\nFile:Proposed PRC national flag 014.svg |Proposal by [[Zhu De]]\nFile:Proposed PRC national flag 015.svg |Proposal by [[Liang Congjie]]\nFile:Proposed PRC flag (Design 8, Guo Moruo).svg |Proposal by [[Guo Moruo]]\nFile:Guo Moruo's Proposal Flag for the PRC.svg |Proposal by [[Guo Moruo]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Symbolism ==\n[[File:Chinese flag (Beijing) - IMG 1104.jpg|thumb|right|Flag of China, Beijing]]\n\nAccording to the current government interpretation of the flag, the red background symbolises the revolution and the golden colors were used to \"radiate\" on the red background though each of the colors represents  one of the [[Color in Chinese culture|Five Elements]] of fire and earth. The five stars and their relationship represents the unity of Chinese people under the leadership of the [[Communist Party of China]]. The orientation of the stars shows that the unity should go around a center.<ref name=\"govprcflag\" /> In the original description of the flag by Zeng, the larger star symbolizes the Communist Party of China, and the four smaller stars that surround the big star symbolize the four social classes (the [[working class]], the [[peasant]]ry, the urban [[petite bourgeoisie]] and the national [[bourgeoisie]]) of China's [[New Democracy]] mentioned in Mao's \"[[On the People's Democratic Dictatorship]]\". <!-- http://www.lishiyushehui.cn/modules/topic/downloads.php?id=218 I need to make the full cite of this, but don't have time right now. --> The five stars that formed an ellipse represent the territory of China which is shaped like a [[Begonia]] leaf. It is sometimes stated that the five stars of the flag represent the five largest ethnic groups: [[Han Chinese]], [[Zhuang people|Zhuang]]s, [[Hui people|Hui Chinese]], [[Manchu people|Manchu]]s and [[Uyghur people|Uyghur]]s.<ref name=\"Shambaugh\">{{cite journal|last=Shambaugh|first=David |date=June 1994|title=Book reviews|journal=The China Quarterly|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press|CUP]] for [[School of Oriental and African Studies|SOAS]]|issue= 138|pages=517\u2013520|doi=10.1017/S0305741000035876 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mayall|first=James|others=ed. Richard W. Bulliet|title=The Columbia History of the 20th Century|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|year=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/columbiahistoryo0000unse/page/186 186]|chapter=Nationalism|isbn=0-231-07628-2|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/columbiahistoryo0000unse/page/186}}</ref> This is generally regarded as an erroneous conflation with the [[Five Races Under One Union|\"Five Races Under One Union\" flag]], used 1912\u201328 by the [[Beiyang Government]] of [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]], whose different-colored stripes represented the Han Chinese, Hui Chinese, Manchus, [[Mongols]] and [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]].<ref name=\"Shambaugh\"/><ref name=\"Zarrow\">{{cite book|last=Zarrow|first=Peter Gue |title=China in War and Revolution, 1895\u20131949|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2005|pages=363|chapter=Revolution and Civil War|isbn=0-415-36448-5}}</ref>\n\n== Construction details, sizes and colors ==\nThe construction sheet for the national flag was published on September 28, 1949 by an order from the Presidium of the First Plenary Session of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]].<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zjswb.gov.cn/zjswbcms/view/en/news.jsp?unid=74DA037561CEAB31AF98BE644285D160 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707043738/http://www.zjswb.gov.cn/zjswbcms/view/en/news.jsp?unid=74DA037561CEAB31AF98BE644285D160 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-07 |title=Law About The National Flag of the People's Republic of China |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=1990-10-01 |publisher=Zhejiang Provincial Foreign Affairs Office }} [[:zh:s:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u65d7\u6cd5|in Chinese]]</ref> The information can also be found in the document \"[[List of GB standards|GB]] 12982-2004: National flag\" that was released by the [[Standardization Administration of China]].<ref name=\"standards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sac.gov.cn/SACSearch/search?channelid=160591&templet=gjcxjg_detail.jsp&searchword=STANDARD_CODE='12982'&XZ=T |language=zh-cn|script-title=zh:\u56fd\u5bb6\u6807\u51c6\u59d4\u6807\u51c6\u5236\u4fee\u8ba2\u7ba1\u7406\u7cfb\u7edf|website=www.sac.gov.cn}}</ref> \n{{-}}\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Construction sheet\n! Standard\n|-\n|[[File:Construction sheet of Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|400px]]\n|\n#The flag is split into 4 sections, with the top hoist part of the flag being a grid of 15 by 10 units. \n#The centre of the biggest star is placed at 5 units from the hoist and 5 units from the top of the flag. The diameter of the biggest star's [[circumscribed circle]] is 6 units.\n#Of the 4 smaller stars, the first one is centred 2 units from the top of the flag, 10 units from the hoist; the second one is centred 4 units from the top of the flag and 12 units from the hoist; the third one is centred 7 units from the top of the flag and 12 units from the hoist; the fourth one is centred 9 units from the top of the flag and 10 units from the hoist. \n#The diameter of each small star's [[circumscribed circle]] is 2 units. Each of the top points of the 4 smaller stars are rotated such that they point towards the center point of the larger star.<ref name=\"chinaflagcon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/spec.html |title= Specifications for the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=2005-11-06 |publisher=Protocol Division, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government of the People's Republic of China }}</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], flags that failed to adhere to the regulations were used in connection with China. The flags, used during the opening ceremony and two medal ceremonies, featured the four small stars incorrectly angled in the same direction, inciting fury at the Olympic organisers.<ref>{{cite news |last= Gajanan|first=Mahita  |date=9 August 2016 |title= Olympic Officials Apologize to China for Using the Wrong Flag|url=http://time.com/4445373/rio-2016-olympics-china-wrong-flags/ |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |location= |access-date=22 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Law on the National Flag mentions five possible sizes that could be made for the national flag:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/standard.html |title= Standard Sizes of the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=2005-11-06 |publisher=Protocol Division, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government of the People's Republic of China }}</ref> According to Article 4 of the Law On the National Flag, people's governments of provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the Central Government are directed to authorize companies to make any copy of the national flag.<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\"/> Besides five official sizes for flying on flagpoles, there are another four smaller sizes for other purposes, such as decoration on cars or display in meeting rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.qizhi147.com/nd.jsp?id=13 |language=zh-cn|script-title=zh:\u56fd\u65d7\u7684\u6807\u51c6\u5c3a\u5bf8\u548c\u56fd\u65d7\u6bcf\u4e2a\u5c3a\u5bf8\u7684\u7528\u9014\u4ecb\u7ecd |publisher=Shanghai Yingfeng Flag Co. Ltd |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Size !!1 !!2 !!3 !!4 !!5 !!6 !!7 !!8 !!9\n|-\n|Length \u00d7 width (cm)\n|| 288&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;192|| 240&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;160|| 192&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;128|| 144&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;96|| 96&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;64|| 66&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;44|| 45&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;30|| 30&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;20|| 21&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;14\n|}\n</center>\n\n=== Colours ===\nThe colours of the national flag are regulated in the document \"GB 12983-2004: Standard Color Sample of the National Flag,\" also released by the Standardization Administration of China. The colors are in the CIE [[Standard illuminant]] D65 and the [[CIE 1964 color space|CIE 1964 Supplementary Standard Colorimetric System]].<ref name=\"flagcolor\">{{cite web |url=http://cnc.zhaobz.com/gb/a/4/zhaobzgb3024coo.rar  |script-title=zh:GB 12983-2004 \u56fd\u65d7\u989c\u8272\u6807\u51c6\u6837\u54c1 |trans-title=Standard Color Sample of the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-02 |year=2004 |format=PDF |publisher=Standardization Administration of China |language=Chinese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813212810/http://cnc.zhaobz.com/gb/a/4/zhaobzgb3024coo.rar |archivedate=2011-08-13 }}</ref>\n{|class = \"wikitable\" width=80%\n|+Standard color sample of the national flag<ref name=\"flagcolor\" />\n|-\n! rowspan=2 colspan=2 | Fabric\n! rowspan=2 | Stimulus value ''Y''<sub>10</sub>\n! colspan=2 | Color coordinate\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Allowable error margin\n|-\n! ''x''<sub>10</sub> !! ''y''<sub>10</sub>\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Synthetic fiber]]\n! Red\n|| 9.4 || 0.555 ||0.328\n| rowspan=6 | All are<br /><math>\\Delta E_{ab}^{\\,\\bullet}\\le 2.0</math>\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 41.2 || 0.446 || 0.489\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Silk]]\n! Red\n|| 12.3 || 0.565 || 0.325\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 32.4 || 0.450 || 0.463\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Cotton cloth]]\n! Red\n|| 9.2 || 0.595 || 0.328\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 33.0 || 0.467 || 0.463\n|-\n! Sleeve !! White\n|| 78.0 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||The stimulus value ''Y''<sub>10</sub> must not be less than 78\n|}\n\n==== Colours scheme ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n![[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|30px]]\n! style=\"background:#de2910ff; width:200px\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span>\n! style=\"background:#ffde00ff; width:200px\" | Gold\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" | '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''\n| <code>222/41/16</code> || <code>255/222/0</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" | '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''\n| <code>#de2910ff</code> || <code>#ffde00ff</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" |'''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''\n| <code>0/82/93/13</code> || <code>0/13/100/0</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" |'''[[Pantone]]''' (approximate)\n| 485 C || Yellow C\n|}\n\n===Unicode===\nThe Flag of China is represented as the [[Unicode]] [[emoji]] sequence {{unichar|1F1E8|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER C}} and {{unichar|1F1F3|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER N}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://emojipedia.org/flag-for-china/|title=\ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddf3 Flag for China Emoji|access-date=2018-05-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Regulations ==\n{{Wikisource|Law About The National Flag of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe current law about the national flag was passed by 14th Meeting of the Standing Committee of the Seventh National People's Congress on June 28, 1990 and was enforced starting October 1, 1990. The main point of the law was to not only set down regulations on how to make the Chinese flag, what it looks like, where it can be flown and how it can be flown. The law also stresses that the national flag is \"the symbol and hallmark of the People's Republic of China\" and that everyone \"shall respect and care for the National Flag.\"<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\"/>\n\n===Folding the flag===\n# Fold horizontally along the center.\n# Repeat, fold horizontally along the centre.\n# Fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the top\n\n===Desecration===\n{{also|Flag desecration#China}}\n[[File:\u9999\u6e2f\u4e4b\u8def 01.jpg|thumb|Desecrated flag]]\nAccording to [[Radio Free Asia]], in January 2014 after [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] residents were reportedly forced to bow to a flag of China before worshipping at Xaniqa mosque in Yengimehelle township, [[Xayar County]], [[Aksu Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang]], three Uyghur youths burned the flag. Raids on Uyghur homes searching for the youths continued into 2015. Authorities warned residents not to discuss the flagburning incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/police-conduct-raids-in-shayar-county-04162015140703.html|title=Police Conduct Raids in Xinjiang a Year After Flag Burning at Mosque|date=16 April 2015|accessdate=26 April 2020|website=Radio Free Asia|authors=[[Shohret Hoshur]], Roseanne Gerin|translator=Shohret Hoshur}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September 2017, Hong Kong elected legislator [[Cheng Chung-tai]] was convicted of desecrating the flag under the National Flag and National Emblem Ordinance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hklii.org/eng/hk/legis/instrument/A401/|title=Hong Kong Constitutional Instruments|website=Hong Kong Legal Information Institute|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>  He had been seen turning representations of the flags (not of standard dimensions) upside down in the legislative chamber in October the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/09/29/breaking-civic-passion-lawmaker-cheng-chung-tai-found-guilty-desecrating-flags-legislative-session/|title=Civic Passion lawmaker Cheng Chung-tai found guilty of 'desecrating' flags during legislative session|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|date=29 September 2017|last=Cheung|first=Karen|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Flags of the Special Administrative Regions of the People's Republic of China==\n{{Main|Flag of Hong Kong|Flag of Macau}}\n[[File:Flag_flying_protocol_of_Hong_Kong_SAR_and_PRC.svg|right|345px|thumb|The regional flag (Hong Kong) displayed with national flag.]]\nDue to an order passed by the CPC Central Committee General Office and General Office of the State Council, cities and provinces are no longer allowed to adopt their own symbols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u4e2d\u5171\u4e2d\u592e\u529e\u516c\u5385\u3001\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u529e\u516c\u5385\u5173\u4e8e\u7981\u6b62\u81ea\u884c\u5236\u4f5c\u548c\u4f7f\u7528\u5730\u65b9\u65d7\u3001\u5fbd\u7684\u901a\u77e5 |title=CPC Central Committee and State Council Notice On the Prohibition of the Creation and Use of Civic Flags |accessdate=2009-11-08 |date=1997-11-18 |publisher=Wikisource }}</ref> However, both of the Hong Kong and [[Macau]] [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]] of China have their own special flags. The precise use of the SAR flags are regulated by laws passed by the [[National People's Congress]].<ref name=\"hongkong_flag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com.cn/zgrdxw/faguiku/dff/F50-1060.html|title=Decision of the Hong Kong SAR Flag|author=[[Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]]|website=People.com.cn|date=1996-08-11|access-date=2009-11-22|language=zh}}</ref><ref name=\"macau_flag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.china.com.cn/law/flfg/txt/2006-08/08/content_7064255.htm|title=Law Regarding The Flag and Emblem of the Hong Kong SAR|publisher=China.com.cn|work=Preparatory Committee for the Macau Special Administrative Region|date=1999-01-16|access-date=2009-11-22|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nThe Flag of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region features a stylized, white, five-petal ''[[Bauhinia blakeana]]'' flower in the center of a red field. On each petal is a red star; the stars are supposed to demonstrate that Hong Kong residents love their motherland while the overall flag design signifies the link re-established between post-colonial Hong Kong and China while demonstrating the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" political principle applied to the region.<ref name=\"symbolism\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BmCFznufJ54C&pg=PA582&lpg=PA582#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=International Law Reports|volume=122|year=2002|page=582|access-date=2009-11-01|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-80775-3 |author1=Elihu Lauterpacht |author2=C. J. Greenwood |author3=A. G. Oppenheimer }}</ref><ref name=\"reflection\">{{cite web|url=http://info.news365.com.cn/was40/detail?record=270&channelid=26700&searchword=%BB%F9%B1%BE%B7%A8 |script-title=zh:\u5fc6\u9999\u6e2f\u533a\u65d7\u533a\u5fbd\u7684\u8bde\u751f\uff08\u4e0a\uff09 |trans-title=Reflecting on the Creation of the Hong Kong SAR Flag and Emblem \u2013 Part 1 |publisher=Wenhui-xinmin United Press Group|date=2007-05-24|access-date=2009-03-20|language=Chinese}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}} and {{cite web|url=http://info.news365.com.cn/was40/detail?record=268&channelid=26700&searchword=%BB%F9%B1%BE%B7%A8 |script-title=zh:\u5fc6\u9999\u6e2f\u533a\u65d7\u533a\u5fbd\u7684\u8bde\u751f\uff08\u4e0b\uff09 |trans-title=Reflecting on the Creation of the Hong Kong SAR Flag and Emblem \u2013 Part 2|publisher=Wenhui-xinmin United Press Group|date=2007-05-25|access-date=2009-03-20|language=Chinese}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The flag of Hong Kong was adopted on 16 February 1990.<ref>{{cite book |author=\u9676\u5b58 |author2=\u8303\u5e0c\u6625, \u5b8b\u5f66\u5c0a |title=Decade After The Return of Hong Kong|accessdate=2009-11-22 |volume=1 |year=2007 |publisher=Shandong People's Publishing House |location=Jinan |language=Chinese |isbn=978-7-209-04247-5 |page=36 |chapter=Deciding the flag and emblem of Hong Kong |chapter-url = http://vip.book.sina.com.cn/book/chapter_42612_27183.html}}</ref> On 10 August 1996, it received formal approval from the [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|Preparatory Committee]], a group which advised the People's Republic of China (PRC) on [[Transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|Hong Kong's transfer of sovereignty]] from the United Kingdom to the PRC in 1997.<ref name=\"hongkong_flag\" /> The flag was first officially hoisted on 1 July 1997, in the [[The handover ceremony of Hong Kong in 1997|handover ceremony]] marking the transfer of sovereignty from the [[United Kingdom]] to China.<ref name=\"HandoverCeremony\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/hongkong/life/lifeschedule.html|title=Schedule of Events|first=Jeffrey |last = Aaronson |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|access-date=2009-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005020342/http://www.time.com/time/hongkong/life/lifeschedule.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archive-date=2009-10-05}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n   | width     = 170\n   | footer    = Flags of the [[Special Administrative Region]]s of [[Flag of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] and [[Flag of Macau|Macau]].\n   | image1    = Flag of Hong Kong.svg\n   | image2    = Flag of Macau.svg\n}}\nThe Regional flag of the Macau Special Administrative Region is \"Macau green\" with a [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus]] flower above a stylized image of the [[Ponte Governador Nobre de Carvalho|Governor Nobre de Carvalho Bridge]] and water in white, beneath an arc of five gold, five-pointed stars: one large star in the center of the arc and four smaller ones. The lotus was chosen as the floral emblem of [[Macau]]. The Governor Nobre de Carvalho Bridge is a bridge linking the [[Macau Peninsula]] and the island of [[Taipa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturalink.gov.cn/cnstatic/doc/exhibition/Macaoe.doc |title=Celebrating the 10th Anniversary of Macao's Return to China |access-date=2009-11-02 |year=2009 |format=DOC |publisher=Office of Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan Affairs, Ministry of Culture, P. R. China |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707032101/http://www.culturalink.gov.cn/cnstatic/doc/exhibition/Macaoe.doc |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The bridge is one of the most recognizable landmarks of the territory. The water beneath the lotus and the bridge symbolize Macau's position as a port and its role played in the territory. The five five-pointed stars echo the design of the national flag, symbolizing the relationship Macau has with its mother country.<ref name=\"ambiente\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ambiente.gov.mo/tchinese/07/lotus05/l0508.asp |title=Lotus and the Macao Special Administrative Region of the Regional Flag and Regional Emblem |access-date=2009-11-02 |author=\u694a\u5141\u4e2d |publisher=Macao Special Administrative Region Government and Environment Committee |language=zh |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071223002632/http://www.ambiente.gov.mo/tchinese/07/lotus05/l0508.asp |archive-date = December 23, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The design was chosen on 15 January 1993 by a committee that was drafting the [[Basic Law of Macau|Basic Law]] for the Macau SAR and was formally adopted by the Macau SAR Preparatory Committee on 16 January 1999.<ref name=\"macauadopt\">{{cite web |url = http://www.cdfao.chengdu.gov.cn/list.asp?ClassID=02011006 |title=Flag and Emblem of the Macao SAR |access-date=2009-11-02 |publisher=Chengdu People's Government Foreign Affairs Office |language= zh |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091206193106/http://www.cdfao.chengdu.gov.cn/list.asp?ClassID=02011006 |archive-date=December 6, 2009 }}</ref> The flag was first officially hoisted on 20 December 1999, in the [[Transfer of sovereignty of Macau|handover ceremony]] marking the transfer of sovereignty from [[Portugal]] to China.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lee | first = Khoon Choy | title = Pioneers of Modern China: Understanding the Inscrutable Chinese | publisher = World Scientific Publishing Co | date = November 2005 | location = | pages = 499 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=1jlOQc8BumIC&pg=PT523&dq=Macau+flag&cd=13#v=onepage&q=Macau%20flag | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-981-256-618-8 }}</ref>\n\n== Military flags ==\n{{Main|Flag of the People's Liberation Army}}\n\nThere are six flags that are used by the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA). The main feature of these flags is a golden star at the top left corner and two Chinese characters \"{{lang|zh|\u516b\u4e00}}\" to the right of the star, all placed on a red background. The characters \"{{lang|zh|\u516b\u4e00}}\" (literally \"eight one\") pay homage to the [[Nanchang uprising|events]] on August 1, 1927 (8th month, 1st day); this was when the PLA was created by the Communist Party to start their rebellion against the [[Kuomintang]] Government in [[Nanchang]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Fei |last=Wu |title = Military Parade Marks Anniversary |date=2009-10-01 |newspaper=China Daily |url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/60th/2009-10/01/content_8759348.htm |agency = Xinhua |accessdate = 2009-11-04 }}</ref> The main flag of the PLA was created on June 15, 1949 by a decree issued from Mao.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ybsy.gov.cn/gfjy/ShowArticle.asp?ArticleID=1494 |title=Flag of the People's Liberation Army |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2009-01-11 |publisher=Yibin Shuangyong Information Network |language = zh |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707043014/http://www.ybsy.gov.cn/gfjy/ShowArticle.asp?ArticleID=1494 |archive-date=2011-07-07 }}</ref> The flag has a ratio of 5 by 4, which has a white sleeve measuring {{frac|16}} of the flag's length. For ceremonies, a PLA flag with golden fringe is placed on a pole with gold and red spiral stripes and topped with a golden finial and red tassel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.lawtime.cn/d662410667504.html |title=Central Military Commission Provisions On The Military Flag |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=1978-06-17 |language= zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513085559/http://law.lawtime.cn/d662410667504.html |archive-date=2009-05-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Each branch of the PLA, the [[People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Ground Forces]], [[People's Liberation Army Navy|Navy]], [[People's Liberation Army Air Force|Air Force]] and [[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force|Rocket Force]], also have their own flags to use. In a 1992 order, the flags of the three branches were defined. The top {{frac|5|8}} of the flags is the same as the PLA flag; the bottom {{frac|3|8}} are occupied by the colors of the branches.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.diyifanwen.com/fanwen/bayijianjunjie/143152262.html |title = 81 Flag and Other Signs |access-date = 2009-11-04 |language=Chinese }}</ref> The flag of the Ground Forces has a forest green bar at the bottom, the naval ensign has stripes of blue and white at the bottom, the Air Force uses a sky blue bar and the Rocket Force uses a yellow bar at the bottom. The forest green represents the earth, the blue and white stripes represent the seas, the sky blue represents the air and the yellow represents the flare of missile launching.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/ziliao/2004-06/23/content_1542456.htm |title = Flag, Emblem and Song of the People's Liberation Army |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2004-06-23 |website = Xinhua Net News |publisher = Xinhua News Agency |language = zh }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://military.people.com.cn/n1/2016/0701/c1011-28516063.html |title = Uniform of Rocket Force |access-date=2016-07-06 |date=2016-07-01 |work = People's Daily |publisher = People's Daily |language = zh}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"120\">\nFile:People's Liberation Army Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background.|[[People's Liberation Army|PLA]]\nFile:Ground Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a green bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Ground Force]]\nFile:Naval Ensign of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag are stripes of blue, white, blue, white and blue.|[[People's Liberation Army Navy|Navy]]\nFile:Air Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a sky blue bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Air Force|Air Force]]\nFile:Rocket Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a yellow bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force|Rocket Force]]\nFile:People's Armed Police Flag.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is 3 green bars.|[[People's Armed Police]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Organizational flags ==\nAfter the Communist Party of China was founded in 1920, various sections of the party made flags based on what the [[Bolshevik]]s used, producing various designs and patterns. The current flag of the CPC was not created until April 28, 1942.  On that date, the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau issued a decree announcing the flag and the pattern it should follow.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.hndjw.gov.cn/dangshibolan/dangshiwenzhai/2009-09-14/11415.html |title= History \u2013 Flag of the Communist Party of China |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2009-09-14 |publisher=Henan Party Network Division | language = zh }}{{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The design was further defined in the CPC Constitution in 1996.<ref name=\"cpcflagcon\">{{cite web |url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/ziliao/2003-01/18/content_695383_1.htm |title=Provisions for Using the Flag and Emblem of the CPC |access-date = 2009-11-05 |date= 1996-09-21 |language = zh }}</ref> The flag has a red background that is charged with the emblem of the CPC in gold at the top left corner.<ref>{{cite book |url = http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#12 |title=Constitution of the Communist Party of China | chapter = XI Party Emblem and Flag |access-date=2009-11-05 |date=2002-11-18 |publisher = [[China International Publishing Group]] |website = [[China Internet Information Center]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018054320/http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#12 |archive-date = October 18, 2007 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The flag ratio is defined as two by three (24\u00d736 units); the size of the emblem is eight units square, placed four units away from the hoist and three units away from the top of the flag.<ref name=\"cpcflagcon\" />\n\nThe flag of the [[Communist Youth League of China]] was adopted on May 4, 1950.  The design of the flag consists of the group emblem, a gold star surrounded by a ring of gold, charged on a red field. The construction of the flag consists of making the top hoist portion of the flag into twelve by eighteen units, placing the emblem in the middle of that rectangle. The radius of the emblem is four units.<ref name=\"cylcflag\">{{cite web| location = CN | url=http://www.nhyouth.gov.cn/news_view.asp?newsid=471 |title=Organization Song, Flag, Emblem and Card |accessdate=2009-11-05 |date=2007-01-06 | publisher = Communist Youth League of China |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nThere are two flags used by the [[Young Pioneers of China]]. The first flag that is used is for pioneer battalions. The length of the flag is 90 centimetres and the width is 120 centimeters.  A golden badge of the Young Pioneers is placed in the center of the flag. For a company, a modified flag is used. The flag has a length of 60 centimetres and a width of 80 centimetres. A 20-centimeter triangle is cut out of the fly edge of the flag and the golden emblem is shifted closer towards the hoist.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.abayouth.gov.cn/html/sxdgz/2007/929/079291015081FDAD8JC96CDAJHIJK8.html |title=Young Pioneers of China Unit Flag |access-date=2009-11-20 |date=2007-09-27 |publisher=Communist Youth League in Sichuan Province |language = zh }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg|alt=A golden, crossed, hammer and sickle placed on a red background.|Communist Party of China\nFile:Flag of the Communist Youth League of China.svg|alt=A golden star placed inside a golden ring, all placed on a red background.|Communist Youth League of China\nFile:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5c11\u5e74\u5148\u950b\u961f\u961f\u65d7 (\u5927\u961f\u65d7).svg|alt=A gold star placed on top of a red torch with a flame, outlined in gold. This is centered on a red background.|Young Pioneers of China (Pioneer Battalions)\nFile:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5c11\u5e74\u5148\u950b\u961f\u961f\u65d7 (\u4e2d\u961f\u65d7).svg|alt=A gold star placed on top of a red torch with a flame, outlined in gold. This is placed on a red background, where the right edge has a triangle section cut out.|Young Pioneers of China (Pioneer Companies)\n</gallery>\n\n==Customs flag==\n[[File:Flag of the Customs of the People's Republic of China.svg|thumb|Customs flag of China]]\nThe customs flag is a China's national flag with the emblem of customs at the lower right corner, which consists of a golden key and the [[Caduceus]] of [[Hermes]], crossing with each other. The current customs flag was officially adopted in October 1, 1953. The customs flag should be hung at the bow of the customs vessel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zhengzhou.customs.gov.cn/publish/portal106/tab1641/module5966/info3564.htm |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6d77\u5173\u5173\u65d7 |publisher=Zhengzhou Customs |date=2005-08-26 |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731195853/http://zhengzhou.customs.gov.cn/publish/portal106/tab1641/module5966/info3564.htm |archive-date=31 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Historical flags ==\n{{Main list|List of Chinese flags}}\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Qing Dynasty (1862-1889).svg|[[Flag of the Qing dynasty]] (1862\u20131889)\nFile:Flag of the Qing Dynasty (1889-1912).svg|Flag of the [[Qing dynasty]] (1889\u20131912)\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China 1912-1928.svg|Flag of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] (1912\u20131928), representing the [[Five Races Under One Union]] principle\nImage:YuanFlag1.svg|National flag of [[Empire of China (1915\u201316)|Empire of China]] 1916\nImage:YuanFlag2.svg|National flag of [[Empire of China (1915\u201316)|Empire of China]] 1916\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China.svg|[[Flag of the Republic of China]] (1928\u2013present)\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|Flag of the [[National Revolutionary Army]] (1928\u20131947) and the flag of the [[Republic of China Army]] (1947\u2013present)\nFile:Naval Jack of the Republic of China.svg|Flag of the [[Kuomintang]] and the naval jack of the [[Republic of China Navy]] (1947\u2013present)\nFile:Flag of Chinese Taipei for Olympic games.svg|[[Chinese Taipei Olympic flag|Flag of Chinese Taipei]] used by ROC (1984\u2013present)\nFile:National Flag of Chinese Soviet Republic.svg|Flag of the [[Chinese Soviet Republic]] (1931\u20131937)\nFlag of the Chinese Communist Party (Pre-1996).svg|Flag of the Chinese Communist Party before 1996\nFile:Second War Flag of Chinese Soviet Republic.svg|War flag of the Chinese Workers' and Peasants' Red Army\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China-Nanjing (Peace, Anti-Communism, National Construction).svg|The [[Flags of the Reorganized National Government of China|Flag]] of the [[Reorganized National Government of the Republic of China]], a Japanese [[puppet state]] during [[World War II]], was based on the Flag of the Republic of China.\nFile:Flag of Manchukuo.svg|[[Flag of Manchukuo|National flag of Manchukuo]] 1934\u20131945\n</gallery>\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery perrow=\"8\" heights=\"180\" widths=\"180\">\nFile:Boeing 747-4J6 Air China B-2447 (7288535966).jpg|