]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{FOTW|id=cn|title=China}}\n* [http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/index.html Official specifications and standard sizes] of the flag.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vXChXT421Ug Hong Kong police demonstration] on raising the flag.\n\n{{-}}\n{{Asia topic|Flag of|title=[[Flags of Asia]]}}\n{{national flags}}\n{{China topics|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of The People's Republic Of China}}\n[[Category:National symbols of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:National flags|China]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1949|China]]\n[[Category:Flags of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Flags adopted through competition|China]]\n[[Category:Flags of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the flag of the People's Republic of China since its creation in 1949|the flag of the Republic of China since 1921|Flag of the Republic of China|other uses|Flag of China (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox flag\n|Name = People's Republic of China\n|Article = the\n|Nickname = ''W\u01d4x\u012bng H\u00f3ngq\u00ed'' (\"Five-starred Red Flag\")\n|Image = Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg\n|Use = 110110\n|Symbol = \n|Proportion = 2:3\n|Adoption = 27 September 1949<ref name=\"CPC news\">{{cite web |url = http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/64165/70293/70320/4861365.html |script-title = zh:1949\u5e749\u670827\u65e5 \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u65d7\u8bde\u751f |trans-title = 27 September 1949: The Birth of PRC's Flag |website = CPC News |access-date = 4 November 2009 |language = zh-Hans }}</ref>\n|Designer = [[Zeng Liansong]]\n|Design = A large golden star within an arc of four smaller golden stars, in the canton, on a field of [[Chinese red]]. \n|Image2 = \n|Nickname2 = \n|Imagetext2 = \n|Morenicks2 = \n|Use2 = \n|Symbol2 = \n|Proportion2 = \n|Adoption2 = \n|Design2 = \n|Designer2 = \n}}\n\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title = Flag of China\n|order = st\n|s = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u56fd|\u56fd\u65d7}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u570b|\u570b\u65d7}}\n|l = State flag of China\n|w = Chungkuo kuoch'i\n|p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 gu\u00f3q\u00ed\n|y = Z\u00f9ngw\u00f3k gw\u00f3kkei\n|xej = \ufe9f\u0652\ufeee \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \u0686\u0650\n|bpmf = \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u3111\u3127\u00b4\n|altname = Flag of the People's Republic of China\n|s2 = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd|\u56fd\u65d7}}\n|t2 = {{linktext|\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b|\u570b\u65d7}}\n|l2 = State flag of the People's Republic of China\n|w2 = Chunghua Jenmin Kunghokuo kuoch'i\n|p2 = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 gu\u00f3q\u00ed\n|y2 = Z\u00f9ngf\u00e0a J\u00e0nman G\u00f9ngwogw\u00f3k gw\u00f3kkei\n|xej2 = \ufe9f\u0652\ufeee \ufea7\u064f\ufeee\u064e \u0698\u064c \u0645\u064d \ufed7\u0652\ufeee \u062d\u0652 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \ufed7\u064f\ufeee\u064e\u0639 \u0686\u0650\n|bpmf2 = \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u00b4 \u3116\u3123\u00b4 \u3107\u3127\u3123\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u3125` \u310f\u311c\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u310d\u3128\u311b\u00b4 \u3111\u3127\u00b4\n|altname3 = Five-star Red Flag\n|s3 = {{linktext|\u4e94|\u661f|\u7ea2|\u65d7}}\n|t3 = {{linktext|\u4e94|\u661f|\u7d05|\u65d7}}\n|p3 = W\u01d4 x\u012bng h\u00f3ng q\u00ed\n|xej3 = \u0621\u064f \u0633\u064d \ufea1\u0652\ufeee \u0686\u0650\n|y3 = Ngh s\u00e8ng g\u00f9ng kei\n}}\n\nThe '''flag of China''', officially the '''National Flag of the People's Republic of China''' and also known as the '''Five-starred Red Flag''',<ref>{{cite book |author1 = \u9a6c\u5168\u6d32 |author2 = \u5468\u51ef\u519b |title = Stories About the National Flag, Emblem and Anthem | publisher = People's Liberation Army Publishing House | date = 2009-04-01 | location = Beijing, China | page = 1 |isbn = 978-7-5065-5729-0 }}</ref> is a [[Vermilion#Chinese red|Chinese red]] field [[charge (heraldry)|charged]] in the [[Glossary of vexillology#Flag elements|canton]] (upper corner nearest the flagpole) with five golden [[Five-pointed star|stars]]. The design features one large star, with four smaller stars in a semicircle set off towards the fly (the side farthest from the flag pole). The red represents the [[Chinese Communist Revolution|revolution]]; the five stars and their relationship represent the unity of the [[Chinese people]] under the leadership of the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC).  The first flag was hoisted by the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA) on a pole overlooking Beijing's [[Tiananmen Square]] on 1 October 1949, at a ceremony announcing the establishment of the [[People's Republic of China]].\n\nOther flags used in the People's Republic use a red background to symbolize the revolution in conjunction with other symbols. The flag of the [[People's Liberation Army]] uses the gold star with the Chinese characters 8-1 (for 1 August, the date of the PLA's founding). The flag of the [[Communist Party of China]] replaces all of the stars with the party emblem. Due to government regulations, cities and provinces of China cannot have their own flags; the only sub-national flags that exist are those of the [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]]. However, this law was defied when the cities of [[Kaifeng]] and [[Shangrao]] adopted their flags in March 2006 and March 2009 respectively.\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Flag of the Qing dynasty|Flag of the Republic of China}}\n\n===Early flags===\n[[File:Flag_of_China_(1862\u20131889).svg|alt=Flag of the Qing Dynasty|thumb|[[Flag of the Qing Dynasty]]]]\n\nOne of the first earlier flags of China was the \"[[Yellow Dragon Flag]]\" used by the [[Qing dynasty]] from 1862 until the overthrow of the monarchy during the Xinhai Revolution.  The Qing dynasty was the last imperial dynasty in China's history. The flag that was adopted in 1862 was triangular, but the dynasty adopted a rectangular version of the dragon flag in 1889.\n\n===Republic of China===\n[[File:Flag of the Republic of China.svg|alt=Flag of the Republic of China|thumb|[[Flag of the Republic of China]]]]\n\nThe [[Flag terminology|canton]] (upper corner on the hoist side) originated from the \"[[Blue Sky with a White Sun|Blue Sky with a White Sun flag]]\" ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u9752\u5929|\u767d\u65e5|\u65d7}}|p=q\u012bngti\u0101n b\u00e1ir\u00ec q\u00ed|labels=no}}) designed by [[Lu Haodong]], a martyr of the [[Xinhai Revolution]]. He presented his design to represent the revolutionary army at the inauguration of the [[Society for Regenerating China]], an [[Anti-Qing sentiment|anti-Qing]] society in [[Hong Kong]], on 21 February 1895. This design was later adopted as the KMT party flag and the [[Coat of Arms of the Republic of China]]. The \"red Earth\" portion was added by [[Sun Yat-sen]] in winter of 1906, bringing the flag to its modern form. According to [[George Yeo]], the Foreign Minister of Singapore, in those days the Blue Sky with a White Sun flag was sewn in the Sun Yat Sen Villa or [[Wan Qing Yuan]] in Singapore by Teo Eng Hock and his wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.mfa.gov.sg/pr/read_content.asp?View,15231,|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610153714/http://app.mfa.gov.sg/pr/read_content.asp?View,15231,|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2011|title=MFA Press Release Admin Page|date=10 June 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wanqingyuan.com.sg/english/onceupon/spsupp.html Dr Sun & 1911 Revolution: Teo Eng Hock (1871\u20131957)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126010654/http://wanqingyuan.com.sg/english/onceupon/spsupp.html |date=2009-11-26 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Wuchang Uprising]] in 1911 that heralded the Republic, the various revolutionary armies had different flags. Lu Hao-tung's \"Blue Sky with a White Sun\" flag was used in the provinces of [[Guangdong]], [[Guangxi]], [[Yunnan]], and [[Guizhou]]. In [[Wuhan]], a flag with 18 yellow stars was used to represent the 18 [[history of the political divisions of China|administrative divisions]] at the time. In [[Shanghai]] and northern China, a \"Five-Colored Flag\" ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u4e94\u8272|\u65d7}}|p=w\u01d4 s\u00e8 q\u00ed|labels=no}}) ([[Five Races Under One Union]] flag) was used of five horizontal stripes representing the five major [[nationalities of China]]: the [[Han Chinese|Han]] (red), the [[Manchu]] (yellow), the [[Mongol]] (blue), the [[Hui Chinese|Hui]] (white), and the [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]] (black).\n\nWhen the government of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] was established on January 1, 1912, the \"Five-Colored Flag\" was selected by the provisional Senate as the national flag. The [[:File:Chinese-Army-Wuhan-Flag-1911-1928 dots18.svg|\"18-Star Flag\"]] was adopted by the army<ref name=\"army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aiplus.idv.tw/soviet/FARMY.HTM |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u6b77\u4ee3\u9678\u8ecd\u65d7\u5e5f |accessdate=2008-12-26 |last=Yu-liang |first=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language=Chinese }}</ref> and the modern flag was adopted as a naval ensign.<ref name=\"navy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aiplus.idv.tw/soviet/FNAVY.HTM |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u570b\u6b77\u4ee3\u6d77\u8ecd\u65d7\u5e5f |accessdate=2007-12-11 |last=Yu-liang |first=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language=Chinese }}</ref> Sun Yat-sen, however, did not consider the five-colored flag appropriate, reasoning that horizontal order implied a hierarchy or class like that which existed during dynastic times.\n\nAfter President [[Yuan Shikai]] assumed [[Dictatorship|dictatorial powers]] in 1913 by dissolving the [[National Assembly of the Republic of China|National Assembly]] and outlawing the KMT, Sun Yat-sen established a government-in-exile in [[Tokyo]] and employed the modern flag as the national ROC flag. He continued using this design when the KMT established a [[Government of the Republic of China in Guangzhou|rival government]] in [[Guangzhou]] in 1917. The modern flag was made the official national flag on December 17, 1928 after the successful [[Northern Expedition (1926\u20131927)|Northern Expedition]] that overthrew the [[Beiyang government|Beijing government]], though the Five-Colored Flag still continued to be used by locals in an unofficial capacity. One reason for this discrepancy in use was lingering regional biases held by officials and citizens of northern China, who favored the Five-Colored Flag, against southerners such as the [[Guangdong|Cantonese]]/Hakka Sun Yat-sen.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n\nDuring [[the Second Sino-Japanese War]], the invading [[Japan]]ese established a [[Japanese puppet states|variety of puppet governments]] using several flag designs. The \"[[Reformed Government of the Republic of China|Reform Government]]\" established in March 1938 in [[Nanjing]] to consolidate the various puppet governments employed the Five-Colored Flag. When [[Wang Jingwei]] was slated to take over the [[Reorganized National Government of the Republic of China|Japanese-installed government in Nanjing]] in 1940, he demanded to use the modern flag as a means to challenge the authority of the [[Nationalist Government]] in [[Chongqing]] under [[Chiang Kai-shek]] and position himself as the rightful successor to Sun Yat-sen. However, the Japanese preferred the Five-Colored flag. As a compromise, the Japanese suggested adding a triangular yellow pennant on top with the slogan \"Peace, Anti-Communism, National Construction\" ({{zh|t=\u548c\u5e73\u53cd\u5171\u5efa\u570b|p=H\u00e9p\u00edng f\u01ceng\u00f2ng ji\u00e0n gu\u00f3|labels=no}}) in black, but this was rejected by Wang. In the end, Wang and the Japanese agreed that the yellow banner was to be used outdoors only, until 1943 when the banner was abandoned, leaving two rival governments with the same flag, each claiming to be the legitimate National Government of China.<ref>{{cite journal\n |first=Andrew \n |last=Cheung \n |title=Slogans, Symbols, and Legitimacy: The Case of Wang Jingwei's Nanjing Regime \n |version=Working paper \n |publisher=East Asian Working Paper Series on Language and Politics in Modern China \n |year=1995 \n |url = http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/working_paper/noframe_6a_sloga.htm \n |access-date=24 July 2008 \n |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080226023546/http://www.indiana.edu/~easc/resources/working_paper/noframe_6a_sloga.htm \n |archive-date=26 February 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\nThe flag was specified in Article Six of the [[Constitution of the Republic of China|1947 Constitution]]. After the [[Chinese Civil War]] in 1949, the ROC government led by Chiang Kai-shek relocated its government and its institutions to the island of [[Geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]]. On the [[mainland China|mainland]], the communist forces of [[Mao Zedong]] established the [[People's Republic of China (PRC)]] and adopted their own national flag. On October 23, 1954, the National Emblem and National Flag of the Republic of China Act ({{zh|t={{linktext|\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b|\u570b\u5fbd|\u570b\u65d7\u6cd5}} |p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 M\u00edngu\u00f3 gu\u00f3hu\u012b gu\u00f3q\u00edf\u01ce|labels=no}}) was promulgated by the [[Legislative Yuan]] to specify the size, measure, ratio, production, and management of the flag.<ref name=\"1954law\">{{cite web |url = http://www.globalflag.idv.tw/wg/gqf.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u570b\u5fbd\u570b\u65d7\u6cd5 |access-date=2008-12-26 |first=Yu-liang |last=Tai |date=1954-10-23 |language= zh-TW }}</ref>\n\n===People's Republic of China===\n[[File:Zeng Liansong's proposal for the PRC flag.svg|thumb|alt=A red flag with four small golden stars and one giant gold star at the top left corner. In the giant gold star, a red crossed hammer and sickle is placed in the center.|The original design submitted by Zeng Liansong]]\n\nOn July 4, 1949, the sixth working group of the Preparatory Committee of the New Political Consultative Conference ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703}}, PCNPCC) created a notice to submit designs for the national flag. After a few changes, the notice was published in the papers ''[[People's Daily]]'', ''Beiping Liberation News'', ''Xinmin News'', ''Dazhong Daily'', ''[[Guangming Daily (China)|Guangming Daily]]'', ''Jinbu Daily'' and ''Tianjin Daily'' during the period July 15\u201326.<ref name=\"gov news\">{{cite web |url = http://gov.people.com.cn/GB/46743/4889273.html |title=Creation of the Flag, Emblem and Anthem of the People's Republic of China |date=2006-10-08|access-date=2009-11-05 |language= zh-CN |website = Chinese Government News |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081013052258/http://gov.people.com.cn/GB/46743/4889273.html |archive-date=2008-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The list of requirements for the national flag were also posted in the notice:\n# Chinese characteristics (geography, nationality, history, culture, etc.);\n# Power characteristics (people's democratic government, led by the working class and based on the worker-peasant alliance);\n# The shape should be rectangular and the length-breadth ratio should be 3:2;\n# The color should mainly be bright red<ref>{{cite web |url = http://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703\u7232\u5fb5\u6c42\u570b\u65d7\u570b\u5fbd\u5716\u6848\u53ca\u570b\u6b4c\u8fad\u8b5c\u5553\u4e8b |script-title = zh:\u65b0\u653f\u6cbb\u5354\u5546\u6703\u8b70\u7c4c\u5099\u6703\u7232\u5fb5\u6c42\u570b\u65d7\u570b\u5fbd\u5716\u6848\u53ca\u570b\u6b4c\u8fad\u8b5c\u5553\u4e8b |trans-title = Notice to Solicit Designs of the National Flag, Emblem and Anthem |author=PCNPCC |date=1949-07-10 |access-date=2009-11-05 |website=Wikisource |language=zh-Hant }}</ref> (an early draft of the notice had the color as dark red, but this was changed to bright red by [[Zhou Enlai]]).<ref name=\"kong\" />\n\n[[File:Mao Zedong's proposal for the PRC flag.svg|thumb|The \"[[Yellow River]]\" flag design originally preferred by [[Mao Zedong]].]]\n[[Zeng Liansong]], a citizen from [[Wenzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], was working in Shanghai at the time the announcement came out; he wanted to create a flag design to express his patriotic enthusiasm for the new country. In the middle of July, he sat down in his attic over several nights to come up with designs. His inspiration for the current design came from the stars shining in the night sky. He thought of a Chinese proverb \"longing for the stars, longing for the moon\", ({{lang|zh|\u76fc\u661f\u661f\u76fc\u6708\u4eae}}, ''p\u00e0n x\u012bngx\u012bng p\u00e0n yu\u00e8li\u00e0ng'') which shows yearning. He viewed the CPC as the great saviour ({{lang|zh|\u5927\u6551\u661f}}, ''d\u00e0 ji\u00f9x\u012bng'' \"great saving star\") of the Chinese people, represented by a larger star. The idea for four small stars came from [[On the People's Democratic Dictatorship]], a speech by Mao Zedong, which defined the Chinese people as consisting of four [[social class]]es, also referred to in Asian cultures as the [[four occupations]] ({{lang|zh|\u58eb\u8fb2\u5de5\u5546}}) ''shi, nong, gong, shang'' (\"the working class, the peasantry, the urban petty bourgeoisie and the national bourgeoisie\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/mao/selected-works/volume-4/mswv4_65.htm|title=On the People's Democratic Dictatorship : In Commemoration of the Twenty-eighth Anniversary of the Communist Party of China, June 30, 1949|accessdate=2017-09-27}}</ref>).  The color yellow implies that China belongs to the Chinese people, a \"[[yellow race]]\".<ref name=\"kong\"/> After working out the details of the placement of the stars and their sizes (he had tried to put all of the stars in the center, but believed it would be too heavy and dull), he sent his \"Five Stars on a Field of Red\" ({{lang|zh|\u7d05\u5730\u4e94\u661f\u65d7}}, ''h\u00f3ng d\u00ec w\u01d4x\u012bng q\u00ed'') design to the committee in the middle of August.<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref name=\"kong\"/>\n\nBy August 20, a between 2,992<ref name=\"design_participation\"/> and 3,012<ref name=\"govprcflag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.cn/test/2005-05/24/content_18247.htm|title=National Flag of the People's Republic of China|publisher=Gov.cn|date=2005-05-24|access-date=2009-11-08|language=Chinese}}</ref> designs had been sent to the flag committee,<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/82819/121799/121806/7185220.html|chapter=2, Work of the Preparatory Committee of the New Political Consultative Conference (4)|title=1948\u20132008, Let history tell the future \u2013 the CPC Central Committee issued \"51 slogan\" 60 anniversary |url = http://cpc.people.com.cn/GB/64162/82819/121799/index.html|publisher=China Publishing House|editor1-first=Weiqun |editor1-last=Zhu|isbn=978-7-5075-2294-5|year=2008|language=zh-CN }}</ref> including input from committee members themselves such as [[Guo Moruo]] and [[Tan Kah Kee]].<ref name=\"design_participation\">{{cite news|url=http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/85040/9850276.html|title=The National People's active participation in the design within 1 month of flag design up to 2992 candidates|author=Chen, Yu|website=CPC News|date=2009-08-13|access-date=2009-11-05|language=Chinese}}</ref> From August 16 to 20, the designs were viewed at the [[Beijing Hotel]] and culled down to a list of 38.<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref name=\"gov news\" /> These designs are collected into a book named ''A Reference of National Flag Designs'' ({{lang|zh-Hant|\u570b\u65d7\u5716\u6848\u53c3\u8003\u8cc7\u6599}}). This book was then submitted to the newly established [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]] (CPPCC) for further discussion. However, Zeng's design was not included until [[Tian Han]] nominated it again.<ref name=\"\u56fd\u65d7\u662f\u600e\u6837\u8bde\u751f\u7684\">{{cite news |url = http://www.gmw.cn/01wzb/1999-07/22/GB/wzb%5E1664%5E6%5EWZ3-2210.htm |title=How Was The National Flag Created? |publisher=Digest News |date=1999-07-22 |access-date=2009-11-06 |last=Bai |first = Zhi |language= zh }}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of September 23, the representatives of the CPPCC discussed the national flags, but came to no conclusion. Some disliked the symbolism which Zeng attached to the four smaller stars, and said it should not include the bourgeoisie. The design Mao and others liked had a giant golden star in the corner on a red flag that was charged with a golden horizontal bar. But this design was strongly opposed by [[Zhang Zhizhong]], who saw the golden bar as symbolizing the tearing apart of the revolution from the country.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/8798903.html|title=Zhang Zhizhong and the Birth of the 5 Star Red Flag |date=2009-02-13|access-date=2009-11-05|last=Tian |first = Shuhe |website = CPC News|language= zh-CN }}</ref> That night, Peng Guanghan ({{lang|zh|\u5f6d\u5149\u6db5}}) recommended Zeng's design to [[Zhou Enlai]]. Zhou was satisfied with it and asked for a larger copy of the design to be made. Tan Kah Kee also gave his advice to Mao and Zhou that the power characteristics are more important than Chinese geography characteristics, so there was no need to insist on the golden bar which stands for the [[Yellow River]]. Two days later, Mao had a meeting in his office about the flag. He persuaded everyone to adopt Zeng's design, with some slight modifications.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Witnesses to the Birth of the National Flag|author=Peng Guanghan|journal=At Home and Overseas|publisher=The All-China Federation of returned overseas Chinese and overseas Chinese|location=Beijing|issn=1002-3801|date=March 2003|language=Chinese}}</ref> According to earlier discussions at the Beijing Hotel, the [[hammer and sickle]] from Zeng's original design was removed since it was similar to the [[Flag of the Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"\u56fd\u65d7\u662f\u600e\u6837\u8bde\u751f\u7684\"/> On September 27, 1949, Zeng's modified design was selected unanimously by the First Plenary Session of CPPCC, which changed the flag's name to \"Five-star Red Flag\".<ref name=\"CPC news\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://dangshi.people.com.cn/GB/85039/10163392.html|title=Peng Han: the tortuous process of the flag's birth|author=Wang Jianzhu|date=2009-10-09|publisher=CPC News|accessdate=2009-11-05|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The first flag of China.jpg|thumbnail|[[Mao Zedong]] pressed the button and raised the flag of China for the first time in the announcement of the establishment of the People's Republic of China at [[Tiananmen Square]] on October 1, 1949]]\nOn September 29, the new flag was published in the [[People's Daily]], so the design could be copied by other local authorities.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=People's Daily|url=http://images.china.cn/attachement/jpg/site1000/20090929/000802ab801d0c2c17a32d.jpg|language=Chinese|format=Image|date=1949-09-29|volume=466|page=1|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref> The flag was officially unveiled in Beijing's [[Tiananmen Square]] on October 1, 1949, at the formal announcement of the establishment of the [[People's Republic of China]]. The first flag flown over Tiananmen Square was sewn together by Zhao Wenrui ({{lang|zh|\u8d75\u6587\u745e}}), a seamstress who finished the task around 1{{Nbsp}}pm on September 30.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://2008.qq.com/a/20080807/000443.htm|title=The first one who stitched the flag of The People's Republic of China \u2013 Zhao Wenrui|date=2008-08-07|accessdate=2009-11-06|publisher=QQ.com|language=Chinese}}</ref> Zeng had a hard time believing that his design was picked, due to the missing hammer and sickle from the giant star. However, he was officially congratulated by the General Office of the Central People's Government as the designer of the flag and received 5 million yuan for his work.<ref name=\"kong\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbw.com/btm/issue71/62-63.html |title=The Worker Who Forged the Red Flag |accessdate=2009-11-03 |last=Kong |first=Mark |date=1999-10-01 |work=Beijing This Month |publisher=Chinese Business World |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211184343/http://www.cbw.com/btm/issue71/62-63.html |archivedate=February 11, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hantailun\">{{cite book|title=Witnessed the Tiananmen Square|volume=3|author=Han Tailun|isbn=978-7-224-05364-7|location=Xi'an|publisher=Shaanxi People's Publishing House|year=2000|page=2066|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"140\" caption=\"Rejected designs of the Five-star Red Flag\">\nFile:Proposal 2 for the PRC flag.svg|\nFile:Proposal 3 for the PRC flag.svg|\nFile:Proposal 4 for the PRC flag.svg|\n</gallery><gallery widths=\"140\" caption=\"Other rejected proposed designs\">\nFile:Proposed PRC national flags 006.svg |Proposal by [[Wu Yuzhang]]\nFile:Proposed-PRC-10.svg |Proposal by [[Ai Qing]]\nFile:Proposed PRC national flag 014.svg |Proposal by [[Zhu De]]\nFile:Proposed PRC national flag 015.svg |Proposal by [[Liang Congjie]]\nFile:Proposed PRC flag (Design 8, Guo Moruo).svg |Proposal by [[Guo Moruo]]\nFile:Guo Moruo's Proposal Flag for the PRC.svg |Proposal by [[Guo Moruo]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Symbolism ==\n[[File:Chinese flag (Beijing) - IMG 1104.jpg|thumb|right|Flag of China, Beijing]]\n\nAccording to the current government interpretation of the flag, the red background symbolises the revolution and the golden colors were used to \"radiate\" on the red background though each of the colors represents  one of the [[Color in Chinese culture|Five Elements]] of fire and earth. The five stars and their relationship represents the unity of Chinese people under the leadership of the [[Communist Party of China]]. The orientation of the stars shows that the unity should go around a center.<ref name=\"govprcflag\" /> In the original description of the flag by Zeng, the larger star symbolizes the Communist Party of China, and the four smaller stars that surround the big star symbolize the four social classes (the [[working class]], the [[peasant]]ry, the urban [[petite bourgeoisie]] and the national [[bourgeoisie]]) of China's [[New Democracy]] mentioned in Mao's \"[[On the People's Democratic Dictatorship]]\". <!-- http://www.lishiyushehui.cn/modules/topic/downloads.php?id=218 I need to make the full cite of this, but don't have time right now. --> The five stars that formed an ellipse represent the territory of China which is shaped like a [[Begonia]] leaf. It is sometimes stated that the five stars of the flag represent the five largest ethnic groups: [[Han Chinese]], [[Zhuang people|Zhuang]]s, [[Hui people|Hui Chinese]], [[Manchu people|Manchu]]s and [[Uyghur people|Uyghur]]s.<ref name=\"Shambaugh\">{{cite journal|last=Shambaugh|first=David |date=June 1994|title=Book reviews|journal=The China Quarterly|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press|CUP]] for [[School of Oriental and African Studies|SOAS]]|issue= 138|pages=517\u2013520|doi=10.1017/S0305741000035876 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mayall|first=James|others=ed. Richard W. Bulliet|title=The Columbia History of the 20th Century|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|year=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/columbiahistoryo0000unse/page/186 186]|chapter=Nationalism|isbn=0-231-07628-2|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/columbiahistoryo0000unse/page/186}}</ref> This is generally regarded as an erroneous conflation with the [[Five Races Under One Union|\"Five Races Under One Union\" flag]], used 1912\u201328 by the [[Beiyang Government]] of [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]], whose different-colored stripes represented the Han Chinese, Hui Chinese, Manchus, [[Mongols]] and [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]].<ref name=\"Shambaugh\"/><ref name=\"Zarrow\">{{cite book|last=Zarrow|first=Peter Gue |title=China in War and Revolution, 1895\u20131949|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2005|pages=363|chapter=Revolution and Civil War|isbn=0-415-36448-5}}</ref>\n\n== Construction details, sizes and colors ==\nThe construction sheet for the national flag was published on September 28, 1949 by an order from the Presidium of the First Plenary Session of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]].<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.zjswb.gov.cn/zjswbcms/view/en/news.jsp?unid=74DA037561CEAB31AF98BE644285D160 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707043738/http://www.zjswb.gov.cn/zjswbcms/view/en/news.jsp?unid=74DA037561CEAB31AF98BE644285D160 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-07 |title=Law About The National Flag of the People's Republic of China |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=1990-10-01 |publisher=Zhejiang Provincial Foreign Affairs Office }} [[:zh:s:\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u65d7\u6cd5|in Chinese]]</ref> The information can also be found in the document \"[[List of GB standards|GB]] 12982-2004: National flag\" that was released by the [[Standardization Administration of China]].<ref name=\"standards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sac.gov.cn/SACSearch/search?channelid=160591&templet=gjcxjg_detail.jsp&searchword=STANDARD_CODE='12982'&XZ=T |language=zh-cn|script-title=zh:\u56fd\u5bb6\u6807\u51c6\u59d4\u6807\u51c6\u5236\u4fee\u8ba2\u7ba1\u7406\u7cfb\u7edf|website=www.sac.gov.cn}}</ref> \n{{-}}\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Construction sheet\n! Standard\n|-\n|[[File:Construction sheet of Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|400px]]\n|\n#The flag is split into 4 sections, with the top hoist part of the flag being a grid of 15 by 10 units. \n#The centre of the biggest star is placed at 5 units from the hoist and 5 units from the top of the flag. The diameter of the biggest star's [[circumscribed circle]] is 6 units.\n#Of the 4 smaller stars, the first one is centred 2 units from the top of the flag, 10 units from the hoist; the second one is centred 4 units from the top of the flag and 12 units from the hoist; the third one is centred 7 units from the top of the flag and 12 units from the hoist; the fourth one is centred 9 units from the top of the flag and 10 units from the hoist. \n#The diameter of each small star's [[circumscribed circle]] is 2 units. Each of the top points of the 4 smaller stars are rotated such that they point towards the center point of the larger star.<ref name=\"chinaflagcon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/spec.html |title= Specifications for the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=2005-11-06 |publisher=Protocol Division, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government of the People's Republic of China }}</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], flags that failed to adhere to the regulations were used in connection with China. The flags, used during the opening ceremony and two medal ceremonies, featured the four small stars incorrectly angled in the same direction, inciting fury at the Olympic organisers.<ref>{{cite news |last= Gajanan|first=Mahita  |date=9 August 2016 |title= Olympic Officials Apologize to China for Using the Wrong Flag|url=http://time.com/4445373/rio-2016-olympics-china-wrong-flags/ |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |location= |access-date=22 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Law on the National Flag mentions five possible sizes that could be made for the national flag:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/standard.html |title= Standard Sizes of the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-07 |date=2005-11-06 |publisher=Protocol Division, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government of the People's Republic of China }}</ref> According to Article 4 of the Law On the National Flag, people's governments of provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities directly under the Central Government are directed to authorize companies to make any copy of the national flag.<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\"/> Besides five official sizes for flying on flagpoles, there are another four smaller sizes for other purposes, such as decoration on cars or display in meeting rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.qizhi147.com/nd.jsp?id=13 |language=zh-cn|script-title=zh:\u56fd\u65d7\u7684\u6807\u51c6\u5c3a\u5bf8\u548c\u56fd\u65d7\u6bcf\u4e2a\u5c3a\u5bf8\u7684\u7528\u9014\u4ecb\u7ecd |publisher=Shanghai Yingfeng Flag Co. Ltd |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Size !!1 !!2 !!3 !!4 !!5 !!6 !!7 !!8 !!9\n|-\n|Length \u00d7 width (cm)\n|| 288&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;192|| 240&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;160|| 192&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;128|| 144&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;96|| 96&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;64|| 66&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;44|| 45&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;30|| 30&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;20|| 21&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;14\n|}\n</center>\n\n=== Colours ===\nThe colours of the national flag are regulated in the document \"GB 12983-2004: Standard Color Sample of the National Flag,\" also released by the Standardization Administration of China. The colors are in the CIE [[Standard illuminant]] D65 and the [[CIE 1964 color space|CIE 1964 Supplementary Standard Colorimetric System]].<ref name=\"flagcolor\">{{cite web |url=http://cnc.zhaobz.com/gb/a/4/zhaobzgb3024coo.rar  |script-title=zh:GB 12983-2004 \u56fd\u65d7\u989c\u8272\u6807\u51c6\u6837\u54c1 |trans-title=Standard Color Sample of the National Flag |accessdate=2009-11-02 |year=2004 |format=PDF |publisher=Standardization Administration of China |language=Chinese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813212810/http://cnc.zhaobz.com/gb/a/4/zhaobzgb3024coo.rar |archivedate=2011-08-13 }}</ref>\n{|class = \"wikitable\" width=80%\n|+Standard color sample of the national flag<ref name=\"flagcolor\" />\n|-\n! rowspan=2 colspan=2 | Fabric\n! rowspan=2 | Stimulus value ''Y''<sub>10</sub>\n! colspan=2 | Color coordinate\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Allowable error margin\n|-\n! ''x''<sub>10</sub> !! ''y''<sub>10</sub>\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Synthetic fiber]]\n! Red\n|| 9.4 || 0.555 ||0.328\n| rowspan=6 | All are<br /><math>\\Delta E_{ab}^{\\,\\bullet}\\le 2.0</math>\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 41.2 || 0.446 || 0.489\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Silk]]\n! Red\n|| 12.3 || 0.565 || 0.325\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 32.4 || 0.450 || 0.463\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | [[Cotton cloth]]\n! Red\n|| 9.2 || 0.595 || 0.328\n|-\n! Gold\n|| 33.0 || 0.467 || 0.463\n|-\n! Sleeve !! White\n|| 78.0 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||The stimulus value ''Y''<sub>10</sub> must not be less than 78\n|}\n\n==== Colours scheme ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n![[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|30px]]\n! style=\"background:#de2910ff; width:200px\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">Red</span>\n! style=\"background:#ffde00ff; width:200px\" | Gold\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" | '''[[RGB color model|RGB]]'''\n| <code>222/41/16</code> || <code>255/222/0</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" | '''[[Hexadecimal]]'''\n| <code>#de2910ff</code> || <code>#ffde00ff</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" |'''[[CMYK color model|CMYK]]'''\n| <code>0/82/93/13</code> || <code>0/13/100/0</code>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2; text-align:right\" |'''[[Pantone]]''' (approximate)\n| 485 C || Yellow C\n|}\n\n===Unicode===\nThe Flag of China is represented as the [[Unicode]] [[emoji]] sequence {{unichar|1F1E8|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER C}} and {{unichar|1F1F3|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER N}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://emojipedia.org/flag-for-china/|title=\ud83c\udde8\ud83c\uddf3 Flag for China Emoji|access-date=2018-05-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Regulations ==\n{{Wikisource|Law About The National Flag of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe current law about the national flag was passed by 14th Meeting of the Standing Committee of the Seventh National People's Congress on June 28, 1990 and was enforced starting October 1, 1990. The main point of the law was to not only set down regulations on how to make the Chinese flag, what it looks like, where it can be flown and how it can be flown. The law also stresses that the national flag is \"the symbol and hallmark of the People's Republic of China\" and that everyone \"shall respect and care for the National Flag.\"<ref name=\"cnflaglaw\"/>\n\n===Folding the flag===\n# Fold horizontally along the center.\n# Repeat, fold horizontally along the centre.\n# Fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the centre of the flag.\n# Repeat, fold vertically along the top\n\n===Desecration===\n{{also|Flag desecration#China}}\n[[File:\u9999\u6e2f\u4e4b\u8def 01.jpg|thumb|Desecrated flag]]\nAccording to [[Radio Free Asia]], in January 2014 after [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] residents were reportedly forced to bow to a flag of China before worshipping at Xaniqa mosque in Yengimehelle township, [[Xayar County]], [[Aksu Prefecture]], [[Xinjiang]], three Uyghur youths burned the flag. Raids on Uyghur homes searching for the youths continued into 2015. Authorities warned residents not to discuss the flagburning incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/uyghur/police-conduct-raids-in-shayar-county-04162015140703.html|title=Police Conduct Raids in Xinjiang a Year After Flag Burning at Mosque|date=16 April 2015|accessdate=26 April 2020|website=Radio Free Asia|authors=[[Shohret Hoshur]], Roseanne Gerin|translator=Shohret Hoshur}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September 2017, Hong Kong elected legislator [[Cheng Chung-tai]] was convicted of desecrating the flag under the National Flag and National Emblem Ordinance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hklii.org/eng/hk/legis/instrument/A401/|title=Hong Kong Constitutional Instruments|website=Hong Kong Legal Information Institute|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>  He had been seen turning representations of the flags (not of standard dimensions) upside down in the legislative chamber in October the previous year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/09/29/breaking-civic-passion-lawmaker-cheng-chung-tai-found-guilty-desecrating-flags-legislative-session/|title=Civic Passion lawmaker Cheng Chung-tai found guilty of 'desecrating' flags during legislative session|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|date=29 September 2017|last=Cheung|first=Karen|access-date=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Flags of the Special Administrative Regions of the People's Republic of China==\n{{Main|Flag of Hong Kong|Flag of Macau}}\n[[File:Flag_flying_protocol_of_Hong_Kong_SAR_and_PRC.svg|right|345px|thumb|The regional flag (Hong Kong) displayed with national flag.]]\nDue to an order passed by the CPC Central Committee General Office and General Office of the State Council, cities and provinces are no longer allowed to adopt their own symbols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zh.wikisource.org/wiki/\u4e2d\u5171\u4e2d\u592e\u529e\u516c\u5385\u3001\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u529e\u516c\u5385\u5173\u4e8e\u7981\u6b62\u81ea\u884c\u5236\u4f5c\u548c\u4f7f\u7528\u5730\u65b9\u65d7\u3001\u5fbd\u7684\u901a\u77e5 |title=CPC Central Committee and State Council Notice On the Prohibition of the Creation and Use of Civic Flags |accessdate=2009-11-08 |date=1997-11-18 |publisher=Wikisource }}</ref> However, both of the Hong Kong and [[Macau]] [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China|Special Administrative Regions]] of China have their own special flags. The precise use of the SAR flags are regulated by laws passed by the [[National People's Congress]].<ref name=\"hongkong_flag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com.cn/zgrdxw/faguiku/dff/F50-1060.html|title=Decision of the Hong Kong SAR Flag|author=[[Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region]]|website=People.com.cn|date=1996-08-11|access-date=2009-11-22|language=zh}}</ref><ref name=\"macau_flag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.china.com.cn/law/flfg/txt/2006-08/08/content_7064255.htm|title=Law Regarding The Flag and Emblem of the Hong Kong SAR|publisher=China.com.cn|work=Preparatory Committee for the Macau Special Administrative Region|date=1999-01-16|access-date=2009-11-22|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nThe Flag of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region features a stylized, white, five-petal ''[[Bauhinia blakeana]]'' flower in the center of a red field. On each petal is a red star; the stars are supposed to demonstrate that Hong Kong residents love their motherland while the overall flag design signifies the link re-established between post-colonial Hong Kong and China while demonstrating the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" political principle applied to the region.<ref name=\"symbolism\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BmCFznufJ54C&pg=PA582&lpg=PA582#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=International Law Reports|volume=122|year=2002|page=582|access-date=2009-11-01|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-80775-3 |author1=Elihu Lauterpacht |author2=C. J. Greenwood |author3=A. G. Oppenheimer }}</ref><ref name=\"reflection\">{{cite web|url=http://info.news365.com.cn/was40/detail?record=270&channelid=26700&searchword=%BB%F9%B1%BE%B7%A8 |script-title=zh:\u5fc6\u9999\u6e2f\u533a\u65d7\u533a\u5fbd\u7684\u8bde\u751f\uff08\u4e0a\uff09 |trans-title=Reflecting on the Creation of the Hong Kong SAR Flag and Emblem \u2013 Part 1 |publisher=Wenhui-xinmin United Press Group|date=2007-05-24|access-date=2009-03-20|language=Chinese}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}} and {{cite web|url=http://info.news365.com.cn/was40/detail?record=268&channelid=26700&searchword=%BB%F9%B1%BE%B7%A8 |script-title=zh:\u5fc6\u9999\u6e2f\u533a\u65d7\u533a\u5fbd\u7684\u8bde\u751f\uff08\u4e0b\uff09 |trans-title=Reflecting on the Creation of the Hong Kong SAR Flag and Emblem \u2013 Part 2|publisher=Wenhui-xinmin United Press Group|date=2007-05-25|access-date=2009-03-20|language=Chinese}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The flag of Hong Kong was adopted on 16 February 1990.<ref>{{cite book |author=\u9676\u5b58 |author2=\u8303\u5e0c\u6625, \u5b8b\u5f66\u5c0a |title=Decade After The Return of Hong Kong|accessdate=2009-11-22 |volume=1 |year=2007 |publisher=Shandong People's Publishing House |location=Jinan |language=Chinese |isbn=978-7-209-04247-5 |page=36 |chapter=Deciding the flag and emblem of Hong Kong |chapter-url = http://vip.book.sina.com.cn/book/chapter_42612_27183.html}}</ref> On 10 August 1996, it received formal approval from the [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|Preparatory Committee]], a group which advised the People's Republic of China (PRC) on [[Transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|Hong Kong's transfer of sovereignty]] from the United Kingdom to the PRC in 1997.<ref name=\"hongkong_flag\" /> The flag was first officially hoisted on 1 July 1997, in the [[The handover ceremony of Hong Kong in 1997|handover ceremony]] marking the transfer of sovereignty from the [[United Kingdom]] to China.<ref name=\"HandoverCeremony\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/hongkong/life/lifeschedule.html|title=Schedule of Events|first=Jeffrey |last = Aaronson |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]|access-date=2009-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005020342/http://www.time.com/time/hongkong/life/lifeschedule.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archive-date=2009-10-05}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n   | width     = 170\n   | footer    = Flags of the [[Special Administrative Region]]s of [[Flag of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] and [[Flag of Macau|Macau]].\n   | image1    = Flag of Hong Kong.svg\n   | image2    = Flag of Macau.svg\n}}\nThe Regional flag of the Macau Special Administrative Region is \"Macau green\" with a [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus]] flower above a stylized image of the [[Ponte Governador Nobre de Carvalho|Governor Nobre de Carvalho Bridge]] and water in white, beneath an arc of five gold, five-pointed stars: one large star in the center of the arc and four smaller ones. The lotus was chosen as the floral emblem of [[Macau]]. The Governor Nobre de Carvalho Bridge is a bridge linking the [[Macau Peninsula]] and the island of [[Taipa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturalink.gov.cn/cnstatic/doc/exhibition/Macaoe.doc |title=Celebrating the 10th Anniversary of Macao's Return to China |access-date=2009-11-02 |year=2009 |format=DOC |publisher=Office of Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan Affairs, Ministry of Culture, P. R. China |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707032101/http://www.culturalink.gov.cn/cnstatic/doc/exhibition/Macaoe.doc |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The bridge is one of the most recognizable landmarks of the territory. The water beneath the lotus and the bridge symbolize Macau's position as a port and its role played in the territory. The five five-pointed stars echo the design of the national flag, symbolizing the relationship Macau has with its mother country.<ref name=\"ambiente\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ambiente.gov.mo/tchinese/07/lotus05/l0508.asp |title=Lotus and the Macao Special Administrative Region of the Regional Flag and Regional Emblem |access-date=2009-11-02 |author=\u694a\u5141\u4e2d |publisher=Macao Special Administrative Region Government and Environment Committee |language=zh |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071223002632/http://www.ambiente.gov.mo/tchinese/07/lotus05/l0508.asp |archive-date = December 23, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The design was chosen on 15 January 1993 by a committee that was drafting the [[Basic Law of Macau|Basic Law]] for the Macau SAR and was formally adopted by the Macau SAR Preparatory Committee on 16 January 1999.<ref name=\"macauadopt\">{{cite web |url = http://www.cdfao.chengdu.gov.cn/list.asp?ClassID=02011006 |title=Flag and Emblem of the Macao SAR |access-date=2009-11-02 |publisher=Chengdu People's Government Foreign Affairs Office |language= zh |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091206193106/http://www.cdfao.chengdu.gov.cn/list.asp?ClassID=02011006 |archive-date=December 6, 2009 }}</ref> The flag was first officially hoisted on 20 December 1999, in the [[Transfer of sovereignty of Macau|handover ceremony]] marking the transfer of sovereignty from [[Portugal]] to China.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lee | first = Khoon Choy | title = Pioneers of Modern China: Understanding the Inscrutable Chinese | publisher = World Scientific Publishing Co | date = November 2005 | location = | pages = 499 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=1jlOQc8BumIC&pg=PT523&dq=Macau+flag&cd=13#v=onepage&q=Macau%20flag | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-981-256-618-8 }}</ref>\n\n== Military flags ==\n{{Main|Flag of the People's Liberation Army}}\n\nThere are six flags that are used by the [[People's Liberation Army]] (PLA). The main feature of these flags is a golden star at the top left corner and two Chinese characters \"{{lang|zh|\u516b\u4e00}}\" to the right of the star, all placed on a red background. The characters \"{{lang|zh|\u516b\u4e00}}\" (literally \"eight one\") pay homage to the [[Nanchang uprising|events]] on August 1, 1927 (8th month, 1st day); this was when the PLA was created by the Communist Party to start their rebellion against the [[Kuomintang]] Government in [[Nanchang]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Fei |last=Wu |title = Military Parade Marks Anniversary |date=2009-10-01 |newspaper=China Daily |url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/60th/2009-10/01/content_8759348.htm |agency = Xinhua |accessdate = 2009-11-04 }}</ref> The main flag of the PLA was created on June 15, 1949 by a decree issued from Mao.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ybsy.gov.cn/gfjy/ShowArticle.asp?ArticleID=1494 |title=Flag of the People's Liberation Army |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2009-01-11 |publisher=Yibin Shuangyong Information Network |language = zh |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707043014/http://www.ybsy.gov.cn/gfjy/ShowArticle.asp?ArticleID=1494 |archive-date=2011-07-07 }}</ref> The flag has a ratio of 5 by 4, which has a white sleeve measuring {{frac|16}} of the flag's length. For ceremonies, a PLA flag with golden fringe is placed on a pole with gold and red spiral stripes and topped with a golden finial and red tassel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.lawtime.cn/d662410667504.html |title=Central Military Commission Provisions On The Military Flag |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=1978-06-17 |language= zh |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513085559/http://law.lawtime.cn/d662410667504.html |archive-date=2009-05-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Each branch of the PLA, the [[People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Ground Forces]], [[People's Liberation Army Navy|Navy]], [[People's Liberation Army Air Force|Air Force]] and [[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force|Rocket Force]], also have their own flags to use. In a 1992 order, the flags of the three branches were defined. The top {{frac|5|8}} of the flags is the same as the PLA flag; the bottom {{frac|3|8}} are occupied by the colors of the branches.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.diyifanwen.com/fanwen/bayijianjunjie/143152262.html |title = 81 Flag and Other Signs |access-date = 2009-11-04 |language=Chinese }}</ref> The flag of the Ground Forces has a forest green bar at the bottom, the naval ensign has stripes of blue and white at the bottom, the Air Force uses a sky blue bar and the Rocket Force uses a yellow bar at the bottom. The forest green represents the earth, the blue and white stripes represent the seas, the sky blue represents the air and the yellow represents the flare of missile launching.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/ziliao/2004-06/23/content_1542456.htm |title = Flag, Emblem and Song of the People's Liberation Army |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2004-06-23 |website = Xinhua Net News |publisher = Xinhua News Agency |language = zh }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://military.people.com.cn/n1/2016/0701/c1011-28516063.html |title = Uniform of Rocket Force |access-date=2016-07-06 |date=2016-07-01 |work = People's Daily |publisher = People's Daily |language = zh}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"120\">\nFile:People's Liberation Army Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background.|[[People's Liberation Army|PLA]]\nFile:Ground Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a green bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Ground Force]]\nFile:Naval Ensign of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag are stripes of blue, white, blue, white and blue.|[[People's Liberation Army Navy|Navy]]\nFile:Air Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a sky blue bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Air Force|Air Force]]\nFile:Rocket Force Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is a yellow bar.|[[People's Liberation Army Rocket Force|Rocket Force]]\nFile:People's Armed Police Flag.svg|alt = A golden star, along with three Chinese characters, placed on a red background. At the bottom of a flag is 3 green bars.|[[People's Armed Police]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Organizational flags ==\nAfter the Communist Party of China was founded in 1920, various sections of the party made flags based on what the [[Bolshevik]]s used, producing various designs and patterns. The current flag of the CPC was not created until April 28, 1942.  On that date, the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau issued a decree announcing the flag and the pattern it should follow.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.hndjw.gov.cn/dangshibolan/dangshiwenzhai/2009-09-14/11415.html |title= History \u2013 Flag of the Communist Party of China |access-date=2009-11-04 |date=2009-09-14 |publisher=Henan Party Network Division | language = zh }}{{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The design was further defined in the CPC Constitution in 1996.<ref name=\"cpcflagcon\">{{cite web |url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/ziliao/2003-01/18/content_695383_1.htm |title=Provisions for Using the Flag and Emblem of the CPC |access-date = 2009-11-05 |date= 1996-09-21 |language = zh }}</ref> The flag has a red background that is charged with the emblem of the CPC in gold at the top left corner.<ref>{{cite book |url = http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#12 |title=Constitution of the Communist Party of China | chapter = XI Party Emblem and Flag |access-date=2009-11-05 |date=2002-11-18 |publisher = [[China International Publishing Group]] |website = [[China Internet Information Center]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018054320/http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/49109.htm#12 |archive-date = October 18, 2007 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The flag ratio is defined as two by three (24\u00d736 units); the size of the emblem is eight units square, placed four units away from the hoist and three units away from the top of the flag.<ref name=\"cpcflagcon\" />\n\nThe flag of the [[Communist Youth League of China]] was adopted on May 4, 1950.  The design of the flag consists of the group emblem, a gold star surrounded by a ring of gold, charged on a red field. The construction of the flag consists of making the top hoist portion of the flag into twelve by eighteen units, placing the emblem in the middle of that rectangle. The radius of the emblem is four units.<ref name=\"cylcflag\">{{cite web| location = CN | url=http://www.nhyouth.gov.cn/news_view.asp?newsid=471 |title=Organization Song, Flag, Emblem and Card |accessdate=2009-11-05 |date=2007-01-06 | publisher = Communist Youth League of China |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nThere are two flags used by the [[Young Pioneers of China]]. The first flag that is used is for pioneer battalions. The length of the flag is 90 centimetres and the width is 120 centimeters.  A golden badge of the Young Pioneers is placed in the center of the flag. For a company, a modified flag is used. The flag has a length of 60 centimetres and a width of 80 centimetres. A 20-centimeter triangle is cut out of the fly edge of the flag and the golden emblem is shifted closer towards the hoist.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.abayouth.gov.cn/html/sxdgz/2007/929/079291015081FDAD8JC96CDAJHIJK8.html |title=Young Pioneers of China Unit Flag |access-date=2009-11-20 |date=2007-09-27 |publisher=Communist Youth League in Sichuan Province |language = zh }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg|alt=A golden, crossed, hammer and sickle placed on a red background.|Communist Party of China\nFile:Flag of the Communist Youth League of China.svg|alt=A golden star placed inside a golden ring, all placed on a red background.|Communist Youth League of China\nFile:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5c11\u5e74\u5148\u950b\u961f\u961f\u65d7 (\u5927\u961f\u65d7).svg|alt=A gold star placed on top of a red torch with a flame, outlined in gold. This is centered on a red background.|Young Pioneers of China (Pioneer Battalions)\nFile:\u4e2d\u56fd\u5c11\u5e74\u5148\u950b\u961f\u961f\u65d7 (\u4e2d\u961f\u65d7).svg|alt=A gold star placed on top of a red torch with a flame, outlined in gold. This is placed on a red background, where the right edge has a triangle section cut out.|Young Pioneers of China (Pioneer Companies)\n</gallery>\n\n==Customs flag==\n[[File:Flag of the Customs of the People's Republic of China.svg|thumb|Customs flag of China]]\nThe customs flag is a China's national flag with the emblem of customs at the lower right corner, which consists of a golden key and the [[Caduceus]] of [[Hermes]], crossing with each other. The current customs flag was officially adopted in October 1, 1953. The customs flag should be hung at the bow of the customs vessel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zhengzhou.customs.gov.cn/publish/portal106/tab1641/module5966/info3564.htm |language=zh-cn |script-title=zh:\u6d77\u5173\u5173\u65d7 |publisher=Zhengzhou Customs |date=2005-08-26 |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731195853/http://zhengzhou.customs.gov.cn/publish/portal106/tab1641/module5966/info3564.htm |archive-date=31 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Historical flags ==\n{{Main list|List of Chinese flags}}\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Flag of the Qing Dynasty (1862-1889).svg|[[Flag of the Qing dynasty]] (1862\u20131889)\nFile:Flag of the Qing Dynasty (1889-1912).svg|Flag of the [[Qing dynasty]] (1889\u20131912)\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China 1912-1928.svg|Flag of the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] (1912\u20131928), representing the [[Five Races Under One Union]] principle\nImage:YuanFlag1.svg|National flag of [[Empire of China (1915\u201316)|Empire of China]] 1916\nImage:YuanFlag2.svg|National flag of [[Empire of China (1915\u201316)|Empire of China]] 1916\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China.svg|[[Flag of the Republic of China]] (1928\u2013present)\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China Army.svg|Flag of the [[National Revolutionary Army]] (1928\u20131947) and the flag of the [[Republic of China Army]] (1947\u2013present)\nFile:Naval Jack of the Republic of China.svg|Flag of the [[Kuomintang]] and the naval jack of the [[Republic of China Navy]] (1947\u2013present)\nFile:Flag of Chinese Taipei for Olympic games.svg|[[Chinese Taipei Olympic flag|Flag of Chinese Taipei]] used by ROC (1984\u2013present)\nFile:National Flag of Chinese Soviet Republic.svg|Flag of the [[Chinese Soviet Republic]] (1931\u20131937)\nFlag of the Chinese Communist Party (Pre-1996).svg|Flag of the Chinese Communist Party before 1996\nFile:Second War Flag of Chinese Soviet Republic.svg|War flag of the Chinese Workers' and Peasants' Red Army\nFile:Flag of the Republic of China-Nanjing (Peace, Anti-Communism, National Construction).svg|The [[Flags of the Reorganized National Government of China|Flag]] of the [[Reorganized National Government of the Republic of China]], a Japanese [[puppet state]] during [[World War II]], was based on the Flag of the Republic of China.\nFile:Flag of Manchukuo.svg|[[Flag of Manchukuo|National flag of Manchukuo]] 1934\u20131945\n</gallery>\n\n==Gallery==\n<center>\n<gallery perrow=\"8\" heights=\"180\" widths=\"180\">\nFile:Boeing 747-4J6 Air China B-2447 (7288535966).jpg|The PRC flag on an [[Air China]] [[Boeing 747-400]].\nFile:Yao Ming with the Chinese flag 2008 Summer Olympics - Opening Ceremony.jpg|[[Yao Ming]] holding the PRC flag during the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] Parade of Nations.\nFile:\u56fd\u65d7 - panoramio.jpg|PRC flag flying on the [[Tiananmen Square]] centre.\nFile:2012 Anti-Japan demonstrations2.jpg|Protesters waving PRC and ROC flags during an [[2012 China anti-Japanese demonstrations|anti-Japan demonstrations]] in [[Hong Kong]] in 2012.\nFile:2015 China Victory Day Parade (1).jpg|Flag of the PRC flying in the [[2015 China Victory Day Parade|2015 Victory Day Parade]].\nFile:Chinese Embassy in Nuku'alofa.jpg|PRC embassy in [[Nuku'alofa]], [[Tonga]] with its national flag.\nFile:March of Nations.JPG|Chinese delegates with the PRC flag marching into the stadium for the World Sports Festival.\nFile:HKSM \u9999\u6e2f\u592a\u7a7a\u9928 Hong Kong Space Museum Astronaut blue uniform Shen Zhou logo n RPChina red flag Jan-2013.JPG|The PRC flag on the uniform of [[Shenzhou 5]] spaceflight mission.\nFile:Guy with a large PRC flag running along side of torch 20080409.jpg|A man in [[San Francisco]] holding the PRC flag during the torch relay for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].\nFile:\u041f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c 70-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b - 40.jpg|The [[People's Liberation Army]] with the PRC banner during the [[2015 Moscow Victory Day Parade]].\nFile:\u00c9l\u00e8ve chinoise Polytechnique.jpg|Chinese students with the PRC flag at [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique]].\nFile:Great Wall of China may 2007.JPG|The flag of the PRC flown on the [[Great Wall of China]].\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Socialism|Heraldry}}\n* [[List of Chinese flags]]\n* [[Emblem of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[March of the Volunteers]]\n* [[Flag of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Red flag (politics)|Red flag]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{FOTW|id=cn|title=China}}\n* [http://www.protocol.gov.hk/flags/eng/n_flag/index.html Official specifications and standard sizes] of the flag.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vXChXT421Ug Hong Kong police demonstration] on raising the flag.\n\n{{-}}\n{{Asia topic|Flag of|title=[[Flags of Asia]]}}\n{{national flags}}\n{{China topics|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flag Of The People's Republic Of China}}\n[[Category:National symbols of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:National flags|China]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1949|China]]\n[[Category:Flags of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:Flags adopted through competition|China]]\n[[Category:Flags of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "199.96.183.109", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added facts about the Chinese virus)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_China"}
{"title_page": "Good Will Hunting", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 American drama film directed by Gus Van Sant}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Good Will Hunting\n| image          = Good Will Hunting.png\n| alt            = Photo of Robin Williams (right, name superimposed at top left) and a smiling Matt Damon (left, name superimposed at top right)\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Gus Van Sant]]\n| producer       = [[Lawrence Bender]]\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Matt Damon]]\n* [[Ben Affleck]]\n| story          = Matt Damon\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n<!-- Per BILLING BLOCK -->\n* [[Robin Williams]]\n* Matt Damon\n* Ben Affleck\n* [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Minnie Driver]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jean-Yves Escoffier]]\n| editing        = [[Pietro Scalia]]\n| studio         = Be Gentlemen<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/60750|title=Good Will Hunting  (1997)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Miramax Films]]<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| released       = {{film date|1997|12|02|[[Bruin Theater]]|1997|12|05|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| country        = United States<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Good Will Hunting (1997) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Good-Will-Hunting#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $225.9 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=Good Will Hunting (1997) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=goodwillhunting.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 27, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Good Will Hunting''''' is a 1997 American [[drama film]] directed by [[Gus Van Sant]], and starring [[Robin Williams]], [[Matt Damon]], [[Ben Affleck]], [[Minnie Driver]], and [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]]. Written by Affleck and Damon, the film follows 20-year-old [[South Boston]] janitor Will Hunting, an unrecognized genius who, as part of a [[deferred prosecution]] agreement after assaulting a police officer, becomes a client of a therapist and studies advanced mathematics with a renowned professor. Through his therapy sessions, Will re-evaluates his relationships with his best friend, his girlfriend, and himself, facing the significant task of confronting his past and thinking about his future.\n\nThe film grossed over $225 million during its theatrical run, from a $10 million budget. For the [[70th Academy Awards|1998 Oscars]] it was nominated for nine [[Academy Awards]], including the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]], and won two: [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Williams and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Affleck and Damon.\n\nIn 2014, it was ranked at number 53 in ''The Hollywood Reporter''{{'}}s \"100 Favorite Films\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/person/good-will-hunting|title=Best Hollywood Movies of All Time - Hollywood Reporter|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nTwenty-year-old Will Hunting ([[Matt Damon]]) of [[South Boston]] is a self-taught genius, though he works as a janitor at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] and spends his free time drinking with his friends, Chuckie, Billy, and Morgan. When Professor Gerald Lambeau posts a difficult mathematics problem on a blackboard as a challenge for his graduate students, Will solves the problem anonymously, stunning both the students and Lambeau. As a challenge to the unknown genius, Lambeau posts an even more difficult problem. Will flees when Lambeau catches him writing the solution on the blackboard late at night. At a bar, Will meets Skylar ([[Minnie Driver]]), a British woman about to graduate from [[Harvard College]], who plans on attending medical school at [[Stanford University School of Medicine|Stanford]].\n\nThe next day, Will and his friends fight a gang who used to bully Will as a child. Will is arrested after he attacks a responding police officer. Lambeau sits in on his court appearance and watches Will defend himself. He arranges for him to avoid jail time if he agrees to study mathematics under Lambeau's supervision and participate in therapy sessions. Will tentatively agrees, but treats his therapists with mockery. In desperation, Lambeau calls on Dr. Sean Maguire, his college roommate, who now teaches psychology at [[Bunker Hill Community College]]. Unlike other therapists, Sean actually challenges Will's [[defense mechanism]]s, and after the first session where Sean threatens Will after he insults his deceased wife and a few unproductive sessions, Will begins to open up.\n\nWill is particularly struck by Sean's story of how he met his wife by giving up his ticket to the historic game six of the [[1975 World Series]], after falling in love at first sight. Sean does not regret his decision, even though his wife died of cancer. This encourages Will to build a relationship with Skylar, though he lies to her about his past and is reluctant to introduce her to his friends or show her his rundown neighborhood. Will also challenges Sean to take an objective look at his own life, since Sean cannot move on from his wife's death.\n\nLambeau sets up a number of job interviews for Will, but Will scorns them by sending Chuckie as his \"chief negotiator\", and by turning down a position at the [[National Security Agency|NSA]] with a scathing critique of the agency's moral position. Skylar asks Will to move to California with her, but he refuses and tells her he is an orphan, and that his foster father physically abused him. Will breaks up with Skylar and later storms out on Lambeau, dismissing the mathematical research he has been doing. Sean points out that Will is so adept at anticipating future failure in his interpersonal relationships that he deliberately sabotages them in order to avoid emotional pain. Chuckie likewise challenges Will over his resistance to taking any of the positions he interviews for, telling Will he owes it to his friends to make the most of opportunities they will never have, even if it means leaving one day without looking back. He then tells Will that the best part of his day is a brief moment when he waits on his doorstep thinking Will has moved on to something greater.\n\nWill walks in on a heated argument between Sean and Lambeau over his potential. Sean and Will share and find out that they were both victims of child abuse. Sean helps Will to see that he is a victim of his own inner demons and to accept that it is not his fault, causing him to break down in tears. Will accepts one of the job offers arranged by Lambeau. Having helped Will overcome his problems, Sean reconciles with Lambeau and decides to take a sabbatical. Will's friends present him with a rebuilt [[Chevrolet Nova]] for his 21st birthday. Later, Chuckie goes to Will's house to pick him up, only to find that he is not there, much to his happiness. Will sends Sean a letter telling him to tell Lambeau that he had to go \"see about a girl\", revealing he passed on the job offer and instead is heading to California to reunite with Skylar.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Matt Damon]] as Will Hunting\n* [[Robin Williams]] as Dr. Sean Maguire\n* [[Ben Affleck]] as Chuckie Sullivan\n* [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]] as Professor Gerald Lambeau\n* [[Minnie Driver]] as Skylar\n* [[Casey Affleck]] as Morgan O'Mally\n* [[Cole Hauser]] as Billy McBride\n* [[John Mighton]] as Tom\n* [[Scott William Winters]] as Clark\n* [[Jimmy Flynn]] as Judge George H. Malone\n* [[Christopher Britton (actor)|Christopher Britton]] as Executive #2\n* [[Alison Folland]] as MIT Student\n* [[George Plimpton]] as Henry Lipkin\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Matt Damon]] started writing the film as a final assignment for a playwriting class he was taking at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"boston\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/2013/01/02/good-will-hunting-oral-history/|title=Good Will Hunting: An Oral History|work=[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]|date=January 2, 2013|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> Instead of writing a one-act play, Damon submitted a 40-page script.<ref name=\"boston\" /> He wrote his then-girlfriend, medical student Skylar Satenstein (credited in the closing credits of the film), into his script.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1432111/the-unlikely-link-between-metallica-and-matt-damon/|title=The Unlikely Link Between Metallica And Matt Damon|date=1998-03-11|work=MTV News|access-date=2018-05-08 }}</ref> Damon said the only scene from that script that survived \u2014 \"it survived verbatim\" \u2014 was when Will Hunting (Damon) meets his therapist, Dr. Maguire ([[Robin Williams]]).<ref name=\"boston\" /> He then came to [[Ben Affleck]] and asked him to develop the screenplay together, and the two completed the script in 1994.<ref name=\"boston\" /> At first, it was written as a thriller about a young man in the rough-and-tumble streets of [[South Boston]] who possesses a superior intelligence and is targeted by the government with heavy-handed recruitment.<ref name=\"boston\" />\n\n[[Castle Rock Entertainment]] bought the script for $675,000 against $775,000, meaning that Damon and Affleck would stand to earn an additional $100,000 if the film was produced and they retained sole writing credit.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Castle Rock president [[Rob Reiner]] urged them to drop the thriller aspect of the story and to focus on the relationship between Will and his therapist. [[Terrence Malick]] told Affleck and Damon over dinner that the film ought to end with Will's decision to follow his girlfriend Skylar to California, not them leaving together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tomshone.blogspot.com/2011/01/how-good-will-hunting-got-its-ending.html|title=THESE VIOLENT DELIGHTS: Malick gave Good Will Hunting its ending|date=2011-01-05|website=THESE VIOLENT DELIGHTS|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n\nAt Reiner's request, screenwriter [[William Goldman]] read the script. Goldman consistently denied the persistent rumor that he wrote ''Good Will Hunting'' or acted as a [[script doctor]]. In his book ''[[Which Lie Did I Tell?]]'' Goldman jokingly writes, \"I did not just doctor it. I wrote the whole thing from scratch,\" before dismissing the rumor as false and saying his only advice was agreeing with Reiner's suggestion.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PmE9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA332#v=onepage|title=Which Lie Did I Tell?: More Adventures in the Screen Trade|last=Goldman|first=William|year=2001|publisher=Vintage Books|pages=332\u2013333|isbn=9780375703195 }}</ref>\n\nAffleck and Damon proposed to act in the lead roles, but many studio executives said they wanted [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Juul | first=Matt | title='Good Will Hunting' Might've Been Very Different Without Sylvester Stallone | url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/2016/01/06/matt-damon-sylvester-stallone-rocky/ | work=[[Boston Magazine]] | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Kevin Smith]] was working with Affleck on ''[[Mallrats]]'' and with both Damon and Affleck on ''[[Chasing Amy]].''<ref>Smith's comments on the ''[[Mallrats]]'' DVD audio commentary</ref> Castle Rock put the script in turnaround, and gave Damon and Affleck 30 days to find another buyer for the script who would reimburse Castle Rock the money paid, otherwise the script reverted to the studio, and Damon and Affleck would be out. All the studios that were involved in the original bidding war for the screenplay now turned the pair down, taking meetings with Affleck and Damon only to tell them this to their face. As a last resort, Affleck passed the script to his ''Chasing Amy'' director Kevin Smith, who read it and promised to walk the script directly into [[Harvey Weinstein]]'s office at Miramax. Weinstein read the script, loved it, and paid Castle Rock their due, while also agreeing to let Damon and Affleck star in the film. In his recollection of the meeting, Weinstein asked about an out-of-place, mid-script [[oral sex]] scene, which Damon and Affleck explained was a test to see which studio executives had actually read the script.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=623Es9ZYmt8&t=25s|title = Harvey Weinstein - The Graham Norton Show|date = Mar 15, 2015 |accessdate = |website = |publisher = BBC America|via= [[YouTube]] |last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=\"boston\" />\n[[File:Dunkin' Donuts, Cambridge, MA.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Baskin-Robbins]]/[[Dunkin' Donuts]], in front of which Will mocked Harvard student Clark (as seen in 2013; as of 2019, it is a ramen restaurant).]]\nAfter buying the rights from Castle Rock, Miramax put the film into production. Several well-known filmmakers were originally considered to direct, including [[Mel Gibson]], [[Michael Mann]], and [[Steven Soderbergh]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Originally, Affleck asked Kevin Smith whether he was interested in directing. He declined, saying they needed a \"good director\" and that he only directs things he writes and is not much of a visual director, but still served as one of the film's executive producers. Damon and Affleck later chose [[Gus Van Sant]] for the job, whose work on previous films like ''[[Drugstore Cowboy]]'' (1989) had left a favorable impression on the fledgling screenwriters. Miramax was persuaded and hired Van Sant to direct the film.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Au Bon Pain, Cambridge, MA.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Au Bon Pain]] in [[Harvard Square]] where Skylar asked Will to explain his \"[[photographic memory]]\" to her (as seen in 2013; it has since been redeveloped by Harvard).]]\nFilming took place between April and June 1997. Although the story is set in Boston, and many of the scenes were done on location in the Greater Boston area, much of the interior shots were filmed at locations in Toronto, with the [[University of Toronto]] standing in for [[MIT]] and [[Harvard University]]. The classroom scenes were filmed at McLennan Physical Laboratories (of the University of Toronto) and [[Central Technical School]]. Harvard normally disallows filming on its property, but permitted limited filming by the project after intervention by Harvard alumnus [[John Lithgow]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=2 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=2 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Likewise, only the exterior shots of [[Bunker Hill Community College]] were filmed in Boston; however, Sean's office was built in Toronto as an exact replica of one at the college.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=21 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=21 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe interior bar scenes set in \"[[South Boston|Southie]]\" were shot on location at Woody's L St. Tavern.<ref>{{cite web | last=Dunn | first=Gabrielle | title=Famous Movie Locations: Woody's L Street Tavern in 'Good Will Hunting' (Boston) | url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/06/03/famous-movie-locations-woodys-l-street-tavern-good-will-hunting-boston/ | work=Blog.moviefone.com | date=June 3, 2010 | accessdate=January 25, 2017 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121203101349/http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/06/03/famous-movie-locations-woodys-l-street-tavern-good-will-hunting-boston/ | archive-date=December 3, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Meanwhile, the homes of Will (190 West 6th Street) and Sean (259 E Street), while some distance apart in the movie, actually back up to each other on Bowen Street, the narrow street Chuckie drives down to walk up to Will's back door.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=6 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=6 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=scenery>{{cite web | url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/magazine/articles/2007/11/25/behind_the_scenery/ | title=Behind the Scenery | work=The Boston Globe | date=November 25, 2007 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Bow and Arrow Pub, which was located at the corner of Bow Street and Massachusetts Avenue in Cambridge, doubled as the Harvard bar in which Will met Skylar for the first time.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=8 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=8 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The [[Baskin-Robbins]]/[[Dunkin' Donuts]] featured in the \"How do you like ''them'' apples?\" scene was next door to the pub at the time of the film's release.<ref name=scenery/>\n\n[[Tasty Sandwich Shop|The Tasty]], at the corner of JFK and Brattle Streets, was the scene of Will and Skylar's first kiss.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=20 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=20 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The [[Au Bon Pain]], where Will and Skylar discuss the former's [[photographic memory]], was at the corner of Dunster Street and Mass Ave.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=23 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=23 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boston Public Garden]] bench on which Will and Sean sat for a scene in the film became a temporary shrine after Williams' death in 2014.<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/2014/08/12/good-will-hunting-bench-boston-public-garden-becomes-robin-williams-memorial/9NupwfvGMPMUolDr9IpsYL/story.html \"\u2018Good Will Hunting\u2019 Bench in Boston Public Garden Becomes Robin Williams Memorial\"] - Boston.com, August 12, 2014</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nIn the film's opening weekend in limited release, it earned $272,912. In its January 1998 wide-release opening weekend, it earned $10,261,471. It went on to gross $138,433,435 in North America and a total worldwide gross of $225,933,435.<ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 97% based on 75 reviews, with an average rating of 8.05/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"It follows a predictable narrative arc, but ''Good Will Hunting'' adds enough quirks to the journey \u2013 and is loaded with enough powerful performances \u2013 that it remains an entertaining, emotionally rich drama.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/good_will_hunting/ |title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 70 out of 100, based on 28 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/good-will-hunting |title=Good Will Hunting Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> At [[CinemaScore]], audiences gave the film a grade \"A\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 |access-date= 2019-07-22 }}</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of four stars, writing that while the story is \"predictable\", it is \"the individual moments, not the payoff, that make it so effective\".<ref>{{cite web |last= Ebert |first= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |url= http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/good-will-hunting-1997 |title= Good Will Hunting Movie Review (1997) |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date= 1997-12-25 |accessdate= 2013-09-01 }}</ref> Duane Byrge of [[The Hollywood Reporter|''The Hollywood Reporter'']] praised the performances of the cast, writing \"The acting is brilliant overall, with special praise to Matt Damon for his ragingly tender portrayal of the boy cursed with genius\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/good-will-hunting-1997-review-952640|title='Good Will Hunting': THR's 1997 Review|last=Byrge|first=Duane|date=1991-12-01|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> Peter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' was equally positive, writing \"The glow goes well beyond a radiant performance by Matt Damon ... Intimate, heartfelt and wickedly funny, it's a movie whose impact lingers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-REVIEW-Will-Has-a-Way-About-It-2788001.php|title=FILM REVIEW -- `Will' Has a Way About It / Williams, Damon are funny and heartfelt in Van Sant's sure-handed drama|last=Stack|first=Peter|last2=Critic|first2=Chronicle Staff|date=1997-12-25|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]], writing for [[Entertainment Weekly|''Entertainment Weekly'']], gave the film a \"B\", stating \"''Good Will Hunting'' is stuffed \u2014 indeed, overstuffed \u2014 with heart, soul, audacity, and blarney. You may not believe a minute of it, but you don\u2019t necessarily want to stop watching\". He also noted Damon's and Williams' chemistry, describing it as \"a quicksilver intercepting each other\u2019s thoughts\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/1997/12/05/good-will-hunting-3/|title=Good Will Hunting|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=1997-12-05|website=EW.com|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']], called the screenplay \"smart and touching\", and praised Van Sant for directing with \"style, shrewdness and clarity\". She also complimented the [[Production designer|production design]] and [[cinematography]], which were able to effortlessly move the viewer from \"classroom to dorm room to neighborhood bar\", in a small setting.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/movies/film-review-logarithms-and-biorhythms-test-a-young-janitor.html|title=FILM REVIEW; Logarithms and Biorhythms Test a Young Janitor|date=1997-12-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  \n\nQuentin Curtis of [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Daily Telegraph'']] opined Williams' performance brought \"sharpness and tenderness\", calling the film a \"crowd-pleaser, with bags of charm to spare. It doesn't bear thinking too much about its message ... Damon and Affleck's writing has real wit and vigour, and some depth\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Curtis|first=Quentin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/11035949/Good-Will-Hunting-review-Robin-Williams-brings-off-sharpness-and-tenderness.html|title=Good Will Hunting, review: 'Robin Williams brings off sharpness and tenderness'|date=2014-08-15|access-date=2020-04-28|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Andrew O'Hehir of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' stated that despite the \"enjoyable characters\", he thought the film was somewhat superficial, writing \"there isn't a whole lot of movie to take home with you ... many will wake the next morning wondering why, with all that talent on hand, it amounts to so little in the end\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/1997/12/05/goodwill/|title=\"Good Will Hunting\"|last=O'Hehir|first=Andrew|date=1997-12-06|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> Writing for the [[BBC]], Nev Pierce gave the film four out of five stars, describing the film as \"touching, without being sentimental\", although he felt some scenes were \"odd lapses into self-help speak\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/12/06/good_will_hunting_1998_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Good Will Hunting|last=Pierce|first=Nev|date=2001-12-06|website=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Emanuel Levy]] of [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] called the film a \"beautifully realized tale ... engaging and often quite touching\". He felt that the film's visual style showcased Van Sant's talent, but the plot was \"quite predictable\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/film/reviews/good-will-hunting-3-1200452429/|title=Good Will Hunting|last=Levy|first=Emanuel|last2=Levy|first2=Emanuel|date=1997-12-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> \n\n===Academic response===\nSeveral scholars have examined the film as a portrayal of [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|residual Catholic\u2013Protestant tensions in Boston]], as [[Irish Catholic]]s from [[South Boston|Southie]] are aligned against ostensibly [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|Protestant]] characters who are affiliated with [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]].<ref name=\"Herlihy-Mera\">{{cite journal|last=Herlihy-Mera|first=Jeffrey |url=https://www.academia.edu/1548918 |title=Revisioning Migration: On the Stratifications of Irish Boston in Good Will Hunting |journal=ALIF: Journal of Comparative Poetics|volume=32 |date=2012 |pages=1\u201322 |isbn=9789774165283 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n;'''[[70th Academy Awards]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1998/G?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees|title=70th Annual Academy Awards Nominees & Winners|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=August 27, 2016}}</ref>\n: '''Won''': [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Robin Williams]]\n: '''Won''': [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]] \u2013 [[Ben Affleck]] & [[Matt Damon]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] \u2013 [[Lawrence Bender]] (producer)\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Director]] \u2013 [[Gus Van Sant]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] \u2013 Matt Damon\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Minnie Driver]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing]] \u2013 [[Pietro Scalia]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Academy Award for Best Original Dramatic Score]] \u2013 [[Danny Elfman]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] \u2013 \"Miss Misery\" (music and lyrics by [[Elliott Smith]])\n\n;'''[[55th Golden Globe Awards]]''':\n: '''Won''': [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay]] \u2013 Ben Affleck & Matt Damon<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/19/movies/titanic-wins-top-golden-globe-award.html | title='Titanic' Wins Top Golden Globe Award | last=Sterngold | first=James | date=January 19, 1998 | accessdate=August 27, 2016 | work= [[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]]<ref name=\"globes\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9712/18/golden.globes.list/index.html| title=Nominees for Golden Globe Awards | date=1997 | accessdate=August 27, 2016 | work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]] \u2013 Matt Damon<ref name=\"globes\" />\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] \u2013 Robin Williams<ref name=\"globes\" />\n\n;'''[[4th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/4th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 4th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards {{!}} Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=www.sagawards.org |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>:\n: '''Won''': [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role]] \u2013 Robin Williams\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 Matt Damon\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role]] \u2013 Minnie Driver\n\n;'''Other Major Awards / Nominations''':\n: '''Won''': [[Berlin International Film Festival|Silver Bear for Outstanding Single Achievement]] \u2013 Matt Damon<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/03_preistr_ger_1998/03_Preistraeger_1998.html |title=Berlinale: 1998 Prize Winners |accessdate=2012-01-16 |work=[[Berlinale]].de}}</ref>\n: '''Won''': [[Humanitas Prize]] for Feature Film \u2013 Matt Damon & Ben Affleck<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/1998/film/news/damon-affleck-win-humanitas-pic-prize-1117478325/|title=Damon, Affleck win Humanitas pic prize|last=Olson|first=Eric J.|date=1998-07-10|work=Variety|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Directors Guild of America|Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Motion Pictures]] \u2013 Gus Van Sant<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/1998/0126-DGA-Announces-Five-Nominees-for-Outstanding-Directorial-Achievement-in-Feature-Film.aspx|title=DGA Announces Five Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Feature Film for 1997 -|website=www.dga.org |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Writers Guild of America, west|Writers Guild of America Award for Best Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen]] \u2013 Ben Affleck & Matt Damon<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/2015-valentine-davies-award-ben-affleck|title=Screenwriter-Director-Actor Ben Affleck to Receive WGAW's 2015 Valentine Davies Award|website=awards.wga.org|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Good Will Hunting: Music from the Miramax Motion Picture\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Various artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 2, 1997\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]], [[indie rock]], [[acoustic rock]], [[indie folk]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe musical score for ''Good Will Hunting'' was composed by [[Danny Elfman]], who had previously collaborated with [[Gus Van Sant]] on ''[[To Die For]]'' and would go on to score many of the director's other films.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.parkrecord.com/entertainment/filmmaker-gus-van-sant-and-composer-danny-elfman-talk-of-their-collaborations/|title=Filmmaker Gus Van Sant and composer Danny Elfman talk of their collaborations|access-date=2018-05-11 }}</ref> The film also features many songs written and recorded by singer-songwriter [[Elliott Smith]]. His song \"[[Miss Misery]]\" was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]], but lost to \"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\" from ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2013/01/10/elliott-smiths-music-good-hunting/|title=How Elliott Smith\u2019s Music Transformed Good Will Hunting \u2013 Boston Magazine|date=2013-01-10|work=Boston Magazine|access-date=2018-05-10 }}</ref> Elfman's score was also nominated for an [[Academy Award|Oscar]], but lost to ''Titanic'' as well. On September 11, 2006, ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'' used Elfman's song \"Weepy Donuts\" while [[Matt Lauer]] spoke during the opening credits.\n\nA soundtrack album for the film was released by [[Capitol Records]] on November 18, 1997, though only two of Elfman's cues appear on the release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Original Soundtrack|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/good-will-hunting-mw0000030450|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=All Media Network, LLC|accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/cinema-sounds-good-will-hunting-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/|title=Cinema Sounds: Good Will Hunting|date=2009-08-26|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-05-11 }}</ref>\n\n# [[Elliott Smith]] \u2013 \"Between the Bars\" (Orchestral)\n# [[Jeb Loy Nichols]] \u2013 \"As the Rain\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"Angeles\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"No Name #3\"\n# [[The Waterboys]] \u2013 \"[[Fisherman's Blues (song)|Fisherman's Blues]]\"\n# [[Luscious Jackson]] \u2013 \"Why Do I Lie?\"\n# [[Danny Elfman]] \u2013 \"Will Hunting\" (Main Titles)\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Between the Bars]]\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Say Yes (Elliott Smith song)|Say Yes]]\"\n# [[Gerry Rafferty]] \u2013 \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\"\n# [[Andru Donalds]] \u2013 \"Somebody's Baby\"\n# [[The Dandy Warhols]] \u2013 \"[[Boys Better]]\"\n# [[Al Green]] \u2013 \"How Can You Mend a Broken Heart?\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Miss Misery (song)|Miss Misery]]\"\n# [[Danny Elfman]] \u2013 \"Weepy Donuts\"\n\n\"[[Afternoon Delight]]\" by the [[Starland Vocal Band]] was featured in the film, but did not appear on the soundtrack album.\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Good Will Hunting: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Danny Elfman, Elliott Smith\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 3, 2014\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Music Box Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nA limited edition soundtrack album featuring Elfman's complete score from the film was released by Music Box Records on March 3, 2014. The soundtrack, issued in 1500 copies, includes all of Elfman's cues (including music not featured on the rare Miramax Academy promo) and also contains the songs by Elliott Smith. One of the tracks is Smith's songs with Elfman's arrangements added into the mix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Danny Elfman|url=http://www.musicbox-records.com/en/cd-catalog/60-good-will-hunting.html|work=Music Box Records|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n# Main Title (2:44)\n# Genie Mopper (0:37)\n# First Calculation (1:08)\n# Theorem (0:42)\n# Kick Ass Choir (0:59)\n# Mystery Math (2:28)\n# Them Apples (0:57)\n# Jail (1:13)\n# Second Shrink (1:14)\n# Any Port (1:25)\n# Times Up (1:14)\n# Oliver Twist (1:58)\n# Staring Contest (0:49)\n# Secret Weapon (0:57)\n# Retainer (Part A) (0:58)\n# Retainer (Part B) (0:20)\n# Tell You Something (0:48)\n# No Love Me (0:47)\n# Fire Music (1:11)\n# Whose Fault (2:34)\n# End Titles (3:50)\n# Between the Bars (Orchestral) (1:09) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith / Arr. by Elfman\n# No Name #3 (3:04) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Say Yes (2:15) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Between the Bars (2:21) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Angeles (2:55) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Miss Misery (3:12) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n\n==Mathematics==\nIn an early version of the script, Will Hunting was going to be a physics prodigy, but Nobel Laureate in Physics [[Sheldon Lee Glashow|Sheldon Glashow]] at Harvard told Damon the subject should be math instead of physics. Glashow referred Damon to his brother-in-law, [[Daniel Kleitman]], a mathematics professor at MIT. In the spring of 1997, Damon and Affleck asked Kleitman to \"speak math to us\" for writing realistic dialogue, so Kleitman invited postdoc [[Tom Bohman]] to join him giving them a \"quick lecture\". When asked for a problem that Will could solve, Kleitman and Bohman suggested the unsolved computer science [[P versus NP problem]], but the movie used other problems. [[Columbia University]]'s physics and math professor [[Brian Greene]] at the [[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]] [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation|Sloan]] retrospective explained that for physics, \"Having some deep insight about the universe [\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060] typically [\u2060\u200a\u2060is\u200a\u2060] a group project in the modern era,\" while \"doing some mathematical theorem is a singular undertaking very often.\"<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/good-will-hunting-matt-damon-harvard-professor-helped-change-movie-2015-4|title=One of Matt Damon's Harvard professors gave him a small note that completely changed 'Good Will Hunting'|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref><ref name=\"mit\">{{Cite news|url=https://alum.mit.edu/slice/how-mit-professor-helped-good-will-hunting-get-math-right-and-landed-tiny-role-film|title=How an MIT Professor Helped Good Will Hunting Get the Math Right\u2014and Landed a Tiny Role in the Film|access-date=2018-05-10|last=London|first=Jay|work=MIT Alumni - Slice of MIT }}</ref>\n\nPatrick O'Donnell, professor of physics at [[University of Toronto]], served as mathematical consultant for the film production.<ref>O'Donnell relied on ''Graph Theory and Theoretical Physics'' by [[Frank Harary]] where at page 63 P.W. Kasteleyn wrote on \"Graph theory and crystal physics\".</ref>\n\nThe main hallway blackboard is used twice to reveal Will Hunting's talent, first to the audience, second to Professor Lambeau. Matt Damon based it on his artist brother Kyle visiting MIT's [[Infinite Corridor]] and writing \"an incredibly elaborate, totally fake, version of an equation\" on a blackboard which lasted for months. Kyle returned to Matt saying MIT needed these blackboards \"because these kids are so smart they just need to, you know, drop everything and solve problems!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/matt-damon-commencement-address-0603|title=Matt Damon's Commencement address|work=MIT News|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nThe first turning point in the plot occurs when Will sets aside his mop in a hallway and studies a difficult blackboard [[graph theory]] problem posed by Professor Lambeau.<ref>[[Burkard Polster]] & Marty Ross (2012) ''Math goes to the Movies'', [[Johns Hopkins University Press]], page 9, {{ISBN|1-4214-0483-4}}</ref> The question is to find the number of 3-step [[walk (graph theory)|walks]] in a given graph. Will chalks up the [[adjacency matrix]]\n:<math>A=\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0& 1 \\\\ 1 & 0 & 2 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 2 & 0 & 0 \\\\ 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}.</math> To answer the question, he finds the third power matrix:\n:<math>A^3=\\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 7 & 2 & 3 \\\\ 7 & 2 & 12 & 7 \\\\ 2 & 12 & 0 & 2 \\\\ 3 & 7 & 2 & 2 \\end{pmatrix}.</math>\nThe other characters are astounded that a janitor could show such facility with [[matrix (mathematics)|matrices]] applied this way.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|1990s}}\n* [[The Man Who Knew Infinity (film)|''The Man Who Knew Infinity'']]\n* [[Ramanujan (film)|''Ramanujan'']]<!-- a different biopic about the same man -->\n* [[List of films about mathematicians]]\n* ''[[Farmers and Fishermen: Two Centuries of Work in Essex County, Massachusetts, 1630\u20131850]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119217|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{tcmdb title|324221|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{AllMovie title|160083|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{mojo title|goodwillhunting|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|good_will_hunting|Good Will Hunting}}\n* [http://www.imsdb.com/scripts/Good-Will-Hunting.html Screenplay on IMSDb]\n* {{cite web|last=Grime|first=James|title=The Real Good Will Hunting|url=http://www.numberphile.com/videos/who_was_good_will_hunting.html|work=Numberphile|publisher=[[Brady Haran]]|access-date=2013-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419123013/http://www.numberphile.com/videos/who_was_good_will_hunting.html|archive-date=2017-04-19|url-status=dead}}\n* [http://www.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later/ Then & Now: Revisiting ''Good Will Hunting''] \u2013 Boston.com\n\n{{Gus Van Sant}}\n{{Ben Affleck}}\n{{Matt Damon}}\n\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1997 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Elliott Smith]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gus Van Sant]]\n[[Category:Films about academia]]\n[[Category:Films about educators]]\n[[Category:Films about mathematics]]\n[[Category:Films about orphans]]\n[[Category:Films about psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1997]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Harvard University]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Harvard Square]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ben Affleck]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matt Damon]]\n[[Category:Works about janitors]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of mathematicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 American drama film directed by Gus Van Sant}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Good Will Hunting\n| image          = \n| alt            = Photo of Robin Williams (right, name superimposed at top left) and a smiling Matt Damon (left, name superimposed at top right)\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Gus Van Sant]]\n| producer       = [[Lawrence Bender]]\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Matt Damon]]\n* [[Ben Affleck]]\n| story          = Matt Damon\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n<!-- Per BILLING BLOCK -->\n* [[Robin Williams]]\n* Matt Damon\n* Ben Affleck\n* [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]]\n* [[Minnie Driver]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Danny Elfman]]\n| cinematography = [[Jean-Yves Escoffier]]\n| editing        = [[Pietro Scalia]]\n| studio         = Be Gentlemen<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/60750|title=Good Will Hunting  (1997)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[Miramax Films]]<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| released       = {{film date|1997|12|02|[[Bruin Theater]]|1997|12|05|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| country        = United States<ref name=\"afi\" />\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Good Will Hunting (1997) - Financial Information |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Good-Will-Hunting#tab=summary |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $225.9 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=Good Will Hunting (1997) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=goodwillhunting.htm |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 27, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Good Will Hunting''''' is a 1997 American [[drama film]] directed by [[Gus Van Sant]], and starring [[Robin Williams]], [[Matt Damon]], [[Ben Affleck]], [[Minnie Driver]], and [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]]. Written by Affleck and Damon, the film follows 20-year-old [[South Boston]] janitor Will Hunting, an unrecognized genius who, as part of a [[deferred prosecution]] agreement after assaulting a police officer, becomes a client of a therapist and studies advanced mathematics with a renowned professor. Through his therapy sessions, Will re-evaluates his relationships with his best friend, his girlfriend, and himself, facing the significant task of confronting his past and thinking about his future.\n\nThe film grossed over $225 million during its theatrical run, from a $10 million budget. For the [[70th Academy Awards|1998 Oscars]] it was nominated for nine [[Academy Awards]], including the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]], and won two: [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for Williams and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for Affleck and Damon.\n\nIn 2014, it was ranked at number 53 in ''The Hollywood Reporter''{{'}}s \"100 Favorite Films\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/person/good-will-hunting|title=Best Hollywood Movies of All Time - Hollywood Reporter|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nTwenty-year-old Will Hunting ([[Matt Damon]]) of [[South Boston]] is a self-taught genius, though he works as a janitor at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] and spends his free time drinking with his friends, Chuckie, Billy, and Morgan. When Professor Gerald Lambeau posts a difficult mathematics problem on a blackboard as a challenge for his graduate students, Will solves the problem anonymously, stunning both the students and Lambeau. As a challenge to the unknown genius, Lambeau posts an even more difficult problem. Will flees when Lambeau catches him writing the solution on the blackboard late at night. At a bar, Will meets Skylar ([[Minnie Driver]]), a British woman about to graduate from [[Harvard College]], who plans on attending medical school at [[Stanford University School of Medicine|Stanford]].\n\nThe next day, Will and his friends fight a gang who used to bully Will as a child. Will is arrested after he attacks a responding police officer. Lambeau sits in on his court appearance and watches Will defend himself. He arranges for him to avoid jail time if he agrees to study mathematics under Lambeau's supervision and participate in therapy sessions. Will tentatively agrees, but treats his therapists with mockery. In desperation, Lambeau calls on Dr. Sean Maguire, his college roommate, who now teaches psychology at [[Bunker Hill Community College]]. Unlike other therapists, Sean actually challenges Will's [[defense mechanism]]s, and after the first session where Sean threatens Will after he insults his deceased wife and a few unproductive sessions, Will begins to open up.\n\nWill is particularly struck by Sean's story of how he met his wife by giving up his ticket to the historic game six of the [[1975 World Series]], after falling in love at first sight. Sean does not regret his decision, even though his wife died of cancer. This encourages Will to build a relationship with Skylar, though he lies to her about his past and is reluctant to introduce her to his friends or show her his rundown neighborhood. Will also challenges Sean to take an objective look at his own life, since Sean cannot move on from his wife's death.\n\nLambeau sets up a number of job interviews for Will, but Will scorns them by sending Chuckie as his \"chief negotiator\", and by turning down a position at the [[National Security Agency|NSA]] with a scathing critique of the agency's moral position. Skylar asks Will to move to California with her, but he refuses and tells her he is an orphan, and that his foster father physically abused him. Will breaks up with Skylar and later storms out on Lambeau, dismissing the mathematical research he has been doing. Sean points out that Will is so adept at anticipating future failure in his interpersonal relationships that he deliberately sabotages them in order to avoid emotional pain. Chuckie likewise challenges Will over his resistance to taking any of the positions he interviews for, telling Will he owes it to his friends to make the most of opportunities they will never have, even if it means leaving one day without looking back. He then tells Will that the best part of his day is a brief moment when he waits on his doorstep thinking Will has moved on to something greater.\n\nWill walks in on a heated argument between Sean and Lambeau over his potential. Sean and Will share and find out that they were both victims of child abuse. Sean helps Will to see that he is a victim of his own inner demons and to accept that it is not his fault, causing him to break down in tears. Will accepts one of the job offers arranged by Lambeau. Having helped Will overcome his problems, Sean reconciles with Lambeau and decides to take a sabbatical. Will's friends present him with a rebuilt [[Chevrolet Nova]] for his 21st birthday. Later, Chuckie goes to Will's house to pick him up, only to find that he is not there, much to his happiness. Will sends Sean a letter telling him to tell Lambeau that he had to go \"see about a girl\", revealing he passed on the job offer and instead is heading to California to reunite with Skylar.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Matt Damon]] as Will Hunting\n* [[Robin Williams]] as Dr. Sean Maguire\n* [[Ben Affleck]] as Chuckie Sullivan\n* [[Stellan Skarsg\u00e5rd]] as Professor Gerald Lambeau\n* [[Minnie Driver]] as Skylar\n* [[Casey Affleck]] as Morgan O'Mally\n* [[Cole Hauser]] as Billy McBride\n* [[John Mighton]] as Tom\n* [[Scott William Winters]] as Clark\n* [[Jimmy Flynn]] as Judge George H. Malone\n* [[Christopher Britton (actor)|Christopher Britton]] as Executive #2\n* [[Alison Folland]] as MIT Student\n* [[George Plimpton]] as Henry Lipkin\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Matt Damon]] started writing the film as a final assignment for a playwriting class he was taking at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"boston\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/2013/01/02/good-will-hunting-oral-history/|title=Good Will Hunting: An Oral History|work=[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]|date=January 2, 2013|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> Instead of writing a one-act play, Damon submitted a 40-page script.<ref name=\"boston\" /> He wrote his then-girlfriend, medical student Skylar Satenstein (credited in the closing credits of the film), into his script.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1432111/the-unlikely-link-between-metallica-and-matt-damon/|title=The Unlikely Link Between Metallica And Matt Damon|date=1998-03-11|work=MTV News|access-date=2018-05-08 }}</ref> Damon said the only scene from that script that survived \u2014 \"it survived verbatim\" \u2014 was when Will Hunting (Damon) meets his therapist, Dr. Maguire ([[Robin Williams]]).<ref name=\"boston\" /> He then came to [[Ben Affleck]] and asked him to develop the screenplay together, and the two completed the script in 1994.<ref name=\"boston\" /> At first, it was written as a thriller about a young man in the rough-and-tumble streets of [[South Boston]] who possesses a superior intelligence and is targeted by the government with heavy-handed recruitment.<ref name=\"boston\" />\n\n[[Castle Rock Entertainment]] bought the script for $675,000 against $775,000, meaning that Damon and Affleck would stand to earn an additional $100,000 if the film was produced and they retained sole writing credit.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Castle Rock president [[Rob Reiner]] urged them to drop the thriller aspect of the story and to focus on the relationship between Will and his therapist. [[Terrence Malick]] told Affleck and Damon over dinner that the film ought to end with Will's decision to follow his girlfriend Skylar to California, not them leaving together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tomshone.blogspot.com/2011/01/how-good-will-hunting-got-its-ending.html|title=THESE VIOLENT DELIGHTS: Malick gave Good Will Hunting its ending|date=2011-01-05|website=THESE VIOLENT DELIGHTS|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>\n\nAt Reiner's request, screenwriter [[William Goldman]] read the script. Goldman consistently denied the persistent rumor that he wrote ''Good Will Hunting'' or acted as a [[script doctor]]. In his book ''[[Which Lie Did I Tell?]]'' Goldman jokingly writes, \"I did not just doctor it. I wrote the whole thing from scratch,\" before dismissing the rumor as false and saying his only advice was agreeing with Reiner's suggestion.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PmE9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA332#v=onepage|title=Which Lie Did I Tell?: More Adventures in the Screen Trade|last=Goldman|first=William|year=2001|publisher=Vintage Books|pages=332\u2013333|isbn=9780375703195 }}</ref>\n\nAffleck and Damon proposed to act in the lead roles, but many studio executives said they wanted [[Brad Pitt]] and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Juul | first=Matt | title='Good Will Hunting' Might've Been Very Different Without Sylvester Stallone | url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/arts-entertainment/2016/01/06/matt-damon-sylvester-stallone-rocky/ | work=[[Boston Magazine]] | date=January 6, 2016 | accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Kevin Smith]] was working with Affleck on ''[[Mallrats]]'' and with both Damon and Affleck on ''[[Chasing Amy]].''<ref>Smith's comments on the ''[[Mallrats]]'' DVD audio commentary</ref> Castle Rock put the script in turnaround, and gave Damon and Affleck 30 days to find another buyer for the script who would reimburse Castle Rock the money paid, otherwise the script reverted to the studio, and Damon and Affleck would be out. All the studios that were involved in the original bidding war for the screenplay now turned the pair down, taking meetings with Affleck and Damon only to tell them this to their face. As a last resort, Affleck passed the script to his ''Chasing Amy'' director Kevin Smith, who read it and promised to walk the script directly into [[Harvey Weinstein]]'s office at Miramax. Weinstein read the script, loved it, and paid Castle Rock their due, while also agreeing to let Damon and Affleck star in the film. In his recollection of the meeting, Weinstein asked about an out-of-place, mid-script [[oral sex]] scene, which Damon and Affleck explained was a test to see which studio executives had actually read the script.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=623Es9ZYmt8&t=25s|title = Harvey Weinstein - The Graham Norton Show|date = Mar 15, 2015 |accessdate = |website = |publisher = BBC America|via= [[YouTube]] |last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=\"boston\" />\n[[File:Dunkin' Donuts, Cambridge, MA.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Baskin-Robbins]]/[[Dunkin' Donuts]], in front of which Will mocked Harvard student Clark (as seen in 2013; as of 2019, it is a ramen restaurant).]]\nAfter buying the rights from Castle Rock, Miramax put the film into production. Several well-known filmmakers were originally considered to direct, including [[Mel Gibson]], [[Michael Mann]], and [[Steven Soderbergh]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} Originally, Affleck asked Kevin Smith whether he was interested in directing. He declined, saying they needed a \"good director\" and that he only directs things he writes and is not much of a visual director, but still served as one of the film's executive producers. Damon and Affleck later chose [[Gus Van Sant]] for the job, whose work on previous films like ''[[Drugstore Cowboy]]'' (1989) had left a favorable impression on the fledgling screenwriters. Miramax was persuaded and hired Van Sant to direct the film.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Au Bon Pain, Cambridge, MA.JPG|thumb|left|The [[Au Bon Pain]] in [[Harvard Square]] where Skylar asked Will to explain his \"[[photographic memory]]\" to her (as seen in 2013; it has since been redeveloped by Harvard).]]\nFilming took place between April and June 1997. Although the story is set in Boston, and many of the scenes were done on location in the Greater Boston area, much of the interior shots were filmed at locations in Toronto, with the [[University of Toronto]] standing in for [[MIT]] and [[Harvard University]]. The classroom scenes were filmed at McLennan Physical Laboratories (of the University of Toronto) and [[Central Technical School]]. Harvard normally disallows filming on its property, but permitted limited filming by the project after intervention by Harvard alumnus [[John Lithgow]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=2 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=2 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Likewise, only the exterior shots of [[Bunker Hill Community College]] were filmed in Boston; however, Sean's office was built in Toronto as an exact replica of one at the college.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=21 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=21 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe interior bar scenes set in \"[[South Boston|Southie]]\" were shot on location at Woody's L St. Tavern.<ref>{{cite web | last=Dunn | first=Gabrielle | title=Famous Movie Locations: Woody's L Street Tavern in 'Good Will Hunting' (Boston) | url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/06/03/famous-movie-locations-woodys-l-street-tavern-good-will-hunting-boston/ | work=Blog.moviefone.com | date=June 3, 2010 | accessdate=January 25, 2017 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121203101349/http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/06/03/famous-movie-locations-woodys-l-street-tavern-good-will-hunting-boston/ | archive-date=December 3, 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Meanwhile, the homes of Will (190 West 6th Street) and Sean (259 E Street), while some distance apart in the movie, actually back up to each other on Bowen Street, the narrow street Chuckie drives down to walk up to Will's back door.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=6 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=6 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref name=scenery>{{cite web | url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/magazine/articles/2007/11/25/behind_the_scenery/ | title=Behind the Scenery | work=The Boston Globe | date=November 25, 2007 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Bow and Arrow Pub, which was located at the corner of Bow Street and Massachusetts Avenue in Cambridge, doubled as the Harvard bar in which Will met Skylar for the first time.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=8 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=8 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The [[Baskin-Robbins]]/[[Dunkin' Donuts]] featured in the \"How do you like ''them'' apples?\" scene was next door to the pub at the time of the film's release.<ref name=scenery/>\n\n[[Tasty Sandwich Shop|The Tasty]], at the corner of JFK and Brattle Streets, was the scene of Will and Skylar's first kiss.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=20 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=20 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The [[Au Bon Pain]], where Will and Skylar discuss the former's [[photographic memory]], was at the corner of Dunster Street and Mass Ave.<ref>{{cite web | last=Ba Tran | first=Andrew | title=Then and Now: Revisiting 'Good Will Hunting' | url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later?pg=23 | work=Boston.com | publisher=The New York Times Co. | page=23 | accessdate=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Boston Public Garden]] bench on which Will and Sean sat for a scene in the film became a temporary shrine after Williams' death in 2014.<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/2014/08/12/good-will-hunting-bench-boston-public-garden-becomes-robin-williams-memorial/9NupwfvGMPMUolDr9IpsYL/story.html \"\u2018Good Will Hunting\u2019 Bench in Boston Public Garden Becomes Robin Williams Memorial\"] - Boston.com, August 12, 2014</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nIn the film's opening weekend in limited release, it earned $272,912. In its January 1998 wide-release opening weekend, it earned $10,261,471. It went on to gross $138,433,435 in North America and a total worldwide gross of $225,933,435.<ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 97% based on 75 reviews, with an average rating of 8.05/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"It follows a predictable narrative arc, but ''Good Will Hunting'' adds enough quirks to the journey \u2013 and is loaded with enough powerful performances \u2013 that it remains an entertaining, emotionally rich drama.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/good_will_hunting/ |title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 70 out of 100, based on 28 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/good-will-hunting |title=Good Will Hunting Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More at Metacritic |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> At [[CinemaScore]], audiences gave the film a grade \"A\" on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 |access-date= 2019-07-22 }}</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of four stars, writing that while the story is \"predictable\", it is \"the individual moments, not the payoff, that make it so effective\".<ref>{{cite web |last= Ebert |first= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |url= http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/good-will-hunting-1997 |title= Good Will Hunting Movie Review (1997) |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date= 1997-12-25 |accessdate= 2013-09-01 }}</ref> Duane Byrge of [[The Hollywood Reporter|''The Hollywood Reporter'']] praised the performances of the cast, writing \"The acting is brilliant overall, with special praise to Matt Damon for his ragingly tender portrayal of the boy cursed with genius\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/good-will-hunting-1997-review-952640|title='Good Will Hunting': THR's 1997 Review|last=Byrge|first=Duane|date=1991-12-01|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> Peter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' was equally positive, writing \"The glow goes well beyond a radiant performance by Matt Damon ... Intimate, heartfelt and wickedly funny, it's a movie whose impact lingers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-REVIEW-Will-Has-a-Way-About-It-2788001.php|title=FILM REVIEW -- `Will' Has a Way About It / Williams, Damon are funny and heartfelt in Van Sant's sure-handed drama|last=Stack|first=Peter|last2=Critic|first2=Chronicle Staff|date=1997-12-25|website=SFGate|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]], writing for [[Entertainment Weekly|''Entertainment Weekly'']], gave the film a \"B\", stating \"''Good Will Hunting'' is stuffed \u2014 indeed, overstuffed \u2014 with heart, soul, audacity, and blarney. You may not believe a minute of it, but you don\u2019t necessarily want to stop watching\". He also noted Damon's and Williams' chemistry, describing it as \"a quicksilver intercepting each other\u2019s thoughts\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/1997/12/05/good-will-hunting-3/|title=Good Will Hunting|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=1997-12-05|website=EW.com|language=EN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']], called the screenplay \"smart and touching\", and praised Van Sant for directing with \"style, shrewdness and clarity\". She also complimented the [[Production designer|production design]] and [[cinematography]], which were able to effortlessly move the viewer from \"classroom to dorm room to neighborhood bar\", in a small setting.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/movies/film-review-logarithms-and-biorhythms-test-a-young-janitor.html|title=FILM REVIEW; Logarithms and Biorhythms Test a Young Janitor|date=1997-12-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-28|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  \n\nQuentin Curtis of [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Daily Telegraph'']] opined Williams' performance brought \"sharpness and tenderness\", calling the film a \"crowd-pleaser, with bags of charm to spare. It doesn't bear thinking too much about its message ... Damon and Affleck's writing has real wit and vigour, and some depth\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Curtis|first=Quentin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/11035949/Good-Will-Hunting-review-Robin-Williams-brings-off-sharpness-and-tenderness.html|title=Good Will Hunting, review: 'Robin Williams brings off sharpness and tenderness'|date=2014-08-15|access-date=2020-04-28|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Andrew O'Hehir of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' stated that despite the \"enjoyable characters\", he thought the film was somewhat superficial, writing \"there isn't a whole lot of movie to take home with you ... many will wake the next morning wondering why, with all that talent on hand, it amounts to so little in the end\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/1997/12/05/goodwill/|title=\"Good Will Hunting\"|last=O'Hehir|first=Andrew|date=1997-12-06|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> Writing for the [[BBC]], Nev Pierce gave the film four out of five stars, describing the film as \"touching, without being sentimental\", although he felt some scenes were \"odd lapses into self-help speak\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/12/06/good_will_hunting_1998_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Good Will Hunting|last=Pierce|first=Nev|date=2001-12-06|website=www.bbc.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> [[Emanuel Levy]] of [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] called the film a \"beautifully realized tale ... engaging and often quite touching\". He felt that the film's visual style showcased Van Sant's talent, but the plot was \"quite predictable\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1997/film/reviews/good-will-hunting-3-1200452429/|title=Good Will Hunting|last=Levy|first=Emanuel|last2=Levy|first2=Emanuel|date=1997-12-01|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> \n\n===Academic response===\nSeveral scholars have examined the film as a portrayal of [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|residual Catholic\u2013Protestant tensions in Boston]], as [[Irish Catholic]]s from [[South Boston|Southie]] are aligned against ostensibly [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|Protestant]] characters who are affiliated with [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]].<ref name=\"Herlihy-Mera\">{{cite journal|last=Herlihy-Mera|first=Jeffrey |url=https://www.academia.edu/1548918 |title=Revisioning Migration: On the Stratifications of Irish Boston in Good Will Hunting |journal=ALIF: Journal of Comparative Poetics|volume=32 |date=2012 |pages=1\u201322 |isbn=9789774165283 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n;'''[[70th Academy Awards]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1998/G?qt-honorees=1#block-quicktabs-honorees|title=70th Annual Academy Awards Nominees & Winners|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=August 27, 2016}}</ref>\n: '''Won''': [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] \u2013 [[Robin Williams]]\n: '''Won''': [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]] \u2013 [[Ben Affleck]] & [[Matt Damon]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] \u2013 [[Lawrence Bender]] (producer)\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Director]] \u2013 [[Gus Van Sant]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] \u2013 Matt Damon\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] \u2013 [[Minnie Driver]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing]] \u2013 [[Pietro Scalia]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Academy Award for Best Original Dramatic Score]] \u2013 [[Danny Elfman]]\n: Nominated: [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] \u2013 \"Miss Misery\" (music and lyrics by [[Elliott Smith]])\n\n;'''[[55th Golden Globe Awards]]''':\n: '''Won''': [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay]] \u2013 Ben Affleck & Matt Damon<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/19/movies/titanic-wins-top-golden-globe-award.html | title='Titanic' Wins Top Golden Globe Award | last=Sterngold | first=James | date=January 19, 1998 | accessdate=August 27, 2016 | work= [[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]]<ref name=\"globes\">{{cite web| url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9712/18/golden.globes.list/index.html| title=Nominees for Golden Globe Awards | date=1997 | accessdate=August 27, 2016 | work=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]] \u2013 Matt Damon<ref name=\"globes\" />\n: Nominated: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture]] \u2013 Robin Williams<ref name=\"globes\" />\n\n;'''[[4th Screen Actors Guild Awards]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/4th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 4th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards {{!}} Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=www.sagawards.org |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>:\n: '''Won''': [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role]] \u2013 Robin Williams\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 Matt Damon\n: Nominated: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role]] \u2013 Minnie Driver\n\n;'''Other Major Awards / Nominations''':\n: '''Won''': [[Berlin International Film Festival|Silver Bear for Outstanding Single Achievement]] \u2013 Matt Damon<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/03_preistr_ger_1998/03_Preistraeger_1998.html |title=Berlinale: 1998 Prize Winners |accessdate=2012-01-16 |work=[[Berlinale]].de}}</ref>\n: '''Won''': [[Humanitas Prize]] for Feature Film \u2013 Matt Damon & Ben Affleck<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/1998/film/news/damon-affleck-win-humanitas-pic-prize-1117478325/|title=Damon, Affleck win Humanitas pic prize|last=Olson|first=Eric J.|date=1998-07-10|work=Variety|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Directors Guild of America|Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Motion Pictures]] \u2013 Gus Van Sant<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/1998/0126-DGA-Announces-Five-Nominees-for-Outstanding-Directorial-Achievement-in-Feature-Film.aspx|title=DGA Announces Five Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Feature Film for 1997 -|website=www.dga.org |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n: Nominated: [[Writers Guild of America, west|Writers Guild of America Award for Best Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen]] \u2013 Ben Affleck & Matt Damon<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/2015-valentine-davies-award-ben-affleck|title=Screenwriter-Director-Actor Ben Affleck to Receive WGAW's 2015 Valentine Davies Award|website=awards.wga.org|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Good Will Hunting: Music from the Miramax Motion Picture\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Various artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 2, 1997\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]], [[indie rock]], [[acoustic rock]], [[indie folk]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe musical score for ''Good Will Hunting'' was composed by [[Danny Elfman]], who had previously collaborated with [[Gus Van Sant]] on ''[[To Die For]]'' and would go on to score many of the director's other films.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.parkrecord.com/entertainment/filmmaker-gus-van-sant-and-composer-danny-elfman-talk-of-their-collaborations/|title=Filmmaker Gus Van Sant and composer Danny Elfman talk of their collaborations|access-date=2018-05-11 }}</ref> The film also features many songs written and recorded by singer-songwriter [[Elliott Smith]]. His song \"[[Miss Misery]]\" was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]], but lost to \"[[My Heart Will Go On]]\" from ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2013/01/10/elliott-smiths-music-good-hunting/|title=How Elliott Smith\u2019s Music Transformed Good Will Hunting \u2013 Boston Magazine|date=2013-01-10|work=Boston Magazine|access-date=2018-05-10 }}</ref> Elfman's score was also nominated for an [[Academy Award|Oscar]], but lost to ''Titanic'' as well. On September 11, 2006, ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'' used Elfman's song \"Weepy Donuts\" while [[Matt Lauer]] spoke during the opening credits.\n\nA soundtrack album for the film was released by [[Capitol Records]] on November 18, 1997, though only two of Elfman's cues appear on the release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Original Soundtrack|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/good-will-hunting-mw0000030450|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=All Media Network, LLC|accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2009/08/cinema-sounds-good-will-hunting-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/|title=Cinema Sounds: Good Will Hunting|date=2009-08-26|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2018-05-11 }}</ref>\n\n# [[Elliott Smith]] \u2013 \"Between the Bars\" (Orchestral)\n# [[Jeb Loy Nichols]] \u2013 \"As the Rain\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"Angeles\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"No Name #3\"\n# [[The Waterboys]] \u2013 \"[[Fisherman's Blues (song)|Fisherman's Blues]]\"\n# [[Luscious Jackson]] \u2013 \"Why Do I Lie?\"\n# [[Danny Elfman]] \u2013 \"Will Hunting\" (Main Titles)\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Between the Bars]]\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Say Yes (Elliott Smith song)|Say Yes]]\"\n# [[Gerry Rafferty]] \u2013 \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\"\n# [[Andru Donalds]] \u2013 \"Somebody's Baby\"\n# [[The Dandy Warhols]] \u2013 \"[[Boys Better]]\"\n# [[Al Green]] \u2013 \"How Can You Mend a Broken Heart?\"\n# Elliott Smith \u2013 \"[[Miss Misery (song)|Miss Misery]]\"\n# [[Danny Elfman]] \u2013 \"Weepy Donuts\"\n\n\"[[Afternoon Delight]]\" by the [[Starland Vocal Band]] was featured in the film, but did not appear on the soundtrack album.\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Good Will Hunting: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Danny Elfman, Elliott Smith\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 3, 2014\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Music Box Records\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nA limited edition soundtrack album featuring Elfman's complete score from the film was released by Music Box Records on March 3, 2014. The soundtrack, issued in 1500 copies, includes all of Elfman's cues (including music not featured on the rare Miramax Academy promo) and also contains the songs by Elliott Smith. One of the tracks is Smith's songs with Elfman's arrangements added into the mix.<ref>{{cite web|title=Good Will Hunting \u2013 Danny Elfman|url=http://www.musicbox-records.com/en/cd-catalog/60-good-will-hunting.html|work=Music Box Records|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n# Main Title (2:44)\n# Genie Mopper (0:37)\n# First Calculation (1:08)\n# Theorem (0:42)\n# Kick Ass Choir (0:59)\n# Mystery Math (2:28)\n# Them Apples (0:57)\n# Jail (1:13)\n# Second Shrink (1:14)\n# Any Port (1:25)\n# Times Up (1:14)\n# Oliver Twist (1:58)\n# Staring Contest (0:49)\n# Secret Weapon (0:57)\n# Retainer (Part A) (0:58)\n# Retainer (Part B) (0:20)\n# Tell You Something (0:48)\n# No Love Me (0:47)\n# Fire Music (1:11)\n# Whose Fault (2:34)\n# End Titles (3:50)\n# Between the Bars (Orchestral) (1:09) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith / Arr. by Elfman\n# No Name #3 (3:04) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Say Yes (2:15) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Between the Bars (2:21) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Angeles (2:55) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n# Miss Misery (3:12) \u2013 Performed by Elliott Smith\n\n==Mathematics==\nIn an early version of the script, Will Hunting was going to be a physics prodigy, but Nobel Laureate in Physics [[Sheldon Lee Glashow|Sheldon Glashow]] at Harvard told Damon the subject should be math instead of physics. Glashow referred Damon to his brother-in-law, [[Daniel Kleitman]], a mathematics professor at MIT. In the spring of 1997, Damon and Affleck asked Kleitman to \"speak math to us\" for writing realistic dialogue, so Kleitman invited postdoc [[Tom Bohman]] to join him giving them a \"quick lecture\". When asked for a problem that Will could solve, Kleitman and Bohman suggested the unsolved computer science [[P versus NP problem]], but the movie used other problems. [[Columbia University]]'s physics and math professor [[Brian Greene]] at the [[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]] [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation|Sloan]] retrospective explained that for physics, \"Having some deep insight about the universe [\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060.\u2060\u200a\u2060] typically [\u2060\u200a\u2060is\u200a\u2060] a group project in the modern era,\" while \"doing some mathematical theorem is a singular undertaking very often.\"<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/good-will-hunting-matt-damon-harvard-professor-helped-change-movie-2015-4|title=One of Matt Damon's Harvard professors gave him a small note that completely changed 'Good Will Hunting'|work=Business Insider|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref><ref name=\"mit\">{{Cite news|url=https://alum.mit.edu/slice/how-mit-professor-helped-good-will-hunting-get-math-right-and-landed-tiny-role-film|title=How an MIT Professor Helped Good Will Hunting Get the Math Right\u2014and Landed a Tiny Role in the Film|access-date=2018-05-10|last=London|first=Jay|work=MIT Alumni - Slice of MIT }}</ref>\n\nPatrick O'Donnell, professor of physics at [[University of Toronto]], served as mathematical consultant for the film production.<ref>O'Donnell relied on ''Graph Theory and Theoretical Physics'' by [[Frank Harary]] where at page 63 P.W. Kasteleyn wrote on \"Graph theory and crystal physics\".</ref>\n\nThe main hallway blackboard is used twice to reveal Will Hunting's talent, first to the audience, second to Professor Lambeau. Matt Damon based it on his artist brother Kyle visiting MIT's [[Infinite Corridor]] and writing \"an incredibly elaborate, totally fake, version of an equation\" on a blackboard which lasted for months. Kyle returned to Matt saying MIT needed these blackboards \"because these kids are so smart they just need to, you know, drop everything and solve problems!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/matt-damon-commencement-address-0603|title=Matt Damon's Commencement address|work=MIT News|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nThe first turning point in the plot occurs when Will sets aside his mop in a hallway and studies a difficult blackboard [[graph theory]] problem posed by Professor Lambeau.<ref>[[Burkard Polster]] & Marty Ross (2012) ''Math goes to the Movies'', [[Johns Hopkins University Press]], page 9, {{ISBN|1-4214-0483-4}}</ref> The question is to find the number of 3-step [[walk (graph theory)|walks]] in a given graph. Will chalks up the [[adjacency matrix]]\n:<math>A=\\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0& 1 \\\\ 1 & 0 & 2 & 1 \\\\ 0 & 2 & 0 & 0 \\\\ 1 & 1 & 0 & 0 \\end{pmatrix}.</math> To answer the question, he finds the third power matrix:\n:<math>A^3=\\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 7 & 2 & 3 \\\\ 7 & 2 & 12 & 7 \\\\ 2 & 12 & 0 & 2 \\\\ 3 & 7 & 2 & 2 \\end{pmatrix}.</math>\nThe other characters are astounded that a janitor could show such facility with [[matrix (mathematics)|matrices]] applied this way.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|1990s}}\n* [[The Man Who Knew Infinity (film)|''The Man Who Knew Infinity'']]\n* [[Ramanujan (film)|''Ramanujan'']]<!-- a different biopic about the same man -->\n* [[List of films about mathematicians]]\n* ''[[Farmers and Fishermen: Two Centuries of Work in Essex County, Massachusetts, 1630\u20131850]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119217|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{tcmdb title|324221|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{AllMovie title|160083|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{mojo title|goodwillhunting|Good Will Hunting}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|good_will_hunting|Good Will Hunting}}\n* [http://www.imsdb.com/scripts/Good-Will-Hunting.html Screenplay on IMSDb]\n* {{cite web|last=Grime|first=James|title=The Real Good Will Hunting|url=http://www.numberphile.com/videos/who_was_good_will_hunting.html|work=Numberphile|publisher=[[Brady Haran]]|access-date=2013-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419123013/http://www.numberphile.com/videos/who_was_good_will_hunting.html|archive-date=2017-04-19|url-status=dead}}\n* [http://www.boston.com/yourtown/boston/southboston/gallery/good_will_hunting_15_years_later/ Then & Now: Revisiting ''Good Will Hunting''] \u2013 Boston.com\n\n{{Gus Van Sant}}\n{{Ben Affleck}}\n{{Matt Damon}}\n\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1997 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Elliott Smith]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Danny Elfman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Gus Van Sant]]\n[[Category:Films about academia]]\n[[Category:Films about educators]]\n[[Category:Films about mathematics]]\n[[Category:Films about orphans]]\n[[Category:Films about psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Films about child abuse]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Supporting Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1997]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Harvard University]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Harvard Square]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Ben Affleck]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matt Damon]]\n[[Category:Works about janitors]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of mathematicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lizzy150", "label": "safe", "comment": "re-add image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_Will_Hunting"}
{"title_page": "Laminaria nigripes", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| genus = Laminaria\n| species = nigripes\n| authority = J.Agardh, 1868\n}}\n[[File:Laminaria digitata free.JPG|thumb|''Laminaria nigripes'' is commonly confused with ''Laminaria digitata'', pictured above, in the Northwest Atlantic.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Laminaria hyperborea - K\u00f6hler\u2013s Medizinal-Pflanzen-214.jpg|thumb|Laminaria nigripes is commonly confused with Laminaria hyperborea, pictured above, in Europe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref>]]\n'''''Laminaria nigripes''''' is a species of [[kelp]] found in the North Atlantic and North Pacific<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Wilce|first=Robert T.|date=1990|editor-last=Garbary|editor-first=David J.|editor2-last=South|editor2-first=G. Robin|title=Role of the Arctic Ocean as a Bridge between the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans: Fact and Hypothesis|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-75115-8_16|journal=Evolutionary Biogeography of the Marine Algae of the North Atlantic|series=NATO ASI Series|language=en|location=Berlin, Heidelberg|publisher=Springer|pages=323\u2013347|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-75115-8_16|isbn=978-3-642-75115-8}}</ref> within Arctic and subarctic waters<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Filbee-Dexter|first=Karen|last2=Wernberg|first2=Thomas|last3=Fredriksen|first3=Stein|last4=Norderhaug|first4=Kjell Magnus|last5=Pedersen|first5=Morten Foldager|date=2019-01-01|title=Arctic kelp forests: Diversity, resilience and future|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0921818118301826|journal=Global and Planetary Change|language=en|volume=172|pages=1\u201314|doi=10.1016/j.gloplacha.2018.09.005|issn=0921-8181}}</ref> including Vancouver Island, Haida Gawaii, Greenland, Iceland, Norway<ref name=\":4\" />, Downeast Maine<ref name=\":5\" />, and the Bay of Fundy.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' may be found exclusively in the Arctic, but frequent misidentification of samples has lead to speculation and debate over the actual range.<ref name=\":3\" /> There has been some claim that ''Laminaria nigripes'' is subarctic but not Arctic<ref name=\":0\" /> while other research has indicated that the species is found in Arctic waters.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is commonly confused with [[Laminaria digitata|''Laminaria digitata'']] and [[Laminaria hyperborea|''Laminaria hyperborea'']]<ref name=\":4\" /> and is at risk from climate change.<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\n== Phylogony ==\n''Laminaria nigripes'' is a species within the genus Laminaria. The genus [[Laminaria]] is in the family [[Laminariaceae]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=Christopher E.|last2=Mayes|first2=Charlene|last3=Druehl|first3=Louis D.|last4=Saunders|first4=Gary W.|date=2006|title=A Multi-Gene Molecular Investigation of the Kelp (laminariales, Phaeophyceae) Supports Substantial Taxonomic Re-Organization1|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1529-8817.2006.00204.x|journal=Journal of Phycology|language=en|volume=42|issue=2|pages=493\u2013512|doi=10.1111/j.1529-8817.2006.00204.x|issn=1529-8817}}</ref> which is one of eight families in the order of [[Kelp|Laminariales.]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref> The class of Phaeophyceae includes the order of Laminariales.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mathieson|first=Arthur C.|date=2019-01-18|title=A Comparison of Marine and Estuarine Algal Populations from Downeast Maine and Eight Contiguous Northwest Atlantic Areas|url=https://www.rhodorajournal.org/doi/abs/10.3119/17-21|journal=Rhodora|language=en|volume=120|issue=984|pages=310|doi=10.3119/17-21|issn=0035-4902}}</ref> [[Brown algae|Phaeophyceae]] are brown algae commonly referred to as kelp.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' was first described in 1868 under the name [[Saccharina nigripes|''Saccharina nigripes'']] by Jacob Agardh in Spitsbergen, Norway.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=CM|last2=Saunders|first2=GW|date=2016-02-03|title=The relative contribution of Saccharina nigripes (Phaeophyceae) to the Bay of Fundy Laminariaceae: spatial and temporal variability|url=https://www.int-res.com/abstracts/meps/v543/p153-162/|journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series|language=en|volume=543|pages=153\u2013162|doi=10.3354/meps11566|issn=0171-8630}}</ref>\n\n=== Saccharina ===\nRecent molecular genetic insight has lead some researchers to suggest that the genetic species known as ''Laminaria nigripes'' ought to be a part of the genus [[Saccharina]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Specifically, the genus Saccharina Stackhouse from 1809 is proposed for revival. The revived Saccharina Stackhouse would include the genera Hedophyllum and Kjellmaniella, the species ''Cymathaere japonica'', and certain species from Laminaria.<ref name=\":1\" />  With the re-establishment of Saccharina Stackhouse, ''Laminaria nigripes'' would be renamed ''Saccharina nigripes''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Hedophyllum ===\nAdditional phylogenetic and molecular genetic research has added the possibility that the genus Saccharina is actually a clade containing the genera Anthrothamnus, Hedophyllum, Kjellmaniella, and Saccharina.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Starko|first=Samuel|last2=Soto Gomez|first2=Marybel|last3=Darby|first3=Hayley|last4=Demes|first4=Kyle W.|last5=Kawai|first5=Hiroshi|last6=Yotsukura|first6=Norishige|last7=Lindstrom|first7=Sandra C.|last8=Keeling|first8=Patrick J.|last9=Graham|first9=Sean W.|last10=Martone|first10=Patrick T.|date=2019-07-01|title=A comprehensive kelp phylogeny sheds light on the evolution of an ecosystem|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790319300892|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=136|pages=138\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2019.04.012|issn=1055-7903}}</ref>Under this phylogenetic model, ''Laminaria nigripes'' would fall under the reinstated genus [[Hedophyllum]] 1901 Setchell as ''[[Hedophyllum nigripes]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Part of the reasoning behind the proposed switch is bringing ''Laminaria nigripes'' and its closest known relative, ''[[Saccharina subsessilis]]'', together on the phylogenetic tree.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''Saccharina subessilis'' would become ''[[Hedophyllum subsessilis]]'' and be the lectotype species for ''Laminaria nigripes''.<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition to ''H. nigripes'' and ''H. subsessilis,'' the genus Hedophyllum would contain the species ''[[Hedophyllum bongardiana|H. bongardiana]]'', ''[[Hedophyllum dentigera|H. dentigera]]'', ''[[Hedophyllum druehlii|H. druehlii]]'', and ''[[Hedophyllum sessilis|H. sessilis]]''. <ref name=\":2\" /> The species within the Hedophyllum genus have flexible stipes and lack tissue cavitation, true branching, and split branching.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Misidentification ===\nBecause the digitate blade of ''Laminaria nigripes'' is similar to the blade of ''Laminaria digitata''<ref name=\":6\" />, ''Laminaria nigripes'' samples are commonly misidentified as ''Laminaria digitata'' in the Maritime Provinces of Canada<ref name=\":4\" /> and the Northwest Atlantic which has contributed to fewer reportings of ''Laminaria nigripes'' in that region.<ref name=\":6\" /> Additionally, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is often confused with ''Laminaria hyperborea'' in Europe.<ref name=\":4\" /> In addition to the similar blade morphology, the difficulty of correctly identifying a sample via mucilage ducts has added further confusion.<ref name=\":4\" /> Because there is confusion around the identification of ''Laminaria nigripes'' and similar species,<ref name=\":1\" /> the genetic species of ''Laminaria nigripes'' has been referred to by multiple names<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=172696&sk=0&from=results|title=Hedophyllum nigripes (J.Agardh) Starko, S.C.Lindstrom & Martone 2019 :: Algaebase|website=www.algaebase.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> including ''Saccharina nigripes,<ref name=\":4\" /> Hedophyllum nigripes,<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Saccharina groelandica]],''<ref name=\":6\" /> and ''[[Laminaria bongardiana|Laminaria bongardiana.]]''<ref name=\":6\" />\n== Morphology ==\n=== Blades ===\n''Laminaria nigripes'' has two main phenotypes, one with a simple blade and one with a digitate blade.<ref name=\":6\" /> Both of these phenotypes are the same genetic species.<ref name=\":6\" /> The digitate bladed phenotypes is more common<ref name=\":6\" /> and can appear morphologically similar to Laminaria digitata while the simple bladed phenotype, which is much rarer, appears morphologically similar to Saccharina latissima.<ref name=\":6\" /> The presence of these phenotypes varies between the Northeast Pacific and Northwest Atlantic with a higher prevalence of the simple bladed phenotype in the Pacific than in the Atlantic.<ref name=\":4\" /> Because of the presence of multiple phenotypes, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is known to have phenotypic plasticity.<ref name=\":6\" /> When young, Laminaria nigripes has a stipe and bullated blades.<ref name=\":2\" /> As an individual matures, the stipe can be lost but may remain, and the blades often become smooth and cordate with lacerations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Because the blades of Laminaria nigripes are prone to being torn by environmental factors, the blades can be split into multiple segments, but the blades do not experience split branching or trues branching.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Mucilage ducts ===\nThe presence of mucilage ducts varies between kelp species and has been used in the identification process, but pseudo mucilage ducts can be formed from infections and obscure the identification process.<ref name=\":4\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' can have mucilage ducts on the stipe or blades, and the presence of mucilage ducts in the cortex of the stipe for a cross section of a sample can be used to identify ''Laminaria nigripes'' individuals under a microscope.<ref name=\":4\" /> However, the mucilage ducts of ''Laminaria nigripes'' can become infected and appear as pseudo mucilage ducts, and mucilage ducts are less likely to be present in individuals from more northern, colder waters.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Range ==\nLaminaria nigripes is distributed in the North Atlantic and North Pacific,<ref name=\":0\" /> within Arctic, subarctic,<ref name=\":3\" /> and cold temperate<ref name=\":4\" /> waters. The range of ''Laminaria nigripes'' varies latitudinally between the Pacifica and Atlantic with records of the species in the waters around the southern end of British Columbia and a more northern distribution in the Atlantic.<ref name=\":4\" /> In the Northwest Atlantic, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is absent in Atlantic Nova Scotia, the Northumberland Strait of New Brunswick, Southern Maine, Massachusetts, and Rhode Island.<ref name=\":4\" /> Additionally, some researches have claimed that ''Laminaria nigripes'' has distribution in subarctic but not Arctic waters.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is recorded in Europe<ref name=\":0\" /> in addition to the Northwest Atlantic. There is some evidence that ''Laminaria nigripes'' plays an important ecological role in the Bay of Fundy, but researchers caution that more research needs to be done before the distribution of ''Laminaria nigripes'' in Atlantic Canada is clear.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is also found off of Greenland along with ''[[Saccharina latissima]]'', ''[[Laminaria solidungula]]'', ''[[Alaria esculenta]]'', ''[[Agarum clathratum]]'', ''[[Saccharina dermatodea]]'', and ''[[Saccharina logicruris]]''.<ref name=\":3\" /> In the Kara Sea, Laminaria nigripes is observed with ''Saccharina latissima'', ''[[Laminaria solidungula]]'', ''[[Alaria elliptica]]'', and ''[[Alaria oblonga]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Evolution ===\nThe North Pacific has more endemic species of kelp than the North Atlantic<ref name=\":0\" /> and is believed to be where kelps as a whole began.<ref name=\":5\" /> The Saccharina clade likely began in the Northwest Pacific before moving into the Northeast Pacific and later into the Atlantic via passage through the Arctic.<ref name=\":5\" /> During the [[Cretaceous]] through [[Pleistocene]] eras, tectonic plate movements and glacial periods continually changed the seaways into and out of the Arctic.<ref name=\":0\" /> This resulted in a succession of different biotic exchanges between the Arctic and other ocean basins which resulted in the spreading of species across ocean basins and the creation of new species.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Habitat ==\nWithin its range, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is most often found in areas of rocky, intertidal zone with moderate to high wave action.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' has to cope with and adjust to sea ice cover, low temperatures, and unique light conditions.<ref name=\":3\" /> Abrasion, low light, low salinity, and low temperatures are common in areas like these which can have ice cover for part or all of the year.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ice cover is not static and creates abrasions in kelps as it moves.<ref name=\":3\" /> Ice cover also limits the light available for organisms beneath it by reflecting light, and the low availability of light affects photosynthetic activity.<ref name=\":3\" /> With the ice cover and high latitude of these areas, there is a wide range in the amount of light available at certain times for photosynthetic organisms, and there is a rapid increase of light available as the ice cover breaks up.<ref name=\":3\" /> This results in a limited season for ''Laminaria nigripes'' to grow.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' may utilize the cold water of these areas to reproduce by spreading spores and to support early development.<ref name=\":6\" /> Because ''Laminaria nigripes'' prefers areas with moderate to high wave action, it shares that space with ''Laminaria digitata'' in the Bay of Fundy.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==[[Global warming|Climate change]]==\nThe mean summer [[Ocean warming|water temperatures]] in the Arctic are predicted to increase over the next century and have already increased in the past few decades.<ref name=\":3\" /> The rising temperatures will not affect all locations equally and could result in an increase or decrease of kelp production, shifts in competitive interactions, ecosystem changes, and an [[Introduced species|invasion of kelp]] from more southern lattitudes.<ref name=\":3\" /> The introduction of new kelp species has already begun in the regions where ''Laminaria nigripes'' lives.<ref name=\":5\" /> Additionally, the Arctic is rapidly losing [[Sea ice|sea ice cover]] which could aid in the invasion of more southern kelp species, narrow the vertical distribution of kelp, and make new spaces in the Arctic hospitable for kelp.<ref name=\":3\" /> As the ice cover melts, it dumps freshwater into the sea which lowers the salinity of the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Permafrost]] will also melt as ice melts, and the combination of the two will lead to land erosion and increased sediment in the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> As sediment in the water increases, sediment on the bottom of the ocean will increase, limiting the places where kelp can attach, and light and photosynthetic activity will be reduced by the suspension of sediment.<ref name=\":3\" /> As the ice cover melts, more UV radiation could enter the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> Nutrients in the water are predicted to increase which are likely to lead to an increase in the [[Algal bloom|phytoplankton blooms]] that block the light from reaching kelps, but it is unclear if any or all species of kelp would be directly affected by the nurtients.<ref name=\":3\" />  The effects of this would be more minor than other issues but could make photosynthesis difficult.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===''Laminaria nigripes'' example ===\nAt a study site, the presence of ''Laminaria nigripes'' decreased at the same time as sea surface temperatures in the area increased, and the decrease could not be attributed to heavy storms, increased competition, or salinity changes.<ref name=\":6\" /> When the sea surface temperatures returned to a more typical level, ''Laminaria nigripes'' did not recover.<ref name=\":6\" /> Kelps in general are affect by increased water temperatures because it disrupts their reproduction and development which may be why ''Laminaria nigripes'' decreased during a period of increase in sea surface temperatures.<ref name=\":6\" /> During certain life stages, ''Laminaria nigripes'' has an upper tolerance limit for temperature similar to that of Arctic species of kelp, and ''Laminaria nigripes'' could struggle if it is temperature sensitive and if temperatures contain to rise .<ref name=\":6\" />   \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| genus = Laminaria\n| species = nigripes\n| authority = J.Agardh, 1868\n}}\n[[File:Laminaria digitata free.JPG|thumb|''Laminaria nigripes'' is commonly confused with ''Laminaria digitata'', pictured above, in the Northwest Atlantic.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Laminaria hyperborea - K\u00f6hler\u2013s Medizinal-Pflanzen-214.jpg|thumb|Laminaria nigripes is commonly confused with Laminaria hyperborea, pictured above, in Europe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref>]]\n'''''Laminaria nigripes''''' is a species of [[kelp]] found in the North Atlantic and North Pacific<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Wilce|first=Robert T.|date=1990|editor-last=Garbary|editor-first=David J.|editor2-last=South|editor2-first=G. Robin|title=Role of the Arctic Ocean as a Bridge between the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans: Fact and Hypothesis|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-75115-8_16|journal=Evolutionary Biogeography of the Marine Algae of the North Atlantic|series=NATO ASI Series|language=en|location=Berlin, Heidelberg|publisher=Springer|pages=323\u2013347|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-75115-8_16|isbn=978-3-642-75115-8}}</ref> within Arctic and subarctic waters<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Filbee-Dexter|first=Karen|last2=Wernberg|first2=Thomas|last3=Fredriksen|first3=Stein|last4=Norderhaug|first4=Kjell Magnus|last5=Pedersen|first5=Morten Foldager|date=2019-01-01|title=Arctic kelp forests: Diversity, resilience and future|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0921818118301826|journal=Global and Planetary Change|language=en|volume=172|pages=1\u201314|doi=10.1016/j.gloplacha.2018.09.005|issn=0921-8181}}</ref> including Vancouver Island, Haida Gawaii, Greenland, Iceland, Norway<ref name=\":4\" />, Downeast Maine<ref name=\":5\" />, and the Bay of Fundy.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' may be found exclusively in the Arctic, but frequent misidentification of samples has lead to speculation and debate over the actual range.<ref name=\":3\" /> There has been some claim that ''Laminaria nigripes'' is subarctic but not Arctic<ref name=\":0\" /> while other research has indicated that the species is found in Arctic waters.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is commonly confused with [[Laminaria digitata|''Laminaria digitata'']] and [[Laminaria hyperborea|''Laminaria hyperborea'']]<ref name=\":4\" /> and is at risk from climate change.<ref name=\":3\" />  \n\n== Phylogony ==\n''Laminaria nigripes'' is a species within the the genus Laminaria. The genus [[Laminaria]] is in the family [[Laminariaceae]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=Christopher E.|last2=Mayes|first2=Charlene|last3=Druehl|first3=Louis D.|last4=Saunders|first4=Gary W.|date=2006|title=A Multi-Gene Molecular Investigation of the Kelp (laminariales, Phaeophyceae) Supports Substantial Taxonomic Re-Organization1|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1529-8817.2006.00204.x|journal=Journal of Phycology|language=en|volume=42|issue=2|pages=493\u2013512|doi=10.1111/j.1529-8817.2006.00204.x|issn=1529-8817}}</ref> which is one of eight families in the order of [[Kelp|Laminariales.]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=Caroline M.|last2=Saunders|first2=Gary W.|date=2015-09-01|title=On the utility of mucilage ducts as a taxonomic character in Laminaria and Saccharina (Phaeophyceae) \u2013 the conundrum of S. groenlandica|url=https://doi.org/10.2216/15-19.1|journal=Phycologia|volume=54|issue=5|pages=440\u2013450|doi=10.2216/15-19.1|issn=0031-8884}}</ref> The class of Phaeophyceae includes the order of Laminariales.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mathieson|first=Arthur C.|date=2019-01-18|title=A Comparison of Marine and Estuarine Algal Populations from Downeast Maine and Eight Contiguous Northwest Atlantic Areas|url=https://www.rhodorajournal.org/doi/abs/10.3119/17-21|journal=Rhodora|language=en|volume=120|issue=984|pages=310|doi=10.3119/17-21|issn=0035-4902}}</ref> [[Brown algae|Phaeophyceae]] are brown algae commonly referred to as kelp.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' was first described in 1868 under the name [[Saccharina nigripes|''Saccharina nigripes'']] by Jacob Agardh in Spitsbergen, Norway.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Longtin|first=CM|last2=Saunders|first2=GW|date=2016-02-03|title=The relative contribution of Saccharina nigripes (Phaeophyceae) to the Bay of Fundy Laminariaceae: spatial and temporal variability|url=https://www.int-res.com/abstracts/meps/v543/p153-162/|journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series|language=en|volume=543|pages=153\u2013162|doi=10.3354/meps11566|issn=0171-8630}}</ref>\n\n=== Saccharina ===\nRecent molecular genetic insight has lead some researchers to suggest that the genetic species known as ''Laminaria nigripes'' ought to be a part of the genus [[Saccharina]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Specifically, the genus Saccharina Stackhouse from 1809 is proposed for revival. The revived Saccharina Stackhouse would include the genera Hedophyllum and Kjellmaniella, the species ''Cymathaere japonica'', and certain species from Laminaria.<ref name=\":1\" />  With the re-establishment of Saccharina Stackhouse, ''Laminaria nigripes'' would be renamed ''Saccharina nigripes''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Hedophyllum ===\nAdditional phylogenetic and molecular genetic research has added the possibility that the genus Saccharina is actually a clade containing the genera Anthrothamnus, Hedophyllum, Kjellmaniella, and Saccharina.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Starko|first=Samuel|last2=Soto Gomez|first2=Marybel|last3=Darby|first3=Hayley|last4=Demes|first4=Kyle W.|last5=Kawai|first5=Hiroshi|last6=Yotsukura|first6=Norishige|last7=Lindstrom|first7=Sandra C.|last8=Keeling|first8=Patrick J.|last9=Graham|first9=Sean W.|last10=Martone|first10=Patrick T.|date=2019-07-01|title=A comprehensive kelp phylogeny sheds light on the evolution of an ecosystem|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790319300892|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=136|pages=138\u2013150|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2019.04.012|issn=1055-7903}}</ref>Under this phylogenetic model, ''Laminaria nigripes'' would fall under the reinstated genus [[Hedophyllum]] 1901 Setchell as ''[[Hedophyllum nigripes]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Part of the reasoning behind the proposed switch is bringing ''Laminaria nigripes'' and its closest known relative, ''[[Saccharina subsessilis]]'', together on the phylogenetic tree.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''Saccharina subessilis'' would become ''[[Hedophyllum subsessilis]]'' and be the lectotype species for ''Laminaria nigripes''.<ref name=\":2\" /> In addition to ''H. nigripes'' and ''H. subsessilis,'' the genus Hedophyllum would contain the species ''[[Hedophyllum bongardiana|H. bongardiana]]'', ''[[Hedophyllum dentigera|H. dentigera]]'', ''[[Hedophyllum druehlii|H. druehlii]]'', and ''[[Hedophyllum sessilis|H. sessilis]]''. <ref name=\":2\" /> The species within the Hedophyllum genus have flexible stipes and lack tissue cavitation, true branching, and split branching.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Misidentification ===\nBecause the digitate blade of ''Laminaria nigripes'' is similar to the blade of ''Laminaria digitata''<ref name=\":6\" />, ''Laminaria nigripes'' samples are commonly misidentified as ''Laminaria digitata'' in the Maritime Provinces of Canada<ref name=\":4\" /> and the Northwest Atlantic which has contributed to fewer reportings of ''Laminaria nigripes'' in that region.<ref name=\":6\" /> Additionally, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is often confused with ''Laminaria hyperborea'' in Europe.<ref name=\":4\" /> In addition to the similar blade morphology, the difficulty of correctly identifying a sample via mucilage ducts has added further confusion.<ref name=\":4\" /> Because there is confusion around the identification of ''Laminaria nigripes'' and similar species,<ref name=\":1\" /> the genetic species of ''Laminaria nigripes'' has been referred to by multiple names<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.algaebase.org/search/species/detail/?species_id=172696&sk=0&from=results|title=Hedophyllum nigripes (J.Agardh) Starko, S.C.Lindstrom & Martone 2019 :: Algaebase|website=www.algaebase.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> including ''Saccharina nigripes,<ref name=\":4\" /> Hedophyllum nigripes,<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Saccharina groelandica]],''<ref name=\":6\" /> and ''[[Laminaria bongardiana|Laminaria bongardiana.]]''<ref name=\":6\" />\n== Morphology ==\n=== Blades ===\n''Laminaria nigripes'' has two main phenotypes, one with a simple blade and one with a digitate blade.<ref name=\":6\" /> Both of these phenotypes are the same genetic species.<ref name=\":6\" /> The digitate bladed phenotypes is more common<ref name=\":6\" /> and can appear morphologically similar to Laminaria digitata while the simple bladed phenotype, which is much rarer, appears morphologically similar to Saccharina latissima.<ref name=\":6\" /> The presence of these phenotypes varies between the Northeast Pacific and Northwest Atlantic with a higher prevalence of the simple bladed phenotype in the Pacific than in the Atlantic.<ref name=\":4\" /> Because of the presence of multiple phenotypes, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is known to have phenotypic plasticity.<ref name=\":6\" /> When young, Laminaria nigripes has a stipe and bullated blades.<ref name=\":2\" /> As an individual matures, the stipe can be lost but may remain, and the blades often become smooth and cordate with lacerations.<ref name=\":2\" /> Because the blades of Laminaria nigripes are prone to being torn by environmental factors, the blades can be split into multiple segments, but the blades do not experience split branching or trues branching.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Mucilage ducts ===\nThe presence of mucilage ducts varies between kelp species and has been used in the identification process, but pseudo mucilage ducts can be formed from infections and obscure the identification process.<ref name=\":4\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' can have mucilage ducts on the stipe or blades, and the presence of mucilage ducts in the cortex of the stipe for a cross section of a sample can be used to identify ''Laminaria nigripes'' individuals under a microscope.<ref name=\":4\" /> However, the mucilage ducts of ''Laminaria nigripes'' can become infected and appear as pseudo mucilage ducts, and mucilage ducts are less likely to be present in individuals from more northern, colder waters.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Range ==\nLaminaria nigripes is distributed in the North Atlantic and North Pacific,<ref name=\":0\" /> within Arctic, subarctic,<ref name=\":3\" /> and cold temperate<ref name=\":4\" /> waters. The range of ''Laminaria nigripes'' varies latitudinally between the Pacifica and Atlantic with records of the species in the waters around the southern end of British Columbia and a more northern distribution in the Atlantic.<ref name=\":4\" /> In the Northwest Atlantic, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is absent in Atlantic Nova Scotia, the Northumberland Strait of New Brunswick, Southern Maine, Massachusetts, and Rhode Island.<ref name=\":4\" /> Additionally, some researches have claimed that ''Laminaria nigripes'' has distribution in subarctic but not Arctic waters.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is recorded in Europe<ref name=\":0\" /> in addition to the Northwest Atlantic. There is some evidence that ''Laminaria nigripes'' plays an important ecological role in the Bay of Fundy, but researchers caution that more research needs to be done before the distribution of ''Laminaria nigripes'' in Atlantic Canada is clear.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' is also found off of Greenland along with ''[[Saccharina latissima]]'', ''[[Laminaria solidungula]]'', ''[[Alaria esculenta]]'', ''[[Agarum clathratum]]'', ''[[Saccharina dermatodea]]'', and ''[[Saccharina logicruris]]''.<ref name=\":3\" /> In the Kara Sea, Laminaria nigripes is observed with ''Saccharina latissima'', ''[[Laminaria solidungula]]'', ''[[Alaria elliptica]]'', and ''[[Alaria oblonga]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Evolution ===\nThe North Pacific has more endemic species of kelp than the North Atlantic<ref name=\":0\" /> and is believed to be where kelps as a whole began.<ref name=\":5\" /> The Saccharina clade likely began in the Northwest Pacific before moving into the Northeast Pacific and later into the Atlantic via passage through the Arctic.<ref name=\":5\" /> During the [[Cretaceous]] through [[Pleistocene]] eras, tectonic plate movements and glacial periods continually changed the seaways into and out of the Arctic.<ref name=\":0\" /> This resulted in a succession of different biotic exchanges between the Arctic and other ocean basins which resulted in the spreading of species across ocean basins and the creation of new species.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Habitat ==\nWithin its range, ''Laminaria nigripes'' is most often found in areas of rocky, intertidal zone with moderate to high wave action.<ref name=\":6\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' has to cope with and adjust to sea ice cover, low temperatures, and unique light conditions.<ref name=\":3\" /> Abrasion, low light, low salinity, and low temperatures are common in areas like these which can have ice cover for part or all of the year.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ice cover is not static and creates abrasions in kelps as it moves.<ref name=\":3\" /> Ice cover also limits the light available for organisms beneath it by reflecting light, and the low availability of light affects photosynthetic activity.<ref name=\":3\" /> With the ice cover and high latitude of these areas, there is a wide range in the amount of light available at certain times for photosynthetic organisms, and there is a rapid increase of light available as the ice cover breaks up.<ref name=\":3\" /> This results in a limited season for ''Laminaria nigripes'' to grow.<ref name=\":3\" /> ''Laminaria nigripes'' may utilize the cold water of these areas to reproduce by spreading spores and to support early development.<ref name=\":6\" /> Because ''Laminaria nigripes'' prefers areas with moderate to high wave action, it shares that space with ''Laminaria digitata'' in the Bay of Fundy.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==[[Global warming|Climate change]]==\nThe mean summer [[Ocean warming|water temperatures]] in the Arctic are predicted to increase over the next century and have already increased in the past few decades.<ref name=\":3\" /> The rising temperatures will not affect all locations equally and could result in an increase or decrease of kelp production, shifts in competitive interactions, ecosystem changes, and an [[Introduced species|invasion of kelp]] from more southern lattitudes.<ref name=\":3\" /> The introduction of new kelp species has already begun in the regions where ''Laminaria nigripes'' lives.<ref name=\":5\" /> Additionally, the Arctic is rapidly losing [[Sea ice|sea ice cover]] which could aid in the invasion of more southern kelp species, narrow the vertical distribution of kelp, and make new spaces in the Arctic hospitable for kelp.<ref name=\":3\" /> As the ice cover melts, it dumps freshwater into the sea which lowers the salinity of the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Permafrost]] will also melt as ice melts, and the combination of the two will lead to land erosion and increased sediment in the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> As sediment in the water increases, sediment on the bottom of the ocean will increase, limiting the places where kelp can attach, and light and photosynthetic activity will be reduced by the suspension of sediment.<ref name=\":3\" /> As the ice cover melts, more UV radiation could enter the water.<ref name=\":3\" /> Nutrients in the water are predicted to increase which are likely to lead to an increase in the [[Algal bloom|phytoplankton blooms]] that block the light from reaching kelps, but it is unclear if any or all species of kelp would be directly affected by the nurtients.<ref name=\":3\" />  The effects of this would be more minor than other issues but could make photosynthesis difficult.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===''Laminaria nigripes'' example ===\nAt a study site, the presence of ''Laminaria nigripes'' decreased at the same time as sea surface temperatures in the area increased, and the decrease could not be attributed to heavy storms, increased competition, or salinity changes.<ref name=\":6\" /> When the sea surface temperatures returned to a more typical level, ''Laminaria nigripes'' did not recover.<ref name=\":6\" /> Kelps in general are affect by increased water temperatures because it disrupts their reproduction and development which may be why ''Laminaria nigripes'' decreased during a period of increase in sea surface temperatures.<ref name=\":6\" /> During certain life stages, ''Laminaria nigripes'' has an upper tolerance limit for temperature similar to that of Arctic species of kelp, and ''Laminaria nigripes'' could struggle if it is temperature sensitive and if temperatures contain to rise .<ref name=\":6\" />   \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laminaria_nigripes"}
